<FIRST>r a AM-People-MissWestVirginia     12-13 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Miss West Virginia,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magistrate Drops Weapons Charge Against Miss West Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. _ A magistrate on Wednesday dropped a weapons
charge against Miss West Virginia Lisa Bittinger, citing a lack of
evidence.
   Marion County Magistrate C. Frank Jones said the 21-year-old
beauty queen had a right to defend herself with a small-caliber
handgun during her late night tussle with Tammy Boyce, 23.
   ``Now had she taken the gun out and held it on this woman or
initiated the problem, that's different,'' Jones said. ``But if
someone has you by the hair, and you just momentarily bring it into
view to scare them off, that's not brandishing.''
   Boyce had alleged that Bittinger pulled a gun on her during a
Nov. 7 scuffle on a city street after a traffic accident.
   Bittinger, in turn, filed a complaint accusing Boyce of reckless
driving, battery and destruction of property.
   Jones found Boyce guilty of all three counts and sentenced her
to two terms of 120 days in the Marion County Jail, respectively,
on the battery and property charges and 90 days on the driving
offense. The sentences are to run concurrently.
   Boyce was freed on a $2,000 property bond that will allow her to
remain free until Dec. 27.
   ``I wanted togive her time to enjoy her holiday,'' Jones said.
``This whole thing was really just a cat fight.''
   Bittinger said she wants to put the incident behind her.
   ``This wasn't the first threat I've had from her and it's not
the first threat I've had from other people,'' she said. ``I am
afraid, but life happens you just have to deal with it.''
   Bittinger, whose reign ends in June, said she plans to continue
carrying a handgun for protection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
