<DOCNO> AP891213-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Czech-Economy Bjt   12-13 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-Economy, Bjt,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Freedom Doesn't Buy Czechs and Slovaks Western Goods</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Huge crowds opposing a Communist
government chanted, ``Demisi,'' meaning, resign. But some shifted
the chant slightly to ``Devizy.'' That means foreign exchange.
   To Czechoslovaks, freedom to travel is an empty privilege
without currency to spend abroad. Beyond their borders their
banknotes in crowns are hardly worth anything.
   Once a year, Czechoslovaks are allowed to line up for days to
buy a maximum of $23 at twice the official rate. Or they can buy
any amount on the black market at nearly five times the rate.
   That is one crushing problem Czechoslovakia faces in trying to
retool a centrally planned socialist bloc economy into a prosperous
system open to the world. There are a lot more.
   ``Basically, everything that was wrong before is still wrong,''
observed a Western economic analyst who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``And things are getting worse.''
   Dusan Triska, a senior economist in Czechoslovakia's Academy of
Sciences, agreed, adding a litany of crises that reformers will
have to address.
   Western banks are lined up to lend money, and investors are
milling in the wings. In Eastern Europe, however, any economic
solution hinges on social and political priorities.
   ``Above all,'' Triska said, ``we have to avoid mistakes made by
Poland and Hungary. Before we open to the exterior, we have to open
up inside. We can't use foreign resources until we can use our
own.''
   Until the war, Czechoslovakia had Europe's sixth strongest
economy, with heavy industry and some of the world's most advanced
technology.
   During 40 years of Communism, plants were operated with little
investment and shoddy maintenance. The once-strong infrastructure
now needs billions of dollars worth of capital.
   The system operates at a loss, with no relation between costs
and prices. Milk sells for half what it costs to produce. Bread is
so cheap farmers use it for fodder.
   Since the 1968 Soviet-led invasion, Communist leaders have tried
to offer 15 million Czechoslovaks the softest life in Eastern
Europe in exchange for political submissiveness.
   There is a car for every 4.9 people. An average worker can buy
one with 15 months' pay. Most Eastern Europeans wait years for
delivery.
   Everyone has a job, and goldbricking is seldom grounds for
dismissal. Workers are encouraged to spend weekends at vacation
homes.
   Shops offer Italian kiwis and French cheeses. If veal is scarce,
the lamb is excellent. Vacations are cheap for travelers who like
Bulgaria.
   The system is rich ground for larceny, from petty to grand.
Waiters sell caviar from the refrigerator. Doctors take tips for
preferred service. Factory managers wheel and deal.
   Pressure was contained when lives were lived behind an Iron
Curtain. Now that people want to travel and buy Western goods, the
closed economy generates growing frustration.
   The hard part is that it must get worse before it gets better.
Any new government will need a firm mandate.
   ``Someone will have to tell Czechoslovaks they have to work
harder and earn less,'' Triska said. ``The Communist Party can't do
that.''
   Most likely, a Western diplomat noted, a coalition government
will emerge. ``Coalitions are not famous for taking tough
measures,'' he said.
   Economists agree that reform means massive layoffs and reduced
control will send prices soaring. Subsidies have to be eliminated.
And incompetent managers must be replaced.
   ``We will have to abolish many inefficient factories and
gradually open to the international market,'' said economist
Miroslav Slouf, a deputy mayor of Prague. ``Any new elected
government will be unpopular within months.''
   Speaking privately, Czechoslovak specialists wonder if any
political leaders will be able to break up the forbidding mass of
state monopolies for industries and services.
   One reformer, who asked not to be named, put it: ``These mafias
of managers are too organized, too well protected. They don't want
change. There are so many ways to resist.''
   The economy was shaped within the Soviet bloc when central
planners prepared to parallel _ and outdo _ the West. The systems,
though outmoded and largely discredited, remain intact.
   Czechoslovakia's largest employer is an uncompetitive steel
industry. It makes its own version of three-quarters of the world's
range of engineering items.
   Unlike Poland and Hungary, Czechoslovakia borrowed little and
kept up reserves. As other economies failed, it supplied their
staples. With a touch of national pride, leaders subjected
Socialist brothers to customs barriers.
   Czechoslovak economists agree they must avoid borrowing until
loans can be put to use expanding earnings. Meantime, the economy
needs ``devizy,'' hard currency.
   Tourism is a potential source. Prague is among Europe's most
beautiful cities. The countryside, in forests and mountains, is
often dramatic. Other service industries are virgin ground for
joint ventures.
   ``A lot is possible,'' Slouf said. ``But you only have to look
at the experience of our neighbors. It will not be simple.''
</TEXT>
