<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--LePen     12-13 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Le Pen,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extreme Rightist Politician Faces Criminal Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right-wing extremist Jean-Marie Le Pen could face
criminal prosecution for remarks linking a French Cabinet
minister's name to Nazi death camps.
   Court action is possible because the European Parliament, by a
vote of 178-91 on Monday, lifted his immunity.
   The French Justice Ministry had asked the Parliament to remove
the immunity of the leader of the National Front so he could be
taken to court on charges of slandering a government minister.
   Le Pen, at a rally on Sept. 2, 1988, spoke of Public Service
Minister Michel Durafour as ``Durafour-crematoire.'' Crematoire can
be used to refer to the crematories where the Nazis burned the
bodies of their death-camp victims.
   As a member of the European Parliament, based in Strasbourg,
France, Le Pen has immunity from prosecution unless the legislature
votes to remove it.
   Conviction of slandering a Cabinet minister is punishable by a
jail sentence of up to three months and a maximum fine of $13,000.
</TEXT>
