<FIRST>r a PM-PhonyBackground     12-13 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phony Background,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Rejects 18-Month Offer, Gets 15 Year Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman convicted of passing bad checks
pleaded for a lenient sentence by inviting the court to look at her
sterling record as a scholar and a teacher. The judge did _ and
found out she was also a liar.
   Jeanne Brooks was sentenced Monday to the maximum 15 years in
prison on two bad check charges and one count of grand theft. The
sentence was imposed after her last-ditch plea for leniency in
which she noted that the state earlier had offered 18 months.
   The 32-year-old defendant claimed to have a bachelor's degree in
English literature from Holy Cross, a master's degree from
Georgetown University and six years' teaching at a St. Petersburg
high school.
   A presentence investigation portrayed what she had hoped _ a
picture of a person who just made a mistake.
   But Hillsborough Circuit Judge Susan Bucklew noticed an
inconsistency in the report _ while Ms. Brooks was earning her
master's in Washington, D.C., she was serving jail time in New
York. The judge ordered further investigation.
   Ms. Brooks, sobbing before the bench Monday, admitted they were
all lies, although she said she had been a teacher's aide.
   ``I lied to the court. I've lied to everybody in my life for a
long time now,'' Ms. Brooks said. ``I tried to validate what
everybody expected of me. There's no excuse, no justification.''
   ``I would seriously doubt almost anything you tell me now,'' the
judge said.
