<FIRST>u a AM-Helmsley 1stLd-Writethru a0696 12-13 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0975</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Leona Helmsley Gets 4 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10, `Mrs. Helmsley, wearing ...' with two grafs
to CORRECT her quote to ``I've been found guilty'' sted ``I am guilty''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY30, NY39, NY40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leona Helmsley was sentenced Tuesday to four
years in prison and fined $7.1 million by a federal judge who
ignored her sobbing plea for mercy and blamed the hotel queen's tax
evasion on ``naked greed.''
   U.S. District Judge John M. Walker Jr. also sentenced Mrs.
Helmsley, 69, to three years of probation and 750 hours of
community service at Hale House, a home for infants born addicted
to drugs.
   Mrs. Helmsley _ said to have boasted to a maid, ``We don't pay
taxes. Only the little people pay taxes.'' _ was also ordered to
repay nearly $1.7 million in back taxes and bear the government's
costs in bringing her to justice.
   ``Your conduct was a product of naked greed. ... You believed
you were above the law and displayed no remorse or contrition,''
Walker told Mrs. Helmsley.
   He said she shirked a ``moral responsibility to uphold the law''
that came with her position, breaking the law ``consciously and
repeatedly.''
   ``No person,'' he said, ``no matter how wealthy and prominent,
stands above the law.''
   Walker allowed Mrs. Helmsley to remain free pending a decision
on her appeal of her Aug. 30 conviction on 33 counts of tax
evasion. Should her appeals fail and she goes to prison, she would
be eligible for parole after serving a year and three months.
   Mrs. Helmsley could have been sentenced to 127 years in prison
if she had been given the maximum sentence for each of her
convictions and been ordered to serve them consecutively, which is
rare.
   Mrs. Helmsley, wearing a black dress with a gold pendant, told
Walker before sentencing, ``I am more humiliated and ashamed than
anybody can ever imagine that I've been found guilty of a serious
crime. ...
   ``I feel like I'm in the middle of a nightmare,'' she said, her
80-year-old husband, Harry, sitting three rows away.
   ``I beg you, don't let me lose Harry too,'' Mrs. Helmsley said,
sobbing, her cheeks flushed and stained with tears. ``Our whole
life has been work and each other. Please don't. We have nothing
else.''
   But she was stone-faced as she left the courthouse with her
husband.
   ``Four years in jail, you should have got more,'' shouted
someone in a crowd of bystanders that stood by as she left.
   The sentiment was shared by many in the crowd who saw Mrs
Helmsley as the embodiment of a greedy decade in which inside
traders and savings and loan executives grabbed lucre and headlines.
   Since her indictment, Mrs. Helmsley has been vilified in court
and out. She was a high-profile target; her picture appears in
nearly every ad for the Helmsleys' 27 hotels. The ad for
Manhattan's Helmsley Palace describes it as ``the only palace in
the world where the queen stands guard.''
   Mrs. Helmsley's attorney described her as a ``tough bitch'' in
opening arguments. The prosecutor, in his closing, described her
``selfishness, greed and sheer arrogance.''
   Mrs. Helmsley and her husband were worth a billion dollars. But
she was convicted of evading more than $1.2 million in federal
taxes between 1983 and 1985 by billing personal expenses through
the Helmsley business.
   Those expenses included construction of an elaborate, $1.1
million enclosure for the swimming pool at the Helmsley's 28-room
mansion in Greenwich, Conn., along with a $130,000 indoor-outdoor
sound system Mrs. Helmsley fancied after seeing a similar system at
Disney World.
   There were other expenses: $58 for leg waxing, $21 for a
membership in a crossword club, several purchases of lingerie and
underwear.
   Employees who testified at her trial described her as a
capricious, despotic boss who fired people on a whim. When she
balked at paying a contractor who built an outdoor barbecue pit at
the estate, an employee reminded her that the man had six children.
   He should have kept his pants on, she replied.
   These revelations led New York Mayor Edward I. Koch to describe
her as ``the wicked witch'' and developer Donald Trump to call her
a ``sick woman.''
   Mrs. Helmsley told the judge that coverage of the trial had
forced her and her husband to hide from the public in their house.
   Her attorney, Gerald Feffer, told Walker his client had become a
``lightning rod'' for hate mail, death threats and anti-Semitic
remarks. ``She has been ridiculed, abused and humiliated in an
unprecedented way, having nothing to do with her wrongdoing.''
   He asked that her sentence be limited to community service at
Hale House. Prosecutors asked for up to 15 years of prison time.
   Two employees were tried and convicted along with Mrs. Helmsley.
Co-defendant Joseph Licari received 30 months in prison, three
years probation and a $75,000 fine. Co-defendant Frank Turco,
another Helmsley employee, received a two-year term, three years
probation and a $50,000 fine.
   Her husband originally was charged, but his case was dropped
when it was found his mental capacity had diminished. During the
two-hour proceeding Tuesday, Helmsley dozed; when his wife was
sentenced, he watched alertly.
   To suggestions that Harry Helmsley would be left alone if Mrs.
Helmsley was sent to prison, prosecutor James DeVita replied:
   ``At the very least, Mr. Helmsley knowingly acquiesced to Mrs.
Helmsley's insistence that these dealings be carried out. He more
than anyone else had the opportunity to see these crimes were not
committed and he didn't do it.''
   The Helmsleys still face prosecution on charges of evading state
taxes; no trial date has been set.
</TEXT>
