<FIRST>r w PM-PlasticBoycott Bjt   12-13 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plastic Boycott, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmentalists Criticize `Degradable' Plastic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The label ``degradable'' is surfacing on
plastic products from trash bags to diapers, but environmentalists
call it a marketing ploy that should be rejected.
   Six environmental groups called Tuesday for a boycott of all
degradable plastic products, contending there is no proof that the
products will decompose in a landfill any faster than conventional
plastics.
   ``Degradable plastics are a consumer ripoff,'' said Jeanne Wirka
of the Environmental Action Foundation, a Washington-based
environmental group.
   Richard Denison of the Environmental Defense Fund accused
manufacturers of ``preying on the environmental concerns of
American consumers'' to sell trash bags and other plastic items.
   ``Degradable plastics may be good for profits, but they are bad
for the environment,'' Denison said.
   In recent months, an increasing number of degradable products _
from trash and grocery bags to diapers _ have cropped up on grocery
shelves. Manufacturers contend the products made of a plastic
compound will degrade in a relatively short time when left to
sunlight and, in some cases, even in landfills.
   The products include Hefty and Glad trash bags and several
brands of diapers. Some supermarkets also are increasingly using
degradable plastic bags for carrying groceries home because
environmentally concerned consumers shy away from conventional
plastic bags.
   Biodegradable plastics are made by adding corn starch to the
plastic polymer.
   Archer Daniels Midland Co., which manufactures the corn starch
additive, maintains that its use will cause the plastic to degrade
in a landfill ``within three to five years.''
   ``The life of current landfills can be extended by 20 percent
while achieving an operational cost savings of 30 percent,''
company vice president Martin Andreas said recently when describing
the degradable plastic product.
   ``They will not solve all our solid waste issues, but they have
definite advantages if applied properly,'' said Tim Draeger,
executive director of the Degradable Plastics Council, a St.
Louis-based group made up largely of companies involved in the
production or use of degradable plastics.
   The plastics industry is divided on the issue.
   ``Degradability is not the solution to the solid waste
problem,'' said Robert J. Barrett, general manager of solid waste
management solutions at Mobil Chemical Co. in Pittsford, N.Y.
   Mobil, which produces Hefty bags, turned to degradable bags
because of consumer and competitive pressures, he said.
   ``We have found ourselves in the position of a strong consumer
demand for degradable plastics'' and competitors are providing the
product, Barrett said in a telephone interview.
   He said the plastic in Hefty bags will decompose faster than
conventional plastic when exposed to sunlight, but responds no
different from other plastic when buried.
   The plastic compound used by Mobil is different from the corn
starch and plastic polymer mixture that makes up the degradable
plastic products advertised as decomposing when buried.
   Barrett said Mobil had no definitive proof that the corn starch
mixture will decompose significantly faster in a landfill
environment than conventional plastic.
   The groups calling for the boycott are the Environmental Defense
Fund, Environmental Action Foundation, Environmental Policy
Institute-Friends of the Earth, Natural Resources Defense Council,
Public Citizen and the Coalition for Recyclable Waste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseBudget     12-13 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Budget,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats, Republicans Signal Fray Over Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans are clashing over
the adequacy of defense cuts being weighed by the Bush
administration, even as former Pentagon officials support larger
reductions.
   A Senate Budget Committee hearing, held Tuesday to consider the
depth of savings that might be found in the defense budget, offered
a preview of the partisan clashes likely to dominate debate over
the fiscal 1991 budget.
   While committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., argued that
military spending can be reduced well below current levels, ranking
Republican Pete Domenici of New Mexico insisted that cutbacks must
be deliberate and well studied.
   Sasser said that as a result of the military buildup of the
Reagan administration, this year's $285 billion Pentagon budget is
$70 billion above the U.S. peacetime average since World War II,
excluding the Korean and Vietnam war years.
   ``Those massive expenditures have ... diverted us from the
enterprise of building a sounder, more productive domestic
economy,'' he said.
   Domenici, however, warned that a reduction of the defense budget
will have to occur slowly and will not necessarily be an economic
panacea.
   ``Will it solve the problems relating to health care costs?'' he
asked. ``Will it make our children study harder in school? Will it
make Americans more productive?''
   Former Defense Secretary Robert S. McNamara and another one-time
top Pentagon official called for military cuts surpassing those the
Bush administration is considering.
   McNamara and Lawrence J. Korb sought to justify their separate
proposals by citing a need to address domestic problems and react
to the easing of East-West tensions.
   ``In the face of ... economic and social problems, it would be
folly to spend more than we need for defense,'' McNamara, who
served as defense secretary under Presidents Kennedy and Johnson,
told the committee. ``We are doing so.''
   McNamara called for holding military spending to $290 billion in
fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1, and cutting it gradually to $265
billion in 1994.
   Korb, assistant defense secretary for manpower and reserve
policy from 1981 to 1985, said pressures created by the
Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law and Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's arms reduction proposals make the time right for cuts
in U.S. defense outlays.
   ``There is no doubt that the combination of
Gramm-Rudman-Gorbachev can and should drive the level of defense
spending down by about 25 percent'' over the next five years, Korb
told the lawmakers. Under his proposal, the defense budget would
drop to $225 billion by 1995.
   The Bush administration is studying cutting the projected rate
of growth for Pentagon spending by up to $180 billion over 1992 to
1994, reductions that would still leave military outlays above $290
billion for each of those years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HealthPlans     12-13 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Plans,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bogus Health Plans May Leave Workers Without Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers risk being stuck with
paying their own medical bills because of bogus insurance plans
that the federal government allows but doesn't police, authorities
say.
   The Labor Department's efforts to monitor so-called multiple
employer welfare arrangements ``are sorely lacking or are
non-existent,'' Patricia Donovan Petersen, deputy insurance
commissioner in Washington state, told a House subcommittee on
legislation and national security on Tuesday.
   The arrangements, which pool health care coverage for small
employers who can't get coverage from larger insurance carriers,
were created under the federal Employee Retirement Income Security
Act.
   States generally regulate insurance and require cash reserves to
back claims, witnesses told the Government Operations Committee's
subcommittee. The health insurance arrangements generally do not
maintain reserves to pay claims, said Raymond Maria, acting
inspector general for the Labor Department.
   Ms. Petersen acknowledged that the reserve requirements would
hurt many beneficial operators.
   ``With the expectation of staying afloat for a period of time
through aggressive selling and slow claims payment, these
fraudulent (arrangements) have become a variation of the classic
Ponzi scheme,'' Maria said. Many operators abscond with the funds,
leaving the workers high and dry, the two witnesses said.
   Some 5 million such arrangements exist nationwide, Maria said.
The number of fraudulent ones is unknown.
   State enforcement agencies have been frustrated ``by multi-state
fraud schemes, limited resources and historical unresponsiveness''
by the Labor Department.
   Both Maria and Ms. Petersen said the operators try to escape
state enforcement by claiming that the federal government has
jurisdiction.
   But Ms. Petersen said her efforts to bring in the federal
government bore no fruit.
   She said she was shuttled between the Office of Inspector
General and the Office of Pension, Welfare Benefit Administration
until she finally gave up and used what state court action she
could in an investigation begun in 1988. She said she couldn't even
get a list of operators.
   ``You are not required to obtain a license or certificate of
authority to operate from the Department of Labor,'' she said.
   She said she was investigating two operators. One ran programs
known as the Western Business Association, Western Timber
Association and Western Alliance of Agriculture; and one ran a
program known as the Northwest Loggers Association.
   By the time she obtained a state court order, the operator of
Northwest Loggers had left the state with the program funds and
``hundreds of consumers in some six states with thousands _
probably hundreds of thousands _ of dollars of unpaid medical
claims and with no medical coverage.''
   ``To date I know of no criminal, civil or other disciplinary
action taken or planned by any division of the Labor Department or
any other entity,'' she said, adding that the operator, Gary N.
Stone, has settled in Nevada and is setting up another plan.
   Unpaid medical claims for the other companies total at least
$100,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
