<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     12-13 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comedy is King in Nielsen Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedy is still king in the Nielsen's weekly
ratings book as sitcoms held the top six spots.
   NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' was first again, and ABC's ``Roseanne''
moved up to third place behind NBC's ``Cheers,'' according to the
A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings for last week's prime-time shows.
   Cosby's ratings, as well as his assurance he wants to do another
season at NBC, is good news for the first-place network. Despite
published reports that CBS had sought his show, Cosby said he
wanted to stay with NBC.
   CBS had negotiated with producers Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner
for their services as programming chiefs and purchase of their
company, which produces ``Cosby'' and ABC's ``Roseanne.''
   NBC won the week survey by more than 2 ratings points. NBC had
an average of 14.2 to ABC's 11.9 and CBS' 11.3. Each point is the
percentage of the nation's 92.1 million homes with televisions
tuned to a show.
   For the season, NBC leads with a 15.0 average to ABC's 13.3 and
CBS' 12.2.
   Once again, NBC placed its entire Thursday night schedule, plus
two comedies from Saturday, in the top 10.
   Here are last week's top shows: NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and
``Cheers''; ABC's ``Roseanne''; NBC's ``A Different World,'' ``Dear
John,'' and ``The Golden Girls''; CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and ``Murder,
She Wrote''; NBC's ``L.A. Law'' and ``Empty Nest.''
   NBC's plans to move ``Dear John'' from Thursday to Wednesday in
early January could be bad news for the show starring Judd Hirsch.
NBC will replace it on Thursday with a new show, ``Grand,'' from
the Carsey-Werner Co.
   NBC Entertainment president Brandon Tartikoff said at a
televised briefing for affiliate stations Monday that he felt
``Dear John'' was strong enough to survive the move and would be
compatible with ``Night Court.'' He defended giving the coveted
Thursday spot to ``Grand,'' saying the show needed nurturing and
that Carsey-Werner had done well.
   Three CBS Monday night comedies improved their ratings.
``Designing Women'' moved up to 18th place. ``Newhart'' was 21st
and ``Murphy Brown'' was tied for 26th.
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s top-rated show is ``Married...With
Children'' in 47th place. However, the Fox shows are down in the
ratings since their late summer surge when Fox ran original shows
against network reruns.
   ABC was first in the evening news ratings with 11.2 to CBS' 10.2
and NBC's 9.9.
</TEXT>
