<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-13 0919</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>1989 Cotton Crop to be Smaller Than Previous Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the 1989
cotton crop is expected to be slightly less than 12.1 million
bales, down 22 percent from last year's harvest but virtually the
same as estimated in November.
   In its new estimate Tuesday, based on field conditions as of
Dec. 1, the department's National Agricultural Statistics Service
said a 20 percent drop in the acreage for harvest and slightly
lower yields account for the decline from 1988 levels.
   Overall, cotton farmers had 9.53 million acres for harvest this
fall, down 20 percent from 1988. The yield is expected to average
608 pounds per acre, down 11 pounds from last year but up a pound
from the November forecast.
   ``The Delta states experienced favorable weather during harvest
and show an increase from last month,'' the report said. ``In
Texas, an October freeze lowered expected yields.''
   But cotton harvest made good progress last month in the Plains
and could be completed ahead of normal, the report said. By Dec. 3,
the harvest was 89 percent completed in Texas, compared with 75
percent a year earlier and the average of 60 percent.
   Orange production was forecast at 194 million boxes, unchanged
from the previous forecast two months ago based on Oct. 1
indications, but 6 percent below last season.
   ``This decline is due mostly to Florida's 11 percent decrease
from last season,'' the report said. ``Freezing weather in Florida
during late February killed some of the open bloom and damaged new
growth.''
   The report also indicated dry edible bean production this year
at 24.1 million hundredweight, up 25 percent from last year's
drought-reduced harvest but still 7 percent short of 1987
production. Acreage for harvest was up 24 percent from last year
and the average yield, at 1,436 pounds per acre, was up 1 percent.
   Burley tobacco production was estimated at 543 million pounds,
up 14 percent from 1988 but fractionally below the November
forecast. The area for harvest is up 13 percent from last year and
the average yield is up 18 pounds per acre.
   No new estimates were issued for the major field crops such as
corn, wheat and soybeans.
   In a related report, the department's world outlook board said
prospective levels of cotton production and use in 1989 remain at
near the levels indicated last month, although production prospects
are up on a few foreign countries.
   ``This likely will mean reduced needs for U.S. cotton in world
markets and lower U.S. export prospects,'' the report said.
   The global outlook for wheat is ``largely unchanged'' from the
November forecast, the report said. For corn, sorghum, oats and
other so-called coarse grains, 1989-90 production and inventories a
year from now are expected to be down marginally from last month's
outlook.
   ``Larger output is forecast for Canada, Eastern Europe and
Australia,'' the report said. ``However, these gains are more than
offset by smaller crops in the Sudan, Argentina, Mexico and several
other countries.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 103,632 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement.
   The Agriculture Department said Tuesday that the corn was
shifted by exporters from ``unknown destinations'' to the Soviet
Union for 1989-90 delivery.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
total 160,700 tons of soybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal and
7,300 tons of barley.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn
and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 298,700 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 103,632 tons of
corn would be about 4.1 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.22 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the
latest sale could have a farm value of about $9 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter says
that among the things Poland needs to boost food production are
agricultural chemicals, currently the target of environmentalists
and federal regulators in the United States.
   ``We need to do whatever we can to improve agricultural
productivity in Poland,'' Yeutter said Tuesday at the National
Press Club. ``Interestingly, there were two principal requests in
this area.''
   High-protein supplements for livestock feed were one, and
agricultural chemicals were the other.
   ``As we have experienced the situation here where folks are
wanting to ban agricultural chemicals in the United States, the No.
1 priority on the list in Poland was agricultural chemicals,'' he
said.
   But the aid package approved by Congress doesn't include such
chemicals, Yeutter said
   ``There's little that we can do, perhaps nothing that we can do
in the way of agricultural chemicals from a governmental
standpoint.''
   Thus, he said, the private sector may have to meet Poland's
request for farm chemicals through grants and donations.
   Yeutter recently led a presidential mission to Poland to help
determine what kind of aid may be needed to help that country
rebuild its agriculture.
</TEXT>
