<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--AncientBones     12-13 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Ancient Bones,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ice Age Fossils Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODBURN, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers digging a sewer line found bones
of animals dating back from the ice age.
   William Orr, a geology professor at the University of Oregon and
curator of its Thomas Condon Collection of Fossils, brought six
bones from the site to the Woodburn City Council meeting Monday.
   ``I'm here to generate enthusiasm for a summer dig,'' he said.
``My grad students say I rarely get excited about anything, but I'm
excited about this.''
   Orr said the bones were the best representation of ice-age
mammals he had seen in a quarter-century of teaching. The bones
were found 6 to 9 feet below ground and are 30,000 to 50,000 years
old, Orr said.
   He said the crew's discovery was typical. ``Most major finds
happen this way,'' Orr said.
   Woodburn is about 30 miles south of Portland.
</TEXT>
