<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senators-Keating     12-13 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senators-Keating,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Senators Sought Last-Minute Sale of Lincoln S&amp;L</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senators contend their last-ditch bid to
back the sale of Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, and head off
its seizure by federal regulators, was an effort to save taxpayers
a record bailout cost.
   Aides to Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz., acknowledge that the lawmakers were lobbied to back the
sale last spring by a former California congressman, Republican
John H. Rousselot, and Lincoln owner Charles H. Keating Jr., a
major contributor to their campaigns and causes. Rousselot headed
the group that sought to buy the S&amp;L.
   But the senators' discussions with the top thrift regulator _
just days before the government seized Lincoln on April 14 _ were
motivated by a desire to prevent an expected record $2 billion-plus
government bailout of a savings and loan, the aides said in recent
interviews.
   The Lincoln collapse has brought multiple investigations and
lawsuits, including a Senate Ethics Committee review of
intervention by Cranston, DeConcini and three other senators: John
McCain, R-Ariz., Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., and John Glenn,
D-Ohio.
   The five received $1.3 million from Keating, his immediate
family and employees, but all five deny any connection between the
money and their intervention with regulators.
   In the frantic week before the seizure of Lincoln, Cranston and
DeConcini discussed a possible sale with M. Danny Wall, the head of
the government's Office of Thrift Supervision who announced his
resignation last week. The contacts are listed in Wall's office
phone logs and memos, and it was confirmed by spokesmen for the
senators and Wall that the Lincoln sale was discussed.
   A sale of Lincoln could have allowed Keating's American
Continental Corp. _ the bank's parent company _ to avoid its filing
for bankruptcy protection on April 13.
   Rousselot, who led a prospective buyers' group just before the
seizure, said, ``I was lobbying to try to get a sale
accomplished.'' Rousselot, in an interview, added that most of his
discussions were with Cranston or his staff.
   Rousselot said he learned right before the senators' phone calls
that a seizure might be imminent.
   He said he was told by a member of the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board that ``It's a good thing you've got this group together''
because otherwise the board staff was preparing to recommend that
Lincoln ``be put into conservatorship.''
   The board took such action after rejecting the Rousselot deal as
inadequate, as it had done with two previous offers.
   Cranston Chief of Staff Roy F. Greenaway said Rousselot wanted
the California senator to ask Wall to let Rousselot ``present his
case'' before top banking officials. The senator passed on the
request, and Rousselot said he did speak directly with the top
officials.
   The aide, who attended the session, said Cranston told the
regulator he ``didn't have any idea of whether the offer by the
Rousselot group met their standards and didn't want to prejudge
that. But if the sale did meet their standards and there was no
reason to object, he urged the sale be approved to save the
taxpayers money.''
   DeConcini spokesman Robert Maynes said that in the last-ditch
discussions to avoid a takeover, DeConcini asked Wall, ``Is there
any way for a sale to go through so Keating could be out and the
institution could be saved, so jobs would not be lost and taxpayers
would not have to foot another savings and loan bill? The answer he
got back in all cases, was `no.'''
   Keating's chief spokesman did not return telephone calls to
comment on the lobbying effort.
   Karl Hoyle, Wall's spokesman and chief of congressional affairs,
said the calls from the senators to Wall were ``appropriate because
we were not being asked to make any conclusions. We were not being
asked to make a deal,'' but were advised ``if there was a deal,
move on it quickly.''
   He said banking officials also hoped for a sale because ``it was
the least expensive way to solve the problem. It was less costly
than paying it off or taking it over.''
</TEXT>
