<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jewish Santa,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Can't Resist' Santa Role</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You don't have to be Jewish to enjoy bagels
and lox, says Abel Stone, and you don't have to be Christian to
play Santa Claus.
   ``I would've been Santa Claus whether I was white, black, green,
whatever ... I cannot resist,'' said Stone, 75, a New York-born Jew
who devotes much of the year to charities like Jewish Family
Services.
   At Christmas time, he turns into Santa Claus _ in appearances at
schools, parks and churches, but always in poor areas. He spends a
portion of his retirement fund each year on toys.
   Stone said he plays Santa because he likes people, especially
kids.
   ``With the kids,'' he said, ``It's easier to let it out.''
   Silver-haired and jolly most of the time, the retired furniture
maker's representative drives a hard bargain when he's collecting
promised donations for his charitable work.
   ``Well, you tell that no-good (so-and-so) to come up with
something,'' he was overheard telling one donor during a recent
interview.
</TEXT>
