<FIRST>r a PM-HinduTaxidermist     12-13 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hindu Taxidermist,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hindu Makes His Living Stuffing Animals</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRANDYWINE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky for Thakorial Mistry, there are no
sacred cows in his business.
   Mistry is probably the only Hindu taxidermist in the world. It
might seem strange that a Hindu would make a living stuffing and
mounting animals, for Hindus revere living creatures and believe in
reincarnation.
   The people in his hometown outside Bombay, India, were mostly
vegetarians and would never kill an animal, he said. Only the
poorest and hungriest would eat a chicken, but only behind closed
doors.
   No wonder that Mistry was considered an oddball _ or worse _
when he began his boyhood hobby of taxidermy. His first specimen
was a pigeon, which he grabbed in the rafters of his home,
chloroformed and stuffed with cotton.
   ``It didn't turn out real good but it looked good to me, until
it started to smell,'' Mistry said.
   The boy bagged small birds and chipmunks with a BB gun and
stuffed them in the privacy of his attic bedroom. Mistry's secret
escaped the notice of his father, the town blacksmith and a devout
Hindu, but his neighborhood pals were fascinated.
   ``I always enjoyed opening animals,'' he said. ``I love animals.
My friends thought I was crazy, but when I finished they thought I
had created something beautiful. Even my parents, when they found
out, they liked it too.''
   Mistry arrived in the United States in 1971 with a degree in
chemistry and zoology, about $6 in his pocket and plans for a
career in medical technology. However, he said, ``my hobby turned
into a living.'' After an apprenticeship with taxidermy shops in
Maryland and Virginia, he went into business for himself in 1976.
   His large studio in this rural community south of Washington
D.C. is filled with striking examples of Mistry's artistry,
including deer, bear, bison, pheasant, peacocks, fish and big game
from Alaska to Africa.
   Beneath a mounted shark, a red fox leaps after a pair of grouse
rising in flight. Two gamecocks lunge in battle, their neck
feathers bristling.
   Mistry, 43, assisted by his wife Jyotsna, stuffs about 1,000
creatures annually, at prices ranging from $6 an inch for
freshwater fish to as much as $2,000 for a grizzly bear.
   Business is profitable enough for Mistry, who became a U.S.
citizen in 1979, to support his family of four and to help nearly
two dozen relatives immigrate from India.
   Lounging on the marble floor of his showroom is one customer's
unclaimed white Pekinese dog, one of many small pets that Mistry
has lovingly freeze-dried for their grieving owners.
   The Pekinese would make a dandy doorstop, but Mistry says it's
so lifelike that ``it makes a good guard dog'' to scare would-be
intruders peering through the windows.
   Mistry recalls with a grin the time a husband called to ask,
``Can you stuff my wife?'' On another occasion, a lawyer telephoned
to say his client had written a will requesting that his body be
freeze-dried.
   Mistry turned them both down. ``I could do a human being, but
it's illegal,'' he said. ``Even if it were legal, I wouldn't do
it.''
   How does he feel about stuffing a cow, the most sacred animal in
the Hindu religion?
   ``Sure, I could do a cow,'' Mistry replied. ``No problem. You've
got to change to survive wherever you go. This is America.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Drugs     12-13 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Drugs,0643</SECOND>
<BYLINE>U.S. Says Prison Terms For Drug Killers `Tantamount to Life' ^By
JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are hailing the stiff
sentences handed to a pair of Mexican drug lords convicted of
masterminding the torture-slayings of a U.S. narcotics agent and
his pilot.
   ``My heartfelt congratulations go to the government of Mexico
and its judicial authorities for their decisive and correct
action,'' said John Lawn, head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration in Washington.
   Rafael Caro Quintero, 37, and Ernesto Rafael Fonesca Carrillo,
56, were convicted Tuesday of masterminding the 1985 murders of DEA
agent Enrique Camarena and his Mexican pilot and sentenced to 40
years in prison.
   ``There is no chance of these sentences being reduced,''
Attorney General Enrique Castillo de Alvarez said.
   Fernando Arias, a spokesman for the attorney general, said Caro
Quintero and Fonseca would have to serve a total of 74 and 53 years
respectively because of other drug-related convictions. There is no
parole in drug-related cases.
   Lawn said the stiff sentences are ``tantamount to life
imprisonment'' and send a stern warning to other drug kinpins.
   He said it shows that ``no matter how wealthy and powerful their
infamous trade has made these narco-murderers, they are not beyond
the reach of justice.''
   Don Hamilton, spokesman for U.S. drug czar William J. Bennett in
Washington, also praised the convictions and the sentences.
   ``It's certainly nice to see people like Caro Quintero off the
streets,'' he said. ``I think the United States and Mexico will
both be the better for it.''
   The Camarena case badly strained relations between Mexico and
the United States in its early stages because Mexican authorities
allowed Caro Quintero to escape to Costa Rica.
   The United States virtually shut down the border at one point by
searching every Mexican and vehicle trying to enter the United
States.
   DEA acting Deputy Administrator Terrence Burke said in
Washington that he personally informed Camarena's widow and sister
of the convictions.
   ``It was good to be able to call them with good news for once,''
he said. ``They were very pleased that this action was taken by the
courts of Mexico.''
   Caro Quintero was a middleman for Colombian cocaine cartels
smuggling drugs to the United States. His story and the Camarena
killing were the subject of a book and television movie in the
United States, both called ``Desperados.''
   He and Fonseca were tried earlier this year.
   The convictions and sentences were announced Tuesday by Judge
Tomas Hernandez Franco of the 4th Criminal Court in Guadalajara, a
major drug trafficking center 350 miles west of Mexico City where
Camerena was based.
   The U.S. agent was kidnapped there on Feb. 7, 1985. His pilot,
Alfredo Zavala Avelar, was abducted a few days later.
   Their bullet-riddled bodies were found on March 5 in shallow
graves on a ranch 60 miles southeast of Guadalajara, the capital of
Jalisco state.
   Both Camarena and Fonseca are multi-millionaires whose assets
include ranches, aircraft, luxury cars, houses, apartments, hotels
and businesses which the government is in the process of
confiscating.
   Caro Quintero and Fonseca also were sentenced Tuesday on several
other kidnapping, drug trafficking and weapons charges related to
the Camarena case.
   The sentences, which will be served concurrently, add up to 116
years for Caro Quintero and 144 for Fonseca.
   Caro Quintero was sentenced to 34 years in another drug case
earlier this year and Fonseca was given 13 years. These sentences
will run consecutively to those in the Camarena case.
   Ten other men were sentenced to the maximum term of 40 years for
taking part in the killings, and 13 other men received lesser
sentences for their involvement in drug operations run by Caro
Quintero and Fonseca.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-BudgetBlues     12-13 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Budget Blues,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: The Peace Dividend and Bush's 60 Minutes of Gloom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is throwing himself with verve
into crafting a 1991 budget, trying to decide how to apply a
``peace dividend'' while admitting his own budget chief sometimes
gives him ``60 minutes of gloom.''
   The peace dividend is the savings that will come from lower
defense spending because of reduced tensions in Eastern Europe.
   Although some of his predecessors have approached budget choices
with disdain, Bush has been going over next year's budget
line-by-line in excruciating detail, according to top aides.
   He's had no trouble playing Solomon in refereeing battles
between agency heads and Richard G. Darman, director of the Office
of Management and Budget.
   On defense spending, for instance, he simply split the
difference between the $294 billion in defense outlays sought by
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and the $290 billion proposed by
Darman.
   Sources said Bush decided on a final figure of $292 billion _ up
just $1 billion from the current level _ for military spending in
the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1.
   Bush will submit his fiscal 1991 budget to Congress on Jan. 22.
White House and OMB officials say they expect to have final figures
locked in sometime after Christmas.
   Under the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law, the 1991 budget
must reduce the deficit to no more than $64 billion. Since the
current year deficit is expected to be from $100 billion to $105
billion, that suggests Bush must come up with $30 billion to $40
billion in budget savings.
   ``We've got enormous budget problems facing me,'' Bush recently
told a group of reporters who interviewed him in the Oval Office.
   ``I feel very strongly about it because Darman just walked out _
and when you see him walking out, I go through a period of about 60
minutes of gloom before I refocus on what else is happening out
there,'' Bush added.
   Darman is fast earning a reputation as Washington's Christmas
Scrooge.
   And, as some well-placed aides tell it, he's living up to the
characterization placed on him by former colleague and onetime
Budget Director David Stockman: ``He was always asking inconvenient
questions, or seemingly preoccupied with the process _ tactics,
trades, deals, winning.''
   ``It's that time of year. It's December _ time for Christmas and
arm-wrestling with Dick Darman,'' said drug policy director William
Bennett, who has had his own feuds with Darman over spending on the
war on drugs.
   The multimillion-dollar disputes with Darman are common, said
presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``There's millions and
millions of dollars (in differences) between every agency and
Darman,'' Fitzwater said.
   Darman, a master at strategy, this year devised a new process
under which Cabinet officers who do not want to negotiate cuts in
their programs with the OMB can take their appeals directly to Bush
_ but at a risk.
   The risk is that if Bush turns down their appeal or does not
decide to split the difference as he did with Cheney, they would
have to compete among themselves for a small pool of money reserved
for high-priority programs.
   Some Cabinet members have told Darman no thanks, and have taken
their appeals to Bush anyway _ including Cheney and Health and
Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan, who saw Bush on Tuesday.
   Still, White House officials say Darman's new process has cut
down on the number of direct budget appeals to the president.
   Bush has suggested he will ask for small increases in education,
environmental and crime programs and will renew his request for a
child care tax credit. He also is expected to propose additional
Medicare reductions and a lower capital gains tax.
   Bush insists that any ``peace dividend'' that results from a cut
in U.S. armed forces in Europe will not be spent on other programs.
   A student at a Denver high school asked Bush last week: ``What
are you proposing to do with that money?''
   ``It's to pay off the deficit,'' Bush said.
   Suggestions that defense savings be used to fund domestic
programs are ``some crazy ... wild speculation,'' the president
said. ``I will not acquiesce in that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
