<FIRST>r a PM-MagooHomecoming     12-13 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Magoo Homecoming,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transferred Police Dog Returning to Memphis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aging police dog whose transfer to
Atlanta provoked protests by congressmen and schoolchildren, is
returning to Memphis.
   The German shepherd named Magoo was transferred in September by
the Federal Aviation Administration, spurring petitions and angry
letters.
   ``There's no telling how many letters the Department of
Transportation and the FAA may have received,'' police Sgt. Robert
Petrowski, Magoo's former partner and guardian, said Tuesday.
   Magoo first moved to Memphis six years ago as part of an airport
security program. Though assigned to the city dog squad, he
remained FAA property. Memphis police withdrew from the airport
program about a year ago, and the FAA subsequently decided to
transfer Magoo.
   Petrowski collected 7,000 names on a petition he sent to
President Bush. And among those writing on Magoo's behalf were Gov.
Ned McWherter, Tennessee's two U.S. senators and two congressmen.
   ``One teacher at Bartlett Elementary called me and said she had
used (newspaper) stories about Magoo in her class,'' Petrowski
said. ``They had all written letters to the president and letters
to their pen pals, telling them to write letters to the president
to try to get him back.''
   FAA spokesman Jack Barker in Atlanta said his agency reviewed
Magoo's transfer again and agreed to return him to Memphis on the
city's promise he would be available for airport bomb duty if
needed.
   Petrowski said Magoo will continue his general police
assignments and any needed airport work, but at 8 years old, the
dog likely will retire in a year or two.
   Magoo has lived with Petrowski and his family when off duty and
is expected to spend his retirement there as well.
   ``I'm just as happy as I can be,'' Petrowski said, adding that
he expects Magoo to be home in about a week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
