<FIRST>r a PM-NationalAnthem     12-13 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Anthem,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Francis Scott Key's Hometown Riled About Anthem Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would scrap ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' as the national anthem has riled people in
the hometown of Francis Scott Key, who wrote the song 175 years ago.
   ``I honestly feel they should leave it be,'' said Harry L.
Decker, Frederick's historian. ``I think it's more like a hymn than
a song. It brings tears to a lot of people's eyes.''
   Rep. Andrew Jacobs Jr., D-Ind., has introduced legislation in
Congress for the ninth time in 12 years to supplant it with
``America the Beautiful.''
   Decker said Tuesday he thought the campaign for change was being
fueled by people who believe the song embraces war and by those who
think it's too hard to sing.
   ``If they can't sing it, they can't sing,'' Decker said.
   David Maloney Jr., president of the Historical Society of
Frederick County, said he liked ``America the Beautiful,'' but
thinks it's less ``emotionally stirring'' than ``The Star-Spangled
Banner.''
   The proposal to replace the national anthem also has struck a
sensitive chord with the Frederick Keys, the city's new minor
league baseball team.
   ``His monument (in Mount Olivet Cemetery) faces our new
stadium,'' said Mark Zeigler, the team's assistant general manager.
``I've got a lot of pride in this area and the state.
   ``This is something of local significance that is national. It
would take away some of the significance.''
   Frederick County Arts Council Director Carole Werking said: ``I
like `America the Beautiful.' I think it is easier to sing, but
Francis Scott Key being Frederick's native son and having a lot of
pride in my community, I don't think we should change it.''
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer has written to Maryland's
congressional delegation, urging them to oppose any change.
   Jacobs said the protests probably are unnecessary because he
doesn't think his bill will pass.
</TEXT>
