<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-13 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks At New High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed
above the 38,000-point level for the first time Wednesday, while
the dollar moved lower against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 258.89
points, or 0.68 percent, ending the day at 38,062.42, yet another
high. The index had risen 50.86 points on Tuesday.
   The dollar ended trading at 143.70 yen, down 0.77 yen from
Tuesday's 144.47-yen close. The U.S. currency opened at 143.80 yen
and ranged between 143.35 and 143.90 yen.
   The dollar remained weaker against other currencies following
its slump against the West German mark in New York overnight, said
a Bank of Tokyo trader, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. unit fell in New York, where the mark and the Swiss
franc surged against the dollar and other major currencies due to
the recent pro-democracy movements in Eastern Europe as well as
expectations for an interest rate hike in West Germany, dealers
said.
   ``Although the dollar fluctuated less in Tokyo, it continued to
weaken against the mark, which resulted in the yen's relative
strength against the dollar,'' the Bank of Tokyo trader said.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main barometer rose quickly
in early trading as overnight gains in the Dow Jones average of 30
major industrial issues in New York and the yen's recovery against
the dollar reassured participants, dealers said.
   Tomoyuki Morimoto, a dealer with New Japan Securities, Co., said
purchases by speculative investors contributed to the index's rise.
   He said they bought spot issues of the Nikkei and sold other
issues in the futures market to take profits out of the price gap
between the two markets.
   But market players were gradually becoming worried about the
speed of gains in the index, he said.
</TEXT>
