<FIRST>r w PM-FBI-Barry     12-13 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI-Barry,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: FBI Gathered Evidence on Mayor's Alleged Drug Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI report includes evidence the agency
believes could support allegations that Mayor Marion Barry used
drugs, but it does not recommend whether an indictment should be
sought, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post today cited anonymous sources who said
prosecutors have not made any decision on whether charges against
Barry should be filed.
   After six years of intermittent federal inquiries on the mayor's
conduct, the report represents the first focus on a possible case
against Barry, the newspaper said.
   The sources say the report makes it clear that the FBI has
concluded it has obtained enough information for prosecutors to
decide whether to seek an indictment against Barry, the Post
reported.
   It was expected to cover the alleged use of illegal drugs by the
mayor and whether he committed perjury when he testified before a
grand jury in January concerning his relationship with convicted
cocaine dealer Charles Lewis, the Post said.
   Lewis, who is cooperating with federal investigators, testified
Tuesday before the grand jury and was expected to return on
Thursday.
   Sections of the report were sent to U.S. Attorney Jay B.
Stephens, sources told the paper. The decision on whether to go
further rests with Stephens.
   R. Kenneth Mundy, the mayor's attorney, said Barry is
``absolutely innocent'' of any wrongdoing. He said Barry ``is not
concerned'' about any case that would be based on allegations by
Lewis.
   ``He's (Lewis) trying to save himself,'' Mundy told the Post.
``We're not bedeviled by Charles Lewis. This is a man who would lie
about anything.''
   ``This is another example of the Post vendetta to get the mayor
out of office,'' said Lurma Rackley, the mayor's press secretary.
``The media should let the case be tried in the courts and not in
the press.''
</TEXT>
