<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bat Judge,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robed Crusader Chases Down Fugitive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few weeks after he broke up a fight in his
courtroom, Judge Bob Musseman chased down a fugitive who had bolted
from the courthouse.
   Larry Dean Freeman, 30, was in the Tulsa County court Tuesday to
face a traffic violation. But during the case, Musseman learned
Freeman was wanted on two felony warrants.
   Freeman ``started getting antsy'' and asked whether he could
step into the hall for some water, said court clerk Cathy Ardey.
   Musseman followed and was knocked down when Freeman suddenly
turned and struck him in the chest with an elbow, authorities said.
   ``He was able to get up first because I was tangled up in my
robe,'' Musseman said.
   The chase continued outside until Musseman yelled he would catch
Freeman no matter how far they ran. Freeman surrendered.
   Last month, after Musseman broke up a fight between two women,
co-workers awarded him a cape and mask and snickered about the
``Bat Judge.'' In June, Musseman helped collar a man who tried to
flee his trial.
   ``I'm three and oh,'' Musseman said.
</TEXT>
