<SECOND>PM-Weapons Plants-Radiation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flaws in Radiation Protection Cited at Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4, `The inspections ...,' to correct location of
Fernald plant to make it near Cincinnati sted Dayton and fix typo in Piketon;
picks up 5th graf pvs, `The Pantex ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at several government nuclear weapons
plants face unnecessary risks of radiation contamination, in part
because too little is spent on protective measures, according to
Energy Department inspection reports.
   The problem persists despite greatly increased attention in
recent years to health, safety and environmental hazards at the
weapons plants.
   Flaws in worker protection against radiation are a recurring,
though little publicized, theme in recently released health and
safety reports following inspections of facilities in four states.
   The inspections by government and private experts, ordered by
Energy Secretary James D. Watkins in June, document radiation
control problems at the Pantex weapons assembly factory near
Amarillo, Texas; the Y-12 nuclear materials manufacturing plant at
Oak Ridge, Tenn.; the Fernald uranium processing plant near
Cincinnati, Ohio, and the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant
near Denver, Colo.
   Inspections also were conducted at weapons sites in Kansas City,
Mo., Mercury, Nev., and Piketon, Ohio, but the results have not yet
been publicly released. All 17 major weapons facilities eventually
are to undergo such inspections.
   The Pantex report published last week said that while inspectors
found no clear and immediate danger to worker safety, the radiation
protection program was generally inadequate as evidenced by
``extensive'' violations of federal regulations.
   The report said the Energy Department and the company that runs
Pantex under a government contract, Mason &amp; Hanger-Silas Mason Co.,
have been aware of the problem for several years, yet ``little has
been achieved to correct it.''
   In a memo attached to the Pantex report, Watkins said the
findings indicate workers are not adequately protected from routine
and emergency releases of radiation. He ordered immediate action to
fix the problems.
   In late October, Watkins ordered special action to correct
weaknesses in radiation protection at the Y-12 plant at the federal
Oak Ridge nuclear reservation.
   The Y-12 inspection team reported a variety of major problems.
Among them was a failure of the plant's health physics specialists
to routinely check radiation levels in all areas where significant
amounts of radiation could be present.
   The report also said radiation survey results often are poorly
documented, and that the plant does not routinely check for flaws
in warning devices and other safety features of equipment that
generates radiation. For example, such checks are not routinely
done on electron-beam welders, which produce radiation fields
comparable to, and sometimes higher than, X-ray machines, the
report said.
   The inspectors said no health physics specialists were present
to monitor radiation levels when workers removed an air filter from
the roof of a building at the Y-12 plant, ``despite the potential
for spreading contamination on the roof and also for an unmonitored
release of airborne radiation.''
   Also, the report said ``safety work permits'' prepared for
employees at Y-12 were ``not an effective means of informing
workers of the radiological conditions that may be encountered at
the job site.''
   Significant flaws in radiation protection also were found by
inspectors at Fernald, where production lines were closed earlier
this year because of pressing environmental problems.
   Workers at one Fernald building may have unknowingly ingested
radioactive uranium metal aerosols because of ventilation defects
in an area where workers are not required to wear respirators, the
inspection report of last August said.
   Only limited corrections can be made at Fernald because of a
lack of money, the report said. Budget problems also prevent a
quick correction of deficiencies in training of radiation workers
and radiation protection technicians, the report said.
   Inspectors of the Rocky Flats plant, which makes plutonium
triggers for nuclear weapons, cited a variety of radiation
contamination problems, including uncertainty about the accuracy of
measurements of plutonium particles in the air. They said the
measuring equipment is old and prone to breakdowns.
   Rocky Flats' plutonium operations were shut down last month for
a management shakeup. Last year the plant was closed for several
months after two employees walked unknowingly into a contaminated
area and inhaled radioactive particles.
</TEXT>
