<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Nazis     12-13 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Nazis,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Law Allowing Prosecution of Alleged Nazi War
Criminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament's decision to allow the government to
prosecute alleged Nazi war criminals is expected to result in the
trials of at least three aging emigres suspected of the mass murder
of Jews.
   Rabbi Marvin Hier, head of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles, which first brought the issue to the attention of British
authorities, issued a statement after Tuesday's vote that said:
   ``The British Parliament's decision is not an act of vengeance
but a victory for justice. It states clearly that crimes against
humanity can take no refuge in the passing of time, and keeps faith
with the victims of the Holocaust.''
   Home Secretary David Waddington urged the trials, saying, ``It
is the instinctive wish of most us to get on with our lives in
peace and not to rake over the past. But sometimes one is brought
face to face with facts that cannot be buried.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and opposition Labor Party
leader Neil Kinnock both voted in favor of prosecution, which
passed 348-123.
   In order for the prosecutions to proceed, Parliament must pass
further legislation that would enable naturalized British citizens
to be prosecuted for crimes committed abroad. The office of the
Director of Public Prosecutions would decide whether individual
prosecutions should go ahead.
   Australia and Canada have passed similar legislation within the
past few years. The U.S. Justice Department investigates and
deports suspects for trial in Israel.
   The action in Parliament followed the publication of a
government-commissioned report July 24 saying there is enough
evidence to prosecute four suspects, one of whom has since died. It
urged further investigation in another 124 cases.
   The suspects were not identified in the report published after a
year-long investigation by two prominent lawyers, including Sir
Thomas Hetherington, Britain's former Director of Public
Prosecutions.
   The inquiry was set up after the Simon Wiesenthal Center, which
accused Britain of foot-dragging on the issue, submitted a list of
suspects to the government in 1986.
   Almost all the suspects in Britain are from Lithuania, Latvia
and the Ukraine in the Soviet Union.
   One suspect, Antanas Gecas, 73, a Lithuanian-born mining
engineer living in Scotland, has been identified by the British
media. He has acknowledged witnessing atrocities while serving in a
notorious Lithuanian police battalion. But he says he only watched
and is the victim of a Soviet smear campaign.
   The issue has deeply divided legislators. Opponents argued
during Tuesday's debate that prosecutions 45 years after the end of
World War II will turn into show trials, rekindling old hatreds
with witnesses who are unreliable because of age and bent on
revenge.
   ``Most of the witnesses are either senile, infirm or dead,''
said Conservative Party legislator Winston Churchill, grandson of
Britain's World War II leader. ``This would lead to the
establishment of show trials in this country and has no place in
British justice.''
   Supporters argued passionately that Britain should not remain
what several called ``a safe haven for monsters.''
   ``These are not crimes committed in the heat of battle,'' said
legislator Sir Bernard Braine. ``These are cases of the murder of
non-combatants and the slaughter of whole communities of women and
children.''
</TEXT>
