<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-13 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Begins Probe Into Seabrook Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel has launched an investigation of
``apparently contradictory'' methods used by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission in deciding whether to allow the Seabrook nuclear plant
to open.
   Rep. Peter Kostmeyer, D-Pa., chairman of the House Interior
Committee oversight and investigations subcommittee, notified NRC
chairman Kenneth Carr of the inquiry in a letter sent Tuesday.
   Legislators from around New England called for the investigation
last month after the NRC's Atomic Safety and Licensing Board
recommended that Seabrook be awarded a license.
   Kostmeyer cited a recent dispute in which the licensing board
downplayed concerns raised by the NRC's higher level Atomic Safety
and Licensing Appeal Board about the adequacy of New Hampshire
evacuation plans.
   Ron Sher, spokesman for New Hampshire Yankee Electric Co., the
operator of the plant for the multi-company owning consortium,
said, ``Seabrook station has been the most closely scrutinized
nuclear plant ever licensed, and in the 18-year licensing history
of Seabrook, intervenors have had ample opportunity to make their
case.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jailed Woman Urged to Cooperate with Salvadoran Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvadoran ambassador to the United States
says the American woman jailed after an arms cache was found at her
San Salvador apartment would probably be released if she cooperates
with police.
   Ambassador Miguel Angel Salaverria met Tuesday with Rep. Nancy
Johnson, a Republican from Jennifer Casolo's home state of
Connecticut.
   Salaverria, speaking with reporters after the briefing, said
Casolo may have been unaware of arms hidden in her backyard, but
``She needs to say who she rented the house from. ... The more she
cooperates, the easier it will be to end the case.''
   Casolo, 28, went to El Salvador in 1985 to work for Christian
Education Seminars, a group dedicated to influencing U.S. policy by
organizing tours for Americans to learn about the civil war there.
   She was arrested Nov. 26 after police found mortar grenades,
dynamite, detonators and thousands of rounds of ammunition in the
backyard of the house where she was living. She is being held for
90 days pending an investigation into possible links between her,
the explosives and Salvadoran rebel forces.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Tests Intended to Avoid Military Incidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet military ran through
procedures designed to prevent potentially dangerous clashes last
week over the Bering Sea as the two countries conducted
communication tests for the first time.
   Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said the Dec. 6-8 exercise was
designed to show that the two nations' armed forces can cooperate
in anticipation of an agreement scheduled to go into effect Jan. 1.
That accord is supposed to regulate the operation of military
forces near each other.
   Williams said the tests involved ships, aircraft and
ground-based air traffic control and monitoring facilities of both
U.S. and Soviet armed forces.
   U.S. and Soviet aircraft met at specific locations ``and
communicated directly to each other,'' Williams said.
   The tests over the Bering Sea _ which divides Alaska from the
Soviet Union _ included the aircraft from each nation flying over
the other's territory.
</TEXT>
