<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Bonuses 1stLd-Writethru a0472 12-13 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Bonuses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Increase in Winter Bonuses is Highest in Nine Years</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with average monthly wages.</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of 291 major Japanese firms got winter
bonuses this month averaging $4,870, up 7.3 percent from last year
and the highest increase in nine years, the Japan Federation of
Employers' Associations said today.
   An association official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
attributed the increase to business prosperity in Japan.
   The official said winter bonuses rose by 21.3 percent from 1988
to an average of $4,350 for workers in the steel industry.
   In shipbuilding, bonuses rose by 15.1 percent to an average
$4,070 and in the mining industry they climbed 12.8 percent to
$4,310, he added.
   Meanwhile, employees of newspaper companies received winter
bonuses averaging $8,800, up 6.44 percent from a year earlier, the
official reported.
   Bonuses in the information and communications industry averaged
$5,550, up 5.5 percent, those in the food industry $5,470, up 3
percent, and those in the chemical industry $5,170, up 6.1 percent,
the official said.
   He said employees of the 291 major firms account for just 5
percent of Japan's 60 million-member labor force.
   Japanese companies ordinarily pay bonuses twice a year, in
summer and before the new year.
   The average monthly wage at the 291 firms was $1,690, the
official said.
   As of March 1989, the average monthly wage for newspapers was
$2,440, for information and communications $1,805, for the food
industry $1,790, and for the chemical industry $1,750.
   The average monthly wage for the steel industry was $1,740, for
shipbuilding $1,730 and for the mining industry $1,510.
   For all Japanese workers, as of March, the average wage was
$1,620 a month, not including bonuses and overtime, the Labor
Ministry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
