<DOCNO> AP891213-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugLegalization     12-13 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Legalization,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Federal Judge Calls for Legalizing Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The so-called war on drugs is a failure and
drugs from cocaine to heroin should be legalized, taxed and
dispensed by the state, a federal judge says.
   In his speech Tuesday evening at the Cosmopolitan Club, U.S.
District Judge Robert W. Sweet became the first federal judge to
propose publicly that illicit drugs be made legal, according to the
Drug Policy Foundation, a non-profit organization in Washington
that researches alternatives to current drug policy.
   ``I suggest it is time to abolish the prohibition _ to cease
treating indulgence in mind alteration as a crime,'' Sweet said.
   ``More money, more prisoners, more addicts _ these numbers
demonstrate to me our present prohibitive policy has failed, flatly
and without serious question.''
   Among the other prominent individuals favoring legalization are
former Secretary of State George Shultz, Baltimore Mayor Kurt
Schmoke, economist Milton Friedman and conservative columnist
William F. Buckley.
   Sweet said proverty caused the drug epidemic, and drug dealing
will continue to attract some poor people as long as potential
profits are high.
   ``Perhaps we must ask not what can we do to eliminate drugs, but
what can we do to eliminate or at least reduce the level of
poverty,'' he said.
   Sweet, a former New York deputy mayor and prosecutor, and a
trial judge in the Southern District of New York for more than 11
years, said the effort to stem the drug epidemic by jailing more
people is not working. He cited a declining commitment to jobs,
education, health and housing in the nation at a time when building
jails has become a growth industry.
   The enormous increase of criminal drug trials on the docket
forces long delays in civil matters. No juries were available in
Manhattan's federal court in September for civil trials, he said.
   Legalizing drugs would identify users, raise revenue for
prevention and rehabilitation, and eliminate gangs and drug
dealers, Sweet said.
   ``Obviously, the model is the repeal of Prohibition and the end
of Al Capone and Dutch Schultz.''
   Sweet said pharmaceutical companies could manufacture the drugs
and the state could distribute them to addicts for less than what
drug dealers charge, with tax revenue used for research, education
and treatment of addiction.
   Distribution to minors should remain prohibited, Sweet said.
   The Bush administration has said legalization would create an
``unqualified national disaster'' by creating many more addicts.
   On Tuesday, drug czar William Bennett compared legalization
supporters to advocates of slavery.
   ``This is not an economic issue. There were arguments made for
slavery based on economic considerations,'' Bennett said at a news
conference in New Hampshire.
   ``For someone to sit in a room and make an abstract bloodless
economic argument _ when we're looking at 200,000 cocaine babies a
year _ is to miss the point,'' he said.
   Bennett also said he approved of taking custody away from
addicted parents in extreme cases.
   ``Obviously, you give parents _ you give anybody _ the chance to
recover, to get better,'' Bennett said in an interview. ``But
supposing the parent isn't getting better, shows no interest in
improving, going into treatment, and it's adversely and
dramatically affecting the well-being of the child? The state can
intervene.''
   Bennett said most states already have legislation that provides
for taking children away from addicts who have proven unfit to
raise them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
