<FIRST>r a PM-OfficialShot     12-13 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Official Shot,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Critical Condition After Apparent Suicide Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities investigating
illegal bingo gambling and public corruption reportedly were
closing in on a top state official who was in critical condition
today after an apparent suicide attempt.
   The Nashville Banner quoted unidentified sources Tuesday as
saying investigators were focusing on how Secretary of State Gentry
Crowell solicited money for political campaigns from architects,
engineers and bingo operators.
   Crowell, 57, was found by his son, Brooks, on the porch of his
home in Lebanon, about 30 miles east of Nashville. Police said
Crowell apparently shot himself once in the mouth with a
.38-caliber revolver, which was found next to him.
   He left no note, and authorities would not say if they had any
leads as to his motive.
   Tennessee Bureau of Investigation agents were investigating the
shooting to make sure no foul play was involved, said Deputy
Director John Carney.
   Doctors said Crowell's fate depended on how well he reacts to
swelling and infection in his brain.
   Neurosurgeons removed damaged brain tissue and a bullet from his
skull during more than four hours of surgery at Vanderbilt
University Medical Center. The gunshot wound caused ``a lot of
bleeding and it destroyed a lot of tissue,'' said John C. Ross, the
hospital's vice chancellor for health affairs.
   ``It's impossible to know at this time what residual damage
there might be,'' Ross said.
   ``The critical period now will be the next several days.''
   Crowell has not been implicated in any wrongdoing, though part
of the investigation has clouded his office.
   His former chief bingo inspector, W.D. ``Donnie'' Walker,
recently began a seven-year sentence at the federal prison in
Talladega, Ala. The charges included extorting payoffs from bingo
operators. And Crowell's former assistant, Mary Sue Wright,
resigned in August before giving testimony before the U.S. grand
jury in Memphis.
   She was named an unindicted co-conspirator in a Memphis bingo
operation and given immunity from prosecution. She has admitted
taking money from a Democratic legislative campaign fund,
authorities said.
   Bingo was outlawed in Tennessee this year after the state
Supreme Court ruled that the game is a lottery, in violation of the
state constitution.
   Previously, it had been legal for charity fund-raising, but
reports showed that bogus charities were set up and money skimmed
from some operations.
   Since January, 22 people have been indicted or pleaded guilty as
a result of the investigation. They include state Rep. Tommy
Burnett, charged with conspiracy, gambling, mail fraud and perjury.
Burnett has said he is innocent.
   Sen. Robert Rochelle, a Democrat from Crowell's hometown, called
Crowell a private person who didn't talk about his problems.
   But Rochelle pointed to the strain of news coverage in
connection with the federal investigation.
   ``I wish these prosecutors would quit letting people hang out
there to try to get them to talk if they don't have enough evidence
to convict them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
