<FIRST>r a PM-SovietVodka     12-13 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Vodka,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Minnesota Town Knocks Down Ban on Soviet Vodka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't as dramatic as knocking down
the Berlin Wall, but it was another sign of the thaw in East-West
relations. This small town has lifted its 6-year-old ban on Russian
vodka.
   ``It took six years, but the city of Hutchinson finally brought
the Soviet Union to its knees,'' joked Barry Anderson, the city
attorney.
   The sanction was removed Tuesday night through a unanimous voice
vote by the City Council.
   It had been issued to protest the 1983 downing of a South Korean
jetliner by a Soviet fighter pilot
   ``It's not a stunt. We take it seriously,'' insisted Councilman
Michael Carls, who is also a high school government teacher. ``It
was first outrage over their denial of life to those passengers on
the jet and today it's a feeling of pleasure over the extent of
democratization over there.''
   The council's discussion lasted five minutes and did not end
with a libation of vodka or any other beverage.
   Hutchinson's only retail liquor store is owned by the city.
Carls said other U.S. cities with municipal control over liquor
sales banned Soviet vodka after Korean Air Lines Flight 007 was
shot down, but he wasn't able to identify them.
   The plane was shot down in September 1983 on a flight from
Anchorage, Alaska, to Seoul after it strayed into Soviet airspace,
killing all 269 people aboard.
   Paul Ackland, mayor of this city of 10,000 residents, said the
Soviet Embassy in Washington would be informed that the vodka ban
has been lifted.
   ``We as a community support the changes being made and hope our
relationship continues to improve,'' he said.
   Jeanette Matheny, a clerk at Hutchinson Municipal Liquor Store,
said the ban stirred some discussion in 1983, but was quickly
forgotten.
   ``I don't even think most of the public was aware of the ban,''
she said.
</TEXT>
