<FIRST>r a PM-Brown-Desegregation     12-13 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brown-Desegregation,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court: Topeka Not Doing Enough to End School Desegregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals panel ruled that Topeka is
not doing enough to desegregate its schools since the landmark
Brown vs. Board of Education case, but a dissenting judge cited
``substantial integration.''
   In the majority opinion, Judges Stephanie Seymour and Monroe
McKay overturned U.S. District Judge Richard Rogers' 1987 ruling
that Topeka schools were not responsible for lingering segregation
because the Board of Education did not intend to keep the schools
segregated.
   The three-judge panel of the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in Denver released the full decision on the reopened case Tuesday,
sending it back to Rogers.
   The original case led to a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in 1954
that set a nationwide precedent for school desegregation and busing
cases. But the parents of black schoolchildren sued 10 years ago to
have the case reopened.
   The majority opinion, a reworked version of a 2-1 decision last
June, was accompanied by a new dissenting opinion.
   Today, lawyers for both sides expect to receive the latest
ruling.
   Seymour and McKay already had overruled Rogers in June, but
Judge Bobby Baldock didn't release his dissent then. The following
month, Seymour and McKay withdrew their decision without
explanation.
   Lawyers speculated that they wanted a chance to respond to
Baldock's dissent.
   In 1979, the parents of 17 black schoolchildren sued the
district to reopen the Brown case, contending that the district had
failed to eliminate all segregation.
   Among those parents was Linda Brown Buckner, who was a student
at the time of the 1954 decision and whose maiden name heads the
caption of the case.
   Rogers ruled in the reopened case that the school system had no
intention to maintain segregated schools.
   But Seymour wrote: Rogers ``erred by limiting the school
district's burden merely to showing that it had non-discriminatory
reasons for acting as it did. As 30 years of desegregation law have
made clear, the Constitution requires more than ceasing to promote
segregation.''
   Baldock argued the schools had done enough: ``The school board
has demonstrated concern for improving the racial composition in
the Topeka schools while retaining the neighborhood school concept.
   ``In some places the two are not compatible, but in this system
substantial integration has been achieved.''
   Rich Jones, an attorney for the parents who sought the case's
reopening, said lawyers will key on the dissenting opinion.
   ``This is the first time we get to see the dissent,'' he said.
``The school district will be in a position to make a decision.''
   The attorney for the school district, Joe Zima, said the board
plans to schedule a meeting early next week to consider it actions.
   Zima said the school district could ask all 10 judges on the
Court of Appeals to hear the case, ask the U.S. Supreme Court to
hear the case, or go before Rogers to help fashion a solution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0059 </DOCNO>
