<HEAD>Twelve Killed In Gunbattle Betwee Police and Followers of Religious
Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladsesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 policemen raided the home of
a controversial Moslem religious figure, touching off a gunbattle
with his followers in which at least 12 people were killed, police
said today.
   The police officers stormed the northern Bangladesh home of
Matiur Rahman on Tuesday to free a colleague abducted by Rahman's
supporters on Sunday while checking out reports the home was being
used as a sanctuary for criminals.
   Eight supporters of Rahman and four police officers were killed
in the clash in in Pakundia in Kishoreganj district, 50 miles north
of Dhaka, a local police officer said by telephone.
   The officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Rahman's
supporters opened fired on the policemen when they went to free
their colleague.
   Bangladesh, a nation of 110 million people, has many so-called
Moslem saints like Rahman who claim they have extra ordinary
powers. Some exploit people. Moslems make up about 88 percent of
Bangladesh's 104 million people.
