<FIRST>r w PM-GanderCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0487 12-13 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gander Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0487,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman, Others Seek Investigation Into Canadian Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of airline to Arrow Air sted Air Arrow in 3rd
graf, Tallon, victims'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of some of 248 U.S. soldiers killed
in an airliner crash in Newfoundland four years ago are joining
with Congress members and Canadian investigators in urging a U.S.
inquiry into the disaster.
   ``Something is obviously wrong and has been obviously wrong for
the last four years,'' Rep. Robin Tallon, D-S.C., said at a news
conference following ceremonies at Arlington National Cemetery
marking the crash anniversary.
   Tallon, victims' relatives and two Canadian Aviation Safety
Board members who disagreed with a majority conclusion on the crash
said they see a U.S. and Canadian government coverup in the
three-year investigation that concluded the chartered DC-8 Arrow
Air jetliner was downed by ice on the wings as it took off from
Gander, Newfoundland.
   A board minority report said there was evidence of a fire and
explosion, possibly from a terrorist bomb, before the Dec. 12,
1985, crash which killed the soldiers and eight American crew
members.
   A Canadian judge earlier this year disagreed with both the board
majority and minority conclusions but said the inquiry into
Canada's worst aviation disaster should not be reopened because
there wasn't enough evidence left to determine the cause.
   Tallon is trying to get President Bush and a congressional
committee to open inquiries into the crash, which has never been
the subject of a formal U.S. investigation.
   Tallon said he has been lied to about the crash by the FBI and
the Defense Department, which participated in the Canadian
investigation but issued no conclusions of their own.
   ``The FBI said there was no investigation, then they found a
277-page report,'' he said. ``The Defense Department said there was
no cargo manifest, then all of the sudden there was one.''
   ``There is circumstantial evidence of a coverup,'' Tallon said.
He said Canadian authorities appear to have gone along with U.S.
Defense Department decisions on what was in ``the national
interest.''
   Tallon said he was not prepared to say that terrorists were
involved but noted that the soldiers had been on a mission to the
Middle East, that a pro-Iranian group claimed credit for the crash
and that it came at a time when it was later determined that the
United States was involved in the Iran-Contra affair, trying to
exchange arms for U.S. hostages in Lebanon
   Dr. Doug Phillips of St. Petersburg, Fla., said his organization
of victims' families has grown from six members at the first of the
year to 130 with renewed interest in the crash.
   Phillips, a pathologist, said examination of the bodies,
including that of his son, Sgt. James D. Phillips, shows evidence
of a fire prior to the crash.
   He said family members have written to Bush complaining about
the lack of a U.S. investigation but he said none has received a
reply.
   In October, 103 members of Congress signed a letter to Bush
calling for a presidential inquiry, saying the United States has an
``obligation to finish the investigation that was inadequately
conducted by the Canadian government.'' Tallon invited Bush to the
memorial service, but the president did not attend.
   Les Filotas and Ross Stephenson, members of the Canadian
investigative board, told the news conference they believed an
explosion caused the crash _ either from a bomb or explosive
souvenirs in the cargo area. Filotas said U.S. soldiers have been
known in other instances to smuggle aboard in their luggage
weaponry that is not allowed on airliners.
   The Air Line Pilots Association concluded in June, after its own
inquiry, that the Canadian investigators relied on fabricated and
erroneous evidence in reaching their conclusion that the crash was
caused by wing ice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
