<HEAD>Man Who Said he Spied For the Army is Arrested for Desertion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 3rd, `Carelse said...' and inserts 1 graf after
6th, `The army...' to ADD background on ANC operations abroad. Pickup 7th,
`Police...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former army commando who
says he was assigned to spy on anti-apartheid activists in the
Netherlands has been arrested for desertion, military headquarters
said today.
   The arrest came five days after an anti-apartheid newspaper,
Free Weekly, published an interview in which the former soldier,
Robert Carelse, made detailed claims about his activities in the
Netherlands.
   Carelse said he was instructed by the Military Intelligence
branch to live in Amsterdam and infiltrate militant anti-apartheid
groups, including the African National Congress guerrilla movement
and the Committee of South African War Resisters. The Netherlands
has very active anti-apartheid groups, including the main office of
the War Resisters.
   Carelse said he went to the Netherlands in July 1988 and
returned to South Africa in March. While in Amsterdam, Carelse
reportedly stayed with his brother-in-law, Keith Raper, a leader of
the draft resisters' committeee.
   At the time of his arrest, Carelse was enrolled at a technical
college in Johanneburg.
   The army statement said only that Carelse had been arrested as a
deserter. There has been no official comment on Carelse's
allegations.
   Security officials often boast that they have infilitrated the
ANC in neighboring African countries and elsewhere in the world.
The ANC has offices in about 30 countries, more places than South
Africa has embassies worldwide.
   Police are investigating the possibility that some members of
the Military Intelligence branch may have had direct or indirect
links with death squads alleged to have killed anti-apartheid
activists in South Africa over the past 10 years.
