<FIRST>r a PM-Bolles     12-13 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bolles,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reporter Subpoenaed in Bolles Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter who has criticized the Arizona
attorney general's investigation of the 1976 car-bomb murder of
journalist Don Bolles has been slapped with a grand jury subpoena
in an attempt to intimidate him, his lawyer says.
   ``We'll move to quash or limit the subpoena,'' David Bodney, a
lawyer for reporter Don Devereux, said Tuesday.
   Devereux was served with a state grand jury subpoena last week
by aides to Attorney General Bob Corbin. The subpoena came days
after Devereux had published new criticisms of Corbin's efforts to
find Bolles' killers.
   The attorney general and Devereux declined comment, citing a
state law that makes it a crime to disclose grand jury matters.
   But Bodney confirmed that his client had been subpoenaed and
added, ``It is Devereux's judgment that it is harassment and
designed to intimidate.''
   Bolles, a reporter for The Arizona Republic, died 11 days after
a remote-controlled bomb blew up his car 13 years ago.
   Devereux, a freelance reporter, has published stories in The
Scottsdale Progress and in a private newsletter pointing to areas
that he says Corbin's office has failed to pursue.
   The state grand jury does not have jurisdiction over the killing
but has been investigating conspiracy and obstruction of justice
allegations, according to documents made available to The
Associated Press in October.
   Bodney said the subpoena did not ask Devereux to bring any
documents or specify whether he was a potential target or what the
grand jury wants to know.
   ``I think it's improper for the attorney general to conduct a
freewheeling examination of a reporter that will inhibit his
newsgathering ability perhaps for all time,'' the lawyer said.
   In addition to the state and federal constitution's free-press
guarantees, Arizona's shield law protects reporters from having to
disclose their sources, he said.
   ``Let the grand jury call witnesses with first-hand information
and not interrogate reporters about their sources,'' Bodney said.
   Corbin, a Republican, has come under increasing fire over the
unsolved slaying. He has not announced whether he will seek
re-election next year.
   He recently asked a judge to reinstate a murder charge against
one of the original suspects in a move that Devereux had
criticized, days before being subpoenaed, as likely to be
unproductive and a possible case of playing politics.
   Among those known to have been subpoenaed is Neal Roberts, a
Phoenix lawyer who has acknowledged that he arranged for John
Harvey Adamson to travel to Lake Havasu City hours after the
bombing. Adamson, a racing-dog breeder, was convicted of planting
the bomb. No mastermind was ever convicted, and investigators have
not established the motive with any certainty.
</TEXT>
