<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople-Vietnam     12-13 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People-Vietnam,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Blames Economic Embargoes for Boat People Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam said today that embargoes by
non-Communist nations helped create the economic problems that
caused many of its citizens to flee to other countries in search of
better economic opportunity.
   The commentary by the official Vietnam News Agency also
reiterated the government's condemnation of Hong Kong's forcible
repatriation on Tuesday of more than 50 Vietnamese refugees.
   ``The policies of hostility and economic sanctions ... by some
countries against Vietnam over the past 10 years is one of the
reasons causing economic difficulties in Vietnam. This led to the
fact that some people fled the country,'' said the commentary
carried by the Voice of Vietnam radio and monitored in Bangkok.
   ``Vietnam cannot ignore its compatriots who nurtured the
illusion of looking for a paradise in other countries and have been
detained in camps for years,'' it said.
   Hong Kong and its colonial ruler, Britain, flew back home 51
Vietnamese from a Hong Kong camp Tuesday in the first forced
repatriation.
   Hong Kong considers 44,000 Vietnamese who poured into the
territory since June 1988 to be illegal immigrants seeking jobs,
not political refugees from Vietnam's Communist regime.
   ``Vietnam always welcomes those who are willing to repatriate
and at the same time rejects forced repatriation,'' the commentary
said. ``The repatriation from Hong Kong, including those who
returned on Dec. 12, 1989, are part of the framework of that
policy.''
   Vietnam has been largely isolated from the non-Communist world
since North Vietnam overthrew the U.S.-backed South Vietnam
government in April 1975, triggering the boat exodus.
   Most non-Communist countries, including Japan and the United
States, imposed or continued embargoes on Vietnam after its troops
invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and installed a pro-Vietnamese
government.
</TEXT>
