<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 2ndLd-Writethru a0511 12-13 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0511,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>De Klerk Meets With Mandela At His Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf, `Mandela, leader...' to UPDATE
with reaction from far-right party. Pickup 6th graf, `De Klerk, who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed black nationalist
leader Nelson Mandela, whose release is expected within weeks, met
today with President F.W. de Klerk about the prospects for
black-white political negotiations.
   The meeting, announced by the Justice Ministry, was Mandela's
second with a South African president this year. He met with
President P.W. Botha on July 5, also at Tuynhuis, the presidential
office in Cape Town.
   The Justice Ministry said Mandela had requested the meeting and
that de Klerk ``welcomed the opportunity.'' It said further talks
were expected next year.
   The meeting ``fitted in with Mr. de Klerk's program to consult
with the full spectrum of political opinion concerning the mutual
future of all South Africans,'' the statement said.
   Mandela, leader of the outlawed African National Congress and
the country's best-known black leader, has been imprisoned since
1962 and is serving a life sentence for sabotage and plotting to
overthrow the white-led government.
   The far-right Conservative Party, which won 31 percent of the
white vote in September's parliamentary elections, said today's
meeting represented a de facto legalization of the ANC.
   The Conservative's leader, Andries Treurnicht, condemned de
Klerk for meeting the leader of ``a banned terrorist organization''
and suggested he had underestimated whites' desire to retain full
political sovereignty.
   De Klerk, who took office in August, says he wants to end racial
discrimination and extend political rights to South Africa's 28
million blacks within five years.
   However, he opposes black majority rule and a one-man, one-vote
system. He envisions some type of mechanism that will give whites
veto power on major policy decisions.
   At today's meeting, de Klerk and Mandela discussed ``ways and
means to address current obstacles in the way of meaningful
dialogue,'' the Justice Ministry statement said. ``Follow-up talks
in the new year are envisaged.''
   The ministry said no further details about the substance of the
talks would be released.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee and Constitutional Development
Minister Gerrit Viljoen attended the meeting, the statement added.
   All prominent black leaders, even conservative ones, say
Mandela's release is a precondition for negotiations with the
government. Most black leaders also demand the release of other
security prisoners and the lifting of the 3{-year-old state of
emergency before any talks begin.
   Mandela, 71, is not likely to be released this year, but
government sources have been quoted as saying he probably will be
freed before Parliament convenes in early February.
   De Klerk, since succeeding Botha, has ushered in several reforms
that have eased political tension.
   He has permitted huge anti-apartheid demonstrations, ordered
desgregation of whites-only beaches, and proposed the repeal of the
Separate Amenities Act, which permits the segregation of many
public facilities.
   Seven of Mandela's ANC colleagues were freed Oct. 15 in what was
seen as a trial run for Mandela's release. There has been no
upsurge in unrest related to their release and frequent appearances
at anti-government meetings.
   Mandela is held in a suburban-style staff residence at Victor
Verster prison farm outside Cape Town and has been meeting
regularly with a wide range of anti-apartheid activists.
   Mandela met Tuesday for two hours with Walter Sisulu, one of the
ANC leaders freed two months ago.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, wages a bombing and sabotage
campaign in its bid to undermine the government. However, the armed
struggle has been largely dormant in recent months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
