<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Georgia     12-13 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Georgia,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army General Denies Poison Gas Used in Georgia Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army officer in charge of the military
investigation into the deaths of 20 Georgian nationalists in April
has denied that troops used nerve gas to break up a rally, a
newspaper reported today.
   Maj. Gen. V. Vasiliev defended the soldiers' actions and said
they were provoked by nationalists who pelted them with bottles and
stones on April 9 when thousands gathered in the main square of
Tbilisi, the republic's capital.
   Nineteen people died and at least 300 people were hospitalized
when soldiers, many armed with shovels, waded into the crowd to
break up the demonstration. Another nationalist was fatally shot
the night before for a curfew violation.
   A civilian commission and Communist Party officials said two
weeks later that an investigation showed that soldiers had used a
poisonous, incapacitating gas to disperse the rally.
   Vasiliev told the daily Sovietskaya Rossia, ``no poisonous gases
were used, only special tear gas, substances similar to those used
by police in the West.''
   He said his investigation showed that 272 names of alleged
victims of poison gas released by nationalists were false and many
names were repeated ``time and time again.''
   Vasiliev said soldiers acted in self-defense when they attacked
some demonstrators with shovels, but that none of the victims had
died as a result of the attack.
   ``The majority of the people were killed in the mass commotion
when people were horribly pressed together,'' he said.
   Following the fatal rally, Georgian Communist Party chief Givi
Gumbaridze told reporters that some of the victims had died from
gas poisoning.
   A full report on the incident was expected to made to the
Congress of People's Deputies during its current session in Moscow.
</TEXT>
