<FIRST>u i PM-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0456,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvador President Calls Summit Accord a Blow to Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CLARIFY that accord condemned insurgencies
in El Salvador and Nicaragua. Pickup 6th graf ``I do not...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani
says the latest Central American accord strips the leftist rebels
of any legitimacy and if they don't disband ``the army will deal
with them.''
   The five Central American presidents on Tuesday demanded the
dismantling of both the leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front in El Salvador and the U.S.-backed Contras fighting in
Nicaragua.
   The two-day summit in San Jose, Costa Rica, was the latest in a
series that have raised hopes but failed to bring peace to Central
America. It was the first to focus on El Salvador, and it renewed a
call earlier this year for the dissolution of the Contras.
   The joint condemnation of both insurgencies was viewed as a
victory for rightist Cristiani as well as Nicaragua's leftist
President Daniel Ortega, but it was also clouded by skepticism and
suspicion.
   ``I do not trust Daniel Ortega,'' said Cristiani.
   Neither of the rebel armies was represented at the summit and
neither has agreed to be disbanded.
   ``This continues to be the problem with all Central American
accords,'' said Luis Sanchez Sancho of the National Opposition
Union, a coalition that opposes Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government in elections set for Feb. 25.
   Cristiani said the five presidents had a position paper from the
Salvadoran rebels.
   ``Two of the presidents laughed. Others read it with dismay,''
he said. ``The impression was that it was too much gall on the part
of the FMLN, after what they have done, to continue trying to look
like Robin Hood.''
   Ortega said the success of the accord hinges on the cooperation
of the United States.
   Washington ``has the main responsibility for the demobilization
of the Contras because they continue financing them and sending
them supplies,'' he said in a national radio and television address
in Nicaragua on Tuesday.
   The summit accord implicitly chides the United States, the
Soviet Union and Cuba by saying ``nations with interests in the
region'' should be more directly involved in the peace process. The
presidents also requested increased U.N. involvement in the effort
to demobilize ``irregular forces.''
   The Salvadoran rebels have rejected the summit accord, saying it
does nothing to contribute to the possibility of a negotiated
solution to the civil war they have waged for more than a decade
against a series of U.S.-backed governments.
   ``The FMLN cannot be demobilized by means of agreements between
governments, because it is a legitimate force with popular roots in
the whole Salvadoran territory,'' they said in a communique.
   The summit followed a sharp escalation in the Salvadoran civil
war, which has claimed more than 71,000 lives. The rebels launched
a huge offensive on Nov. 11 in which more than 1,500 people _
guerrillas, soldiers and civilians _ are estimated to have been
killed.
   The accord calls on the FMLN to stop fighting and resume peace
talks with Cristiani's rightist government.
   ``With this agreement, the FMLN loses its room to maneuver,''
said Cristiani. ``The presidents are saying to the guerrillas: `You
have no right to continue violent actions.'''
   If the FMLN keeps fighting, ``the armed forces of El Salvador
will deal with them,'' Cristiani told a news conference Tuesday
after returning from the summit.
   Cristiani said his government is willing to resume peace talks
broken off by the rebels Oct. 31 after the bombing of a union
headquarters. But he said the FMLN must cease hostilities first.
   The FMLN had earlier called for a cease-fire with international
verification and recognition of territories under their control.
   ``That position is definitely unacceptable,'' said Cristiani.
   Ortega said his delegation insisted on international
verification of human rights and again criticized the Salvadoran
government for the assassination during the FMLN offensive of six
Jesuit academics.
   The murders have been blamed on the military.
   Presidents Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras, Vinicio Cerezo of
Guatemala and host Oscar Arias of Costa Rica also signed the summit
accord.

</TEXT>
