<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     12-13 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Grant Aquino Further Emergency Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives today
approved a bill granting further emergency powers to President
Corazon Aquino to impose law and order after last week's failed
coup attempt.
   In the Senate, the passage of a similar bill was blocked, with
an opposition senator warning the legislation moved the nation a
step closer to dictatorship. The Senate is expected to pass a
similar version Thursday.
   The bill was passed overwhelmingly on second reading in the
lower chamber. A final reading will be held Thursday.
   Lone opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, who once administered
martial law under the late Ferdinand Marcos, denounced the
emergency decree as a move toward dictatorship. But former human
rights lawyer Sen. Rene Saguisag defended the move in light of the
recent coup attempt.
   In a speech before the Senate, Enrile said the emergency powers
also could be used to extend the lease on the U.S. military bases
in the Philippines.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said today that rebel soldiers who
launched the coup attempt Dec. 1 were still capable of staging
terror attacks and assassinations, although they surrendered their
last stronghold Saturday.
   Ramos told a news conference the government will no longer seek
U.S. air cover over Philippine territory.
   U.S. jets flew over rebel-held bases to discourage more bombing
runs on the Malacanang presidential palace, and the U.S. help
turned the tide in favor of the government on the first day of the
mutiny.
   The Cabinet also was told that the business community is looking
for signs the government will move decisively to address the
political, social and economic damage wrought by the sixth and
bloodiest attempt so far to oust Mrs. Aquino. Share prices on the
Manila Stock Exchange fell for the third consecutive day since
trading resumed after the coup attempt.
   On Dec. 6, Mrs. Aquino declared a nationwide state of emergency,
but officials said the legislation would give her further powers.
   The House and Senate versions of the emergency bill grant Mrs.
Aquino the power to order the search for weapons and ammunition in
private homes without the normal legal constraints.
   The House voted against allowing Mrs. Aquino to intervene in
labor disputes and suspend labor laws which may impede production.
A majority of the 23-member Senate voted to keep the provision,
regarded by critics as a strike ban.
   Both versions allow Mrs. Aquino to take over public utilities,
such as privately-owned transportation firms if they violate
``national policy.''
   The House bill limits Mrs. Aquino's emergency powers to a 90-day
period, while the Senate version extends it up to six months.
</TEXT>
