<FIRST>u i PM-India-Kidnap 5thLd-Writethru a0525 12-13 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Kidnap, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0525,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister's Daughter Freed, Ending 6-Day Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with group warning of future kidnappings,
details on woman's release. Pickup 14th graf, `The Kashmir...' Subs last
graf to move down that Singh is Hindu.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers today freed a senior Cabinet
minister's daughter they had held for six days after the government
met their demand and released five jailed Moslem militants,
officials said.
   Rubaiya Sayeed, 22, was released two hours after the prisoners
went free, thereby ending the first crisis of the 12-day-old
government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh, state-run television
reported.
   The chairman of the militants' organization warned of future
kidnappings unless the government ``behaves.''
   The television flashed a news bulletin saying ``Rubaiya Sayeed
Freed,'' interrupting a cricket match between India and Pakistan.
   Ms. Sayeed's father is Home Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed. She
was kidnapped at gunpoint on Friday in Srinagar, the summer capital
of Jammu-Kashmir state and a popular tourist resort, and the
separatist Kashmir Liberation Front claimed responsibility.
   Militants had threatened to kill Ms. Sayeed, a medical intern,
unless their five jailed comrades were freed. The release followed
haggling over the site of the swap and the safety of the prisoners.
   The five were released at an undisclosed site in the city,
culminating five days of negotiations between the government and
the front, said the police officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   About two hours after the militants were released, a dazed Ms.
Sayeed was dropped at a friend's house and then taken to her home.
Later, she was to be flown to New Delhi for a reunion with her
family.
   ``By the grace of the Almighty and the blessings of millions of
my countrymen, Rubaiya has a new lease on life,'' a relieved Sayeed
said after hearing his youngest daughter was safe. ``Our ordeal of
anxiety and agony has ended. Their prayers and good wishes have
restored our child to us.''
   Sayeed, unshaven but smiling and wrapped in a brown shawl,
condemned his daughter's captors.
   ``There is no bravery in attacking a girl. It is cowardly. You
don't need guns and swords to attack a girl,'' he said. ``They have
lost the sympathy of the people in the state, in India and the
world.''
   Among the freed militants was Abdul Hamid Sheikh, a top leader
in the Kashmir Liberation Front, police said. Sheikh, who was
arrested last month after being wounded in a clash with police, was
taken by ambulance from a Srinagar hospital to the site and turned
over to his organization.
   The other four were identified as Noor Mohammad Kalwal, Mohammad
Altaf Bhat, Sher Khan Azad and Javed Ahmed Zargar, officials said.
All had been arrested on suspicion of subversive activities during
the past year but no charges had been filed.
   As news of the swap spread throughout the city, 3,000 people
filled the streets, setting off firecrackers, waving Pakistan flags
and shouting anti-India slogans.
   In Pakistan, Amanullah Khan, chairman of the militants' group,
said India had made ``a wise step'' and he hoped the government
would adopt ``a similar wise attitude toward the future of Kashmir
and leave Kashmir honorably instead of waiting until it is shunted
out and humiliated by Kashmiri freedom fighters.''
   Asked whether the swap would encourage the front to launch a
campaign of kidnappings to secure its demands, Khan said: ``It
depends on how the Indian government behaves ... because they
compelled us to take this step.''
   The Kashmir Liberation Front, which wants Jammu-Kashmir to
either become independent or part of Islamic Pakistan, commands a
large following in the Moslem-dominated Srinagar.
   The front, formed in 1965, has often attacked the government and
sponsored successful strikes in Jammu-Kashmir, the only Moslem
majority state in the predominantly Hindu India.
   At India's request, the government of Pakistan had appealed to
the militants not to harm Ms. Sayeed.
   Moslems make up 64 percent of the state's 5 million people, but
comprise just 11 percent of India's 880 million people. Hindus
account for about 80 percent of the population.
   Kashmir is claimed both by India and Pakistan, and the two
countries have fought three wars over the territory since gaining
independence from Britain in 1947.
   In a bid to halt the separatism, the new prime minister
appointed Sayeed, a Kashmiri, as head of a Cabinet committee on
Jammu-Kashmir and neighboring Punjab, where Sikh militants also are
demanding an independent homeland.
   Sayeed is the first Moslem to be named India's home minister, a
key post that oversees the country's internal security. The
appointment was seen as part of Singh's efforts to appease Moslems
who have borne the brunt of Hindu-Moslem religious riots that
claimed more than 300 lives this fall. Singh is a Hindu.
</TEXT>
