<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Human-PoweredHelicopter     12-13 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Human-Powered Helicopter,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students' Pedal Copter Certified as Making First Human-Powered Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineering students who designed
a pedal-operated flying machine have been notified that its 6.8
seconds in the air have been certified as the first human-powered
helicopter flight, officials said today.
   ``We are satisfied it was not a jump start, but a bona fide
hover that did take place,'' said Malvern Gross, president of the
National Aeronautic Association in Washington.
   The aircraft, dubbed Da Vinci III by the students at California
Polytechnic State University, hovered about 8 inches off the ground
Sunday under the observation of an NAA consultant, Cal Poly
spokesman Bob Anderson said.
   The NAA, the official keeper of U.S. aviation records, certified
the feat late Tuesday, Gross said. Although school officials at the
time said the flight lasted 7.1 seconds, the observer clocked it at
6.8 seconds, the agency said.
   The record-setting flight won't be the end of the school's
development of human-powered aircraft. ``This will just make them
work harder,'' Anderson said. ``They're already talking about
building Da Vinci IV when they get back from vacation.''
   Engineering students built the 97-pound, 100-foot-long Da Vinci
III out of space-age materials, including carbon graphite. The
machine was powered by cyclist Greg McNeil.
   Da Vinci III flew twice before, on Nov. 12 and Nov. 27. The
experimental vehicle is the fourth pedal-copter built by Cal Poly
students since 1981.
   When they build Da Vinci IV, the students will try to lighten
their flying machine, Anderson said.
   The ultimate goal is a $20,000 prize offered by the American
Helicopter Society to the first group to fly a human-powered
helicopter for one minute and reach a height of at least three
meters.
</TEXT>
