<FIRST>r w PM-HUDChanges 2ndLd-Writethru a0520-a0459 12-13 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Changes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0520-a0459,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Replacing, Shifting Several Field Managers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 2 to add Richmond, Va., manager's transfer; INSERTS
2 grafs after 11th graf, St. George Crosse, with background on Richmond
official's reassignment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top Department of Housing and Urban
Development officials in Los Angeles and New Orleans are resigning
after refusing transfers ordered by HUD Secretary Jack Kemp as part
of an agency management shakeup.
   Also affected by a flurry of personnel moves in recent weeks are
a onetime assistant to former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr., the
former heads of HUD's Baltimore and Richmond, Va., offices, the
agency's top official in Oklahoma City and its No. 2 official in
Chicago.
   None of the moves have been announced publicly. But a HUD
spokesman in Los Angeles confirmed Tuesday that Benjamin Bobo is
resigning as head of that office and will be replaced in February
by Charles Ming, now the Oklahoma City manager. Los Angeles, with
234 workers, is HUD's largest field office.
   Bobo submitted his resignation, effective Feb. 20, after
declining Kemp's offer that he take over the New Orleans office,
Reed said.
   Two HUD sources in Washington, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the current New Orleans HUD manager, Richard
Franco, told Kemp he would resign rather than accept a transfer to
become head of HUD's Newark, N.J., office. Attempts to reach Franco
late Tuesday were unsuccessful and the effective date of his
resignation could not be determined.
   Kemp has said he would replace HUD managers he did not believe
were performing adequately or did not respond aggressively to his
efforts to rid the agency of mismanagement and influence-peddling,
the subject of recent congressional hearings focusing largely on
Pierce's tenure.
   The transfer offers to Bobo and Franco are examples of Kemp
using his power to ``send more than adequate signals'' of his
displeasure, said one source. The jobs offered to Bobo and Franco
are regarded within HUD as demotions and would have required them
to make long-distance moves just before the December holidays.
   Ted Britton Jr., who under Pierce headed an office of
international affairs, accepted the Newark job after Franco turned
it down, the sources said. Kemp had abolished the international
affairs office and reassigned Britton to another headquarters job.
   The New Orleans job has been offered to George T. Ray Jr.,
currently the No. 2 official in HUD's Chicago office but he has not
yet indicated whether he will accept, the sources said.
   The Oklahoma City job has yet to be offered, and HUD also is
looking for a new manager for its Baltimore office.
   St. George Crosse, a Maryland Republican appointed to head that
office two years ago after he lost a congressional race, began
working at HUD headquarters in Washington this week after he lost a
bid to keep his job. Kemp was unhappy with the management of the
Baltimore office, the sources said.
   The former Richmond office manager, G. William Thomas, has been
given a second temporary reassignment after being removed from his
post three months ago because of Kemp's displeasure with the
office's operation.
   Kemp first dispatched Thomas to Charleston, W.Va., for a 120-day
temporary assignment, and now has demoted him three civil service
grades and sent him to Pittsburgh for a three-month stint as a HUD
loan officer.
   Bobo was criticized last year in an Office of Government Ethics
report that found HUD executives violated conflict of interest
rules by raising money from private contractors to pay for a fair
housing campaign that was a pet project of Pierce. Bobo was singled
out for raising $15,000 from a local Board of Realtors to help pay
for the campaign.
   Bobo, 44, came to HUD headquarters at the beginning of the
Reagan administration and has headed the Los Angeles office since
1984.
   His replacement, Ming, 60, is an attorney who was appointed
manager of the Oklahoma City office in February 1984. That office
has been deeply involved in widespread Federal Housing
Administration mortgage fraud investigations.
   Attempts to reach Bobo and Ming were unsuccessful. Calls to Bobo
were referred to Reed and calls to Ming's office late Tuesday went
unanswered.
   It was not immediately clear why Kemp was unhappy with Franco's
performance, although one of the sources said ``there were a lot of
political problems down there.'' Calls to Franco's office late
Tuesday were unanswered.
</TEXT>
