<FIRST>u a PM-FootballThreat     12-13 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Football Threat,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Football League Chief Says He Was Threatened By Mob</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man threatened the president of the Pop
Warner Youth Football League in the name of a major Mafia figure
for disqualifying a mob-connected team from the championships, the
league president says.
   David Tomlin, president of Pop Warner, said he was told by the
unidentified person to reinstate the team.
   ``The fact that we all appeared at the national championships
this past weekend should reassure everyone that any real threats
against us were effectively neutralized,'' Tomlin said in a
statement Tuesday.
   The threats, which were also made against a staff member, began
Nov. 8 and ``several minor physical incidents'' also took place,
Tomlin said. The statement did not elaborate. It did not identity
the team or the Mafia figure.
   Nor did the statement give the nature of the threats or say why
the team was disqualified or how it was connected to organized
crime.
   Tomlin did not immediately return a telephone call this morning.
   The FBI was notified of the alleged threat. However, FBI
spokesman John Kundts would not confirm nor deny any investigation.
   Tomlin said he he did not know of any arrests.
   Pop Warner football, for boys as young as 8, annually
disqualifies about 30 teams from its championships for various
reasons, Tomlin said. All records of teams disqualified in 1989
have been destroyed to protect those not involved, he said.
</TEXT>
