<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bulgaria 2ndLd-Writethru a0535 12-13 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0535,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists May Lose Dominant Role in Bulgaria</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with party deciding to abolish
its monoploly on power. CORRECTS that Balev not former interior minister.
Pickup 3rd pvs, `Since his...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Communist Party today decided
to ask Parliament to formally abolish the party's monopoly on power
by repealing constitutional clauses guaranteeing party supremacy,
state media said.
   Also today, the party expelled long-time leader Todor Zhivkov
along with his son and a close associate, the state BTA news agency
reported.
   The developments, which came on the third day of a key session
of the Communist Party Central Committee, are in line with new
leader Petar Mladenov's stated goal of reforming the party and
democratizing society.
   They also are in line with the rapid changes under way elsewhere
in the East bloc. In Czechoslovakia and East Germany, the Communist
Party has lost its constitutional guarantee of supremacy, and in
Poland the party lost its supremacy in elections.
   The state news agency BTA said the Communist Party's
parliamentary committee planned Thursday to introduce a motion to
abolish two constitutional paragraphs. One establishes the party as
``the leading force in society and in (the) state,'' and the other
says the party ``heads the construction of an advanced socialist
society.''
   The report did not elaborate.
   BTA offered no details on the ousting of Zhivkov, who was
replaced as party leader Nov. 10 and removed from the ruling
Politburo shortly afterward.
   Also expelled were Zhivkov's son, Vladimir, and Milko Balev, a
long-time Zhivkov associate, said BTA in its one-line dispatch.
   Since his removal from power the 78-year-old Zhivkov, who led
the country for more than 35 years, has come under increasing
attacks in the state media for alleged corruption and mismanagement.
   His son Vladimir, said to have enjoyed an opulent lifestyle
during his father's tenure, was removed from his job at the Central
Committee's culture department less than two weeks after his father
was toppled from his positions as party chief and state president.
   The Central Committe and Politburo have been purged repeatedly
since new party chief Petar Mladenov took power and embarked on a
course of reform similar to that under way in other East bloc
countries.
   Also today Peter Dyulgerov, the head of the official trade
unions, resigned from the ruling Politburo. He was seen as a
holdover from the Zhivkov regime.
   In an effort to appease Bulgaria's growing pro-democracy
movement, Mladenov has largely revamped the Politburo by bringing
in new people more likely to embrace reform.
   Dyulgerov reportedly said he was resigning as president of the
trade unions because they had recently declared their independence
from party domination. It was not clear whether he remained on the
policy-making Central Committee.
   Thousands of Bulgarians held a candlelight vigil outside party
headquarters Tuesday evening to emphasize their call for political
change.
   Several speakers denounced Zhivkov and accused the old
leadership of economic and political blunders.
   Politburo member Alexander Lilov repeated earlier calls for the
punishment of Zhivkov and his closest associates, and questioned
how the system could allow ``dictators'' to rule so long. Zhivkov
had been in power since 1954.
   Mladenov proposed Monday that the party relinquish its
consitutional monopoly on power and open dialogue with independent
groups. He also proposed that free elections be announced by May
1990.
   Also Tuesday the head of the Sofia City Committee, Georgi
Grigorov, likened the Communist Party to a sinking ship with a crew
``beheaded'' by decades of hard-line rule. He said the party was
``beheaded in terms of personnel.''
   ``Who are the young economists, who are the professionals, who
are our ideologists?'' Grigorov asked according to the state news
agency BTA, which carried excerpts from the closed-door session.
   ``Maybe we have these young people, but all of them were molded
in a similar way,'' he said. ``We put all of them on our ship,
which is sinking.''
   Boiko Dimitrov, who replaced Mladenov as foreign minister last
month, suggested that some people in the Central Committee still
linked to the Zhivkov government should resign.
   Evgeni Alexandrov, a Central Committee member and party
spokesman, told a news conference that it was ``more important that
the Communist Party members realize...that we are living in a
different age and elect a Central Committee that would act on that
(reform) policy.''
   He said several of the more than 30 speakers who took the floor
Tuesday criticized Zhivkov's rule and ``the administrative
bureaucratic system'' that allowed it. Others, he said, supported
Mladenov's call for dialogue with independent groups.
</TEXT>
