<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   12-13 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0921</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the country:
   Dec. 8
   Argus Leader, Sioux Falls, S.D., on the Philippines:
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino appears to have survived
another coup attempt, the sixth and most serious one she has
endured since taking office four years ago.
   This time, it took U.S. intervention to help her through. The
U.S. responded properly. But in the long run, intervention may
prove to be the catalyst that finally altered relations between the
United States and the Philippines.
   The United States would be wise to step up plans to move its two
important military bases from the Philippines: Subic Bay naval base
and Clark air base.
   Subic Bay and Clark are the largest U.S. bases on foreign soil
and are of strategic importance in the Southeast Asia region.
However, the bases are also becoming increasingly unpopular with
Filipinos.
   Aquino's recent actions will no doubt make the bases even more
unpopular in the Philippines. ...
   (A)t Aquino's request, U.S. jets flew air cover for loyalist
Philippine forces. The move helped prevent insurgents from
continuing their own air strikes and taking over Aquino's
government.
   U.S. fighter planes did not fire on rebel troops. But just the
fact the U.S. warplanes threatened Philippines people enraged many
Filipinos.
   President Bush and Vice President Quayle responded quickly _ and
properly _ to Aquino's request.
   The United States helped preserve a democratically elected
government and, in doing so, also protected U.S. military
interests. But Aquino had to have been desperate to make such an
extreme request.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 11
   Star Tribune, Minneapolis, on drug wars:
   Here's the way Colombia's troubles, on such horrendous display
lately, ought to get resolved.
   An Avianca airliner is blown up at the direction of a cocaine
cartel. Drug lords are probably behind the car-bombing that
shredded national police headquarters and surrounding buildings in
Bogota. President Virgilio Barco pledges to keep fighting the
cartels. Colombians, having lived under democracy most of this
century, resoundingly support the government. The cartels crumble.
   Unfortunately, the happy ending is wishful thinking. Violence on
a grand scale has visited Colombia periodically, as in the 1950s,
when hundreds of thousands died; it could return. And the cocaine
trade enriches Colombia's economy while prices for coffee, its
leading export, have fallen.
   The lesson is familiar: The best way for the United States to
help Colombia fight its drug war is to cut drug demand at home.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 8
   Tampa (Fla.) Tribune on the drug summit:
   (The) bomb blast in downtown Bogota that killed at least 42
peeple and injured more than 1,000 was a terrible tragedy. But even
more spine-chilling for Americans was a bomb attack that killed two
policemen in Cartagena.
   Cartagena is the tentative site of a mid-February drug
``summit'' of President Bush and Latin American presidents.
Cartagena _ or anywhere else in Colombia _ is too risky for the
U.S. President to be, for whatever purpose.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 9
   The Seattle Times on auto insurance:
   A long road through the courts lies ahead, but a ruling ... by
the California insurance commissioner is an overdue stab at the
inequities that permeate the auto insurance rate jungle.
   Under the ruling ... a California driver's address, gender or
marital status no longer can be considered by insurance companies
when setting rates. ...
   There is something intrinsically wrong in assumptions that a
single or divorced woman is a less responsible driver than a
married woman _ and should pay a higher rate. Or that men are worse
than women drivers. Or that a zip code alone makes a driver a
higher risk.
   Blanket rating by gender and marital status is as unconscionable
as rating by race. ...
   While outlawing the so-called ``ZIP code rating,'' (the ruling)
said insurers can consider population density, traffic density,
medical costs and litigation rates when establishing auto rates.
That makes sense. Insurers argue all those things are factored into
ZIP-code ratings, but it doesn't always work out that way.
   Insurance rate-setting is grossly unfair to too many people. The
industry argues it works fairly well for most. (The) ruling sends a
needed message: That's not good enough.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 7
   The Bulletin, Bend, Ore., on the ATV industry:
   Consumer safety advocates are feigning surprise and outrage at
the results of an undercover survey which found that more than half
of all-terrain vehicle dealers violate an agreement that they not
pitch adult-size machines as being safe for youngsters under the
age of 16.
   The government was asking for this trouble when it announced an
ill-considered consent decree with ATV manufacturers in 1988. The
agreement required ATV distributors to use their ``best efforts''
to assure that dealers do not sell adult-size ATVs for use by
children. ...
   The decree was based on the flawed assumption that manufacturers
could force ATV salesmen to dissuade adults from buying the
machines for youngsters. ...
   The fact is the much-ballyhooed consent decree signed a year ago
is an ineffective way to ensure that young people do not end up on
full-size ATVs. If the government truly believes these four-wheeled
vehicles are inherently dangerous for young people, then it should
make it illegal for those under the age of 16 to drive the machines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
