<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   12-13 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the machine.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 7
   The Leaf-Chronicle, Clarksville, Tenn., on the congressional pay
raise:
   The nearly 40 percent pay raise that members of the House voted
themselves in the waning days of the 1989 session probably won't be
much of an election issue next year.
   That's because the chairmen of the Democratic and Republican
parties as well as the congressional committee chairmen from each
party signed a non-aggression agreement. In part, the bipartisan
pact reads:
   ``The four of us have agreed to issue instructions to our staffs
that the vote on HR 3660 (the pay raise) is not an appropriate
point of criticism in the coming campaigns. Further we will
publicly oppose the use of this issue in any campaign in the 1990
cycle.''
   In other words, challengers to a House seat who had hoped to
make an issue of their opponents' vote for a pay raise will be
strongly urged by their own parties not to do so.
   This accommodating attitude between the two parties leads one to
wonder if the political cynics aren't correct: There no longer are
two distinct parties in Washington. They've been replaced by one
large group of incumbents whose primary aims are to keep getting
elected and reaping as many benefits as they can from the taxpayers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 8
   The Providence (R.I.) Journal-Bulletin on the S&amp;L scandal:
   The savings and loan scandal is so vast and complex that an
outraged public feels hard pressed to come up with a central
villain. ...
   M. Danny Wall will serve in that role for (now), but we should
bear in mind that the wings are crowded with bad guys. ...
   His agency (the Office of Thrift Supervision) should be put out
of its misery. ...
   As for other key villains, let's start with Rhode Island's own
Fernand St Germain, who as chairman of the House Banking Committee
pushed through legislation ... raising bank and S&amp;L deposit
insurance to $100,000 per account. That gave S&amp;L operators a big,
riskless treasure chest of capital with which to gamble.
   Then we have President Reagan's one-time chief of staff, Donald
Regan; members of Congress ... as well as the relentless lobbyists
of the U.S. League of Savings Institutions. All acted to protect
shady operators as deregulation slid into nonregulation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 11
   Delta Democrat-Times, Greenville, Miss., on helping people get
homes:
   President Bush's plan to assist the homeless, low-income
families and first-time buyers is, in far too many respects, more
of the same from Washington: Throwing money at a perceived problem
under the assumption that only government has the solution.
   Nonetheless, his $7 billion Home Ownership and Opportunity for
People Everywhere (HOPE) makes sufficient nods in the direction of
self-help and market concepts to make the plan palatable.
   One of the program's more farsighted elements could enable
millions of renters to become homeowners. About $1 billion would be
made available for tenants to convert and rehabilitate federally
subsidized housing into resident-owned cooperatives. ...
   The best element of the plan would provide vouchers to
low-income families to help them escape from public housing
projects and find living quarters more suitable to their needs.
Encouraging families with initiatives to solve their own housing
problems makes infinitely more sense than condemning them to grim
federal projects. ...
   Clearly, HOPE is not meant as a cure-all for the nation's
housing problems. But on balance it is a positive step in
addressing those problems in ways that encourage inividual and
collective enterprise.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 8
   The Phoenix Gazette on AIDS and civil liberties:
   It's been said that AIDS is the first politically protected
disease in history. There is some truth in that statement.
   Concern for the civil liberties of AIDS victims is appropriate,
but it ought not to be the central issue, nor should it stand in
the way of warning people at risk.
   It is difficult to understand how the spread of the disease can
be contained when no one, including those who are infected, knows
who is carrying the HIV virus.
   Some officials admit the problem and encourage voluntary testing
to control the spread of the disease. Unfortunately, voluntary
testing has limited effectiveness. For example, a study at Bellevue
Hospital in New York revealed that voluntary hospital screening
missed more than 85 percent of pregnant women infected with the
deadly virus.
   The fastest growing population of HIV-infected individuals is
I.V. drug users in inner-city minority populations.
   Perhaps it would be more useful to policy-makers if the
recommendations were put in order of priority.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 12
   The Daily Oklahoman, Oklahoma City, on communism and Fidel
Castro:
   Lest anyone think communism is dying, Cuban President Fidel
Castro has declared that the demise of Communist rule in Eastern
Europe will mean a shift of global alliances.
   Castro predicted the Stalinist regimes of China, North Korea and
Vietnam will join Cuba to uphold orthodox communism.
   That boast may be only a product of Castro's exaggerated
self-importance. But the fact remains that, while the Soviet Union
is allowing communism's strength to be sapped in Eastern Europe, it
continues to subsidize Cuba and the Marxist government in Nicaragua
to the tune of more than $6 billion a year.
</TEXT>
