<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   12-13 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0964</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: a year.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 8
   Las Cruces (N.M.) Sun-News on communism:
   A poll says half of all Americans think communism has failed and
is now on its deathbed.
   We think that possibly they may be half right. Marxism is
generally regarded as a failure. But what we perceive as the evils
of the communist system could persist under any number of new names.
   We should never forget that rivalries among nations spring from
deeper causes than ideology. The nations of Europe have been
warring for years over territory and economic advantage. Communism
was no more than a radical pipedream when the nations of Europe
blundered into World War I. National antipathies and rivalries
brought that on. And many of the same rivalries and antipathies
exist today.
   It is only human to expect that every favorable development on
the international scene means the millennium is being ushered in.
But history tells us not to expect it. History tells us that world
powers always tend to collide when their interests conflict. We
must never lose hope, but we must never expect too much.
Complacency, such as that reflected in the poll, could prove to be
our worst enemy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 10
   The News and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on Soviet-Vatican
relations:
   When Mikhail S. Gorbachev met with Pope John Paul II in the
Vatican, many commentators recalled Joseph Stalin's facetious
remark to Winston Churchill: ``How many divisions does the pope
have?''
   Yet the historic encounter between the head of the Roman
Catholic Church and the leader of the international communist
movement signified more than an acknowledgment by ... Gorbachev
that the pope's power cannot be measured in military terms. ...
   Gorbachev cannot, even should he wish to, rule through terror,
like Stalin. It is too late for that. ... He must respond to the
beliefs of the people of the Soviet Union.
   His predecessors were forced to come to an accommodation with
the Russian Orthodox Church, based on the latter's subservience.
... Gorbachev has had to come to an agreement with the pope that
acknowledges the spiritual power of the Catholic Church.
   The Soviet leader will also have to come to an accommodation
with the other divisions of religion, under the banner of Islam as
well as Christianity, as the world witnesses, not the death of God,
but the agony of communism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 10
   Los Angeles Daily News on defense spending:
   In anticipation of an enormous ``peace dividend'' from improved
superpower relations, members of Congress have already begun laying
plans for allocating the tens _ or even hundreds _ of billions of
dollars that are expected to be saved on defense. The idea is to
shift the windfall to domestic programs, from education to the war
on drugs. ...
   Congress, in its eagerness to fatten politically popular
domestic programs, may cut too much from defense and leave American
forces dangerously weakened in a world that still has its dangers,
whatever happens in East-West relations. ...
   To prevent a weakening of America's defenses, both (President)
Bush and Congress need to keep three important points in mind.
   _ Cut troops before anything else, but maintain enough strength
to protect American interests. (For example, cutting the 2.1
million active-duty personnel by 20 percent _ 420,000 troops _
would save about $12.5 billion alone in fiscal 1994). ...
   _ Don't be in a rush to weaken America's strategic capability.
...
   (D)espite the Soviet Union's paring of conventional forces, its
massive nuclear arsenal remains largely intact. ... (T)he United
States should avoid excessively deep cuts, because nuclear systems
tend to be a relatively cheap form of security.
   _ Don't cut research and development. The R&amp;D portion of the
defense budget _ less than 5 percent _ is arguably the best defense
investment the taxpayers can make. Even as Bush and Congress agree
to slash procurement for this and that weapon system, they must
make sure not to jeopardize America's lead in the technology of
warfare.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 9
   Watertown (Wis.) Daily Times on medical research:
   A study published in the ... Journal of the American Medical
Association is being hailed for showing for the first time
scientifically that being fit helps women live longer. In addition,
the study, on the lives of 10,244 men and 3,120 women, who have
been followed for eight to 18 years, was called persuasive
confirmation of earlier ones.
   On review, the figures and conclusions seem unimpressive. Of the
13,444 enrolled for investigation between 1970 and 1981 by
epidemiologist Steven Blair of the Institute of Aerobics Research
in Dallas, only 283 have so far died. That's a death rate of 21.2
per 1,000.
   It is not a large enough figure compiled over a long enough time
to demonstrate that those ``least fit,'' regardless of how this is
defined, are for men at 240 percent greater risk of dying and for
women 360 percent than those ``most fit'' in the long run.
   Agreed that this is true for the sample tested. Nonetheless, it
pushes statistics to the limits to say, as does William Haskell,
``This is a major study.'' In 20 years it may be but not yet.
   Dr. Haskell, a cardiologist at the Stanford University School of
Medicine and an expert in exercise physiology, acted as a
consultant to the Aerobics Institute.
   Fads exist in medical research as in other fields. We have an
impression that this is true of exercise physiology. Exercising and
keeping fit are certainly important, but other things in medicine
as well as in our culture and society are even more so.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
