<FIRST>r a PM-SilveradoSavings-Bush     12-13 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Silverado Savings-Bush,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>President's Son Denies Political Influence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's son Neil said he was never
asked to use his influence with regulators _ and would never have
agreed to do so _ in his three years as director of a Colorado
savings and loan that has since collapsed.
   A former federal bank regulator charged last week that
government officials delayed closing Silverado Savings and Loan
largely because the younger Bush was on the board of the
Denver-based thrift.
   But Neil Bush, who resigned from the board last year, says he
was never asked to influence regulators, according to today's San
Francisco Chronicle.
   ``Nor would I have if I had been asked,'' he said.
   Last week, James Moroney, a former staff analyst for the Federal
Home Loan Bank of Topeka, which supervised Silverado, said Bush's
presence was ``a material part of unconscionable delays in taking
over Silverado.''
   However, Moroney said he has no evidence that Bush exerted
direct pressure for preferential treatment.
   Asked if he thought his presence on Silverado's board influenced
regulators, Bush said: ``I wouldn't know. ... You would have to ask
regulators about that.''
   Bush, 34, stepped down from Silverado's board in August 1988,
immediately after the S&amp;L reported it was $200 million in the red
and four months before the state of Colorado took control of it.
   He told the Chronicle he resigned before his father's acceptance
of the Republican presidential nomination to ``avoid any appearance
of conflict of interest.'' Neither his father nor his father's
advisers pressured him to leave, Bush said.
   Regulators attributed Silverado's failure to ``substantial
dissipation of assets due to alleged violations of laws, rules and
regulations.'' The federal bailout of Silverado may cost taxpayers
$1 billion or more.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is examining the case to
determine whether to sue Silverado's officers and directors.
   Many analysts, including Colorado S&amp;L Commissioner David Paul,
attributed Silverado's collapse to a switch from traditional home
mortgages in favor of riskier securities.
   Bush, however, disagreed. ``My view is the institution had
acquired a portfolio of assets that suffered from a terrible,
depressed economy, not just in Denver, but throughout the
Southwest,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
