<FIRST>r a BC-AIDS-Stats     12-13 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AIDS-Stats,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Statistics On U.S. AIDS Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the latest statistics on acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in the United States, as reported by the
national Centers for Disease Control:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Number of Cases</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Total cases reported since June 1981: 115,158.
   Total deaths: 68,441, or 59 percent of all cases.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Transmission Categories</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Homosexual or bisexual males: 68,567, or 60 percent.
   Intravenous drug abusers: 23,722, or 21 percent.
   Homosexual male and drug abusers: 7,923, or 7 percent.
   Heterosexual cases: 5,447, or 5 percent.
   Transfusion or blood cases: 2,976, or 3 percent.
   Hemophilia patients: 1,151, or 1 percent.
   Children of parents with AIDS or at risk: 1,572, or 1 percent.
   Other or undetermined transmission cause: 3,790, or 3 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Age and Race</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Childhood cases (under age 13): 1,947, or 2 percent.
   Cases among whites: 64,618, or 56 percent.
   Cases among blacks: 31,514, or 27 percent.
   Cases among Hispanics: 17,885, or 16 percent.
   Cases among Asians or Pacific Islanders: 705, or 1 percent.
   Cases among American Indians or Alaskan natives: 156, or 0
percent.
   
   (NOTE: These statistics are through November 1989 and have been
rounded to the nearest whole percent. Cumulative totals are for
AIDS cases reported since June 1981, and include at least 75 cases
subsequently found to have occurred prior to that date.)
</TEXT>
