<FIRST>r w PM-PolandLoan     12-13 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland Loan,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. to Put Up $200 Million Toward Loan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will put up $200 million
toward a $500 million temporary loan for Poland as it awaits
economic help from the International Monetary Fund, the White House
announced today.
   Other, unspecified countries will contribute the remainder of
the funds, said deputy presidential press secretary Stephen Hart.
   He said the U.S. participation ``reflects support for Poland's
economic reform program designed to restore sustained growth.''
   Hart described the package as a short-term bridge loan, separate
from a $1 billion, multi-nation stabilization fund for Poland.
   The United States is contributing a $200 million grant to the
stabilization fund, intended to help put Poland's currency on a
sound footing.
   The loan, expected to run no more than six months, would be tied
to Poland's acceptance of conditions set by the IMF for a broader
assistance program.
   The United States would be repaid by Poland from money from the
IMF program and anticipated loans from the World Bank.
   Separately, Bush signed a bill last month providing $938 million
in assistance for Poland and Hungary over three years. Most of the
money is earmarked for Poland.
</TEXT>
