<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-USSIowa 3rdLd-Writethru a0571 12-13 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-USS Iowa, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0571,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truitt Says Hartwig Did Not Cause Iowa Explosion.</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 7 grafs new with Truitt testimony; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
It was.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petty Officer Kendall Truitt said today his
onetime friend and shipmate, Clayton Hartwig, did not cause the
explosion aboard the USS Iowa that killed 47 sailors.
   Testifying for the first time since the April 19 blast, Truitt
told members of the House Armed Services subcommittee on
investigations that the Navy's conclusion Hartwig probably caused
the explosion was ``ridiculous.''
   ``It's a big coverup, in my opinion,'' Truitt said.
   Hartwig did not know he was going to be the gunner's mate the
day of the explosion, raising doubts about whether he could have
planned the blast, Truitt said.
   In addition, the gunpowder had been stored in high heat and the
cans were not airtight, creating an explosion hazard, Truitt said.
   ``Clayton Michael Hartwig did not cause the explosion. I do not
think he committed suicide. I believe the report is very
misleading,'' Truitt said in his opening statement.
   Earlier in the hearing, a Naval Investigative Service official
said he made a mistake in waiting several weeks before entering the
inquiry into the Iowa explosion.
   ``It was my decision. I made the wrong decision,'' Robert Powers
told the House Armed Services subcommittee on investigations as the
panel held its second day of hearings on the battleship blast.
   Rep. Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., chairman of the panel,
questioned why it took the NIS until May 8 before it began its work
on the April 19 explosion.
   ``An awful lot of the evidence was thrown overboard by the time
you fellows got there on May 8,'' Mavroules said, his voice rising
in anger.
   ``There's no question about that,'' Powers responded.
   In his defense, Powers said the Navy initially considered the
explosion an accident, not a criminal act, and did not believe it
was necessary to call in the NIS, although the agency did offer to
help.
   Powers also said evidence was lost when sailors flooded gun
turret No. 2, where the explosion took place, to put out the fire
and later when the cleanup effort took place.
   ``The crime scene was vastly contaminated, no matter who was
going to investigate,'' Powers said.
   ``It would have been better if you had been there April 20,''
Mavroules said. Powers agreed.
   The Navy, in its Sept. 7 report, concluded that Hartwig,
depicted in psychological profiles as a suicidal loner, ``most
likely'' caused the blast by inserting some type of detonator
between bags of gunpowder in one of the ship's 16-inch guns.
   In testimony Tuesday, Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who oversaw
the Navy inquiry, said he was convinced that conclusion would
``stand up in a court of law.''
   But Milligan added that he cannot blame the 24-year-old gunner's
mate beyond a shadow of a doubt because Hartwig and all the
witnesses died in the explosion.
   However, Dr. Richard C. Froede, the armed forces medical
examiner who performed the autopsies on the sailors, told the House
panel he has not changed his opinion that the deaths were
accidental.
   ``As of this day, it has not changed,'' Froede said. ``I only
would make a change when I had more proof and all the
investigations were over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
