<HEAD>Gun Charges Dismissed Against Miss West Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr. ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRMONT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate today dismissed charges Miss
West Virginia Lisa Bittinger illegally waved a gun at a woman who
kicked in her car window and pulled the beauty queen's hair during
a scuffle.
   ``I don't think it's unreasonable for a person to reach for a
weapon when she's being threatened,'' Magistrice C. Frank Jones
said in dismissing the charge of brandishing a weapon, which
carries up to six months in jail and a fine of $200.
   Tammy Boyce, 23, of Fairmont, had filed the complaint against
Bittinger, 21, after the Nov. 7 scuffle on a downtown street.
Bittinger said the fight began when Boyce ran her car off the road.
   Boyce, during a hearing today, admitted reaching through the
sunroof of Bittinger's car, pulling her hair and screaming at her.
Boyce said she backed off and kicked out the window after Bittinger
pulled a gun.
   Boyce admitted that Bittinger has been dating a former boyfriend
of hers but said that she had stopped dating him three years ago
and that he did not figure into the fight.
   A hearing was scheduled for later today on Bittinger's complaint
against Boyce on battery and destruction of property charges.
   The beauty queen came under fire remarks deemed racist by some
people earlier this year upon her return from the Miss America
pageant, at which she failed to make the top 10.
   ``If it's political, it's not my fault,'' she said. ``If you
look at the to 10, it's quite obvious. It was one black, one
Korean, one Japanese, one hearing impaired, one kidney transplant,
and of course Texas and Florida were part of the top 10. It makes
you wonder.''
</TEXT>
