<FIRST>r w AM-BigNews     12-13 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big News,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake, Berlin Wall Top News Interest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disastrous San Francisco earthquake and
the crumbling of the Berlin Wall were the recent news stories that
loomed largest for Americans, a poll shows.
   Nearly three-quarters of people surveyed said they ``followed
closely'' the stories about the San Francisco tremor, according to
the Times Mirror News Interest Index.
   The tumult surrounding the opening up of East Germany was
watched intently by half of those interviewed, the survey found.
   On the other hand, Americans showed little interest in stories
about the resumption of hostilities in Nicaragua and state and
local election coverage. Only 13 percent said they closely followed
those stories.
   The index was based on a telephone survey of 1,230 adults taken
between Nov. 9-12. The estimated margin of error is plus or minus 3
percentage points.
   Only the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger _ closely
watched by 80 percent of those surveyed _ attracted more attention
than the earthquake, officials said. The survey has been taken
regularly over the last four years.
   Despite the fact that the quake interrupted the World Series,
the survey found weak overall interest in that event, with 23
percent saying they followed the story.
</TEXT>
