<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Costs     12-13 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Costs,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latest Damage Estimates from Hurricane Raised to Nearly $6 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent assessments from rural residences
and condominiums have raised damage estimates for South Carolina
from Hurricane Hugo to $5.9 billion.
   The increased estimate is up from the $4 billion preliminary
estimate reached in November by the state Office of Economic
Research.
   The new report, compiled by the same office, listed damage to
homes at nearly $3 billion as of Dec. 6. Damage in the budget
board's report, reflecting assessments through Oct. 27, listed
residential damage at only $539 million.
   Damage estimates of the agriculture industry, which includes
timber, remained unchanged at $1.4 billion.
   The agriculture industry is ``one of the hardest areas we're
going to have to get back on its feet,'' Gov. Carroll Campbell said
Tuesday during a meeting in which the report was released.
   The latest assessment was based on additional information from
the American Red Cross and county assessors and damage figures from
condominum complexes, the report said.
   The new estimate also includes $700 million in damage reported
by commercial and industrial enterprises that may have included
operating losses, said William C. Gillespie of the Division of
Research and Statistics.
   The report also listed the following damage estimates: $250
million for the Charleston Naval Base; $200 million for public and
private utilities; $150 million for government facilities; $125
million for automobiles; $50 million for Shaw Air Force Base, and
$13 million for the South Carolina Ports Authority.
   Insurance companies, the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
the Small Business Administration and state agencies have already
issued $2.1 billion in aid to hurricane victims, Gillespie said.
   The report was issued to the Hugo Recovery Commission, an
eight-member panel appointed by Campbell to assess the economic
impact of the hurricane and its effect on agriculture, tourism,
forestry, education and the infrastructure.
   The commission is charged with recommending initiatives to
stimulate economic development and enhance industrial recruitment
and expansion in the wake of the storm. A report is due by early
March.
   Hugo killed 29 people in the state when it slammed into South
Carolina on Sept. 21.
</TEXT>
