<FIRST>r a PM-RadioactiveWaste 1stLd-Writethru a0599 12-13 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radioactive Waste, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0599,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Experts Hemmed in By Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with tour over, workers surrounded;
PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `A dispatcher ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAYLOR, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials touring a site under
consideration for a radioactive waste dump had to be escorted two
miles on foot today after demonstrators formed a human chain to pen
them in their cars, a protest leader said.
   Members of Citizens Against Radioactive Dumping also rushed
cars, trucks and tractors to block roads leading to the site after
field teams from the Low-Level Radioactive Waste Siting Commission
and several sheriff's deputies arrived, said Taffy Rook, a
spokeswoman for the protest group.
   Sheriff Lee Price called off the tour and preliminary testing
about 11 a.m. because of the demonstrations, said Jeff Gebhardt,
co-chairman of the protest group.
   About 150 anti-dump protesters clustered around the commission's
two cars, preventing them from leaving the site, Gebhardt said.
After 30 minutes, one group of state workers abandoned their car
and were escorted off the site by deputies who said they would come
back for the others, he said.
   The wooded area is in a dairy region about 50 miles south of
Syracuse.
   Protesters also had staked out a second site under consideration
near Taylor in case teams went there.
   A dispatcher for the Sheriff's Department said no one was
available to comment because most personnel were at the site.
   Protesters had also camped out overnight at three potential dump
sites in Allegany County, preparing to block state officials from
beginning inspections and tests on land there. Authorities said
state officials were not in the county this morning.
   ``I hope that people don't go outside the law,'' commission
spokeswoman Susan Baranski said Tuesday. ``The courts have made it
clear that the commission has the right and responsibility to do
this.''
   Anti-dump groups in Allegany and Cortland counties have vowed to
prevent the testing at the proposed dump sites, saying their
protests would be nonviolent but that they expected arrests.
   ``There will be civil disobedience,'' said Sally Campbell of the
Allegany County Nonviolent Action Group. ``Whatever they try to do
we're going to be out there to stop them from doing it.''
   The five sites were chosen by the commission in September. Under
federal law, states must have a place to store low-level
radioactive waste by 1993.
   The commission plans to complete soil testing and other
evaluations by spring. It will then narrow down the number of sites
to two or three for more comprehensive tests.
</TEXT>
