<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paramedic says he was fired for
arranging to give away teddy bears to children being taken to the
hospital, but an ambulance service spokesman said today the firing
was related to job performance, not stuffed animals.
   Paramedic Chuck Brady Jr. was dismissed Nov. 28 and two other
paramedics were suspended by Kevin Raun, ambulance service director
for Apple Valley, Lakeville and Farmington.
   The three said they were told by Raun that they had circumvented
his authority when money was solicited for the teddy bears without
his knowledge. Beecham and Adams supported the idea but did not
actually solicit money, the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch
reported today.
   An American Legion post donated $1,000 to the paramedics' union
after an appeal from Brady, the St. Paul newspaper reported.
   Raun declined to comment on the matter, but Bill Holton,
chairman of the ambulance service board that upheld Brady's firing,
said the dismissal ``had nothing to do with the teddy bears.''
   ``The dismissal had to do with job performance,'' he said.
Holton would not give specifics of Brady's job performance.
   Holton said the ambulance company has in the past given away
stuffed animals to children being taken to hospitals. ``So, the
program by itself is a very good program and one we had intended to
do again this year,'' he said.
   Brady said that on his most recent job evaluation he received
satisfactory or above-average ratings and no negative remarks.
