<SECOND>PM-Dad Sentenced,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Gets Jail Sentence for Slapping Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEARCY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor says a two-year prison sentence
was appropriate for a man who slapped his 4-year-old son for
sniffing gasoline to get high.
   Richard Lewis Vardaman, 42, of Georgetown pleaded guilty to
battery and was sentenceed last week by Judge Cecil Tedder.
   ``It was a serious case of child abuse,'' Prosecutor Chris Raff
said Monday. ``It was not normal discipline. I think the proof
justified the sentence. The message is clear _ child abuse would
not be tolerated.''
   Defense attorney Bill Mills said the sentence was too harsh but
that his client probably won't appeal it.
   Vardaman caught his son and another boy sniffing gas from a can
near their home in May and paddled both boys, Mills said. But twice
the next day, Vardaman found his son sniffing gas, the defense
attorney said.
   ``He slapped him once on each side of the face that time,''
Mills said.
   Vardaman and his wife took the child to a hospital because the
boy was ``acting drunk,'' Mills said. The boy seemed normal by the
time they reached the hospital, but the emergency room nurse and a
doctor noticed the bruises on his face and contacted police.
   Photos of the boy taken at the hospital were shown to the judge.
``They looked pretty bad,'' Mills said. ``The child has a ruddy
complexion and his face was puffy in the picture.''
   Mills said a representative from the state Human Services
Department testified that it was an isolated case of abuse.
