<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Police     12-13 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Police,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland Closes Police Unit That Read Mail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 700 secret police who were designated
to read other people's mail have been reassigned, and telephone
tapping has been virtually banned, the Solidarity-led government
announced Wednesday.
   The mail-reading unit was closed and its positions are among
1,800 in the Interior Ministry that were most recently transferred
to the regular police force, said spokeswoman Malgorzata
Niezabitowska.
   The police counterintelligence unit also has been cut, by 150
jobs, to a ``necessary minimum,'' she said.
   Previous cuts to the secret police force, including elimination
of the department that monitored churches and religious
organizations, freed up 7,000 jobs for crime fighting, she said.
   New regulations ban installing bugging devices except ``in
extraordinary circumstances, every time with the approval of the
Interior Minister,'' Ms. Niezabitowska said at a news conference.
   ``You are not on this list, unless you work for an intelligence
service,'' she told her audience of foreign correspondents.
   The 8,800 Interior Ministry positions were transferred to the
police forces, but there are still 12,000 vacancies in the regular
police, the spokeswoman said.
   The dismantling of the secret police and shifting resources to
the regular police force for crime-fighting were key priorities of
the government of Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   The Interior Ministry still is run by a Communist, Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczek, but he has cooperated in the change of priorities and
announced the disbanding of the ZOMO riot police who had symbolized
government suppression of dissent.
   Poor pay and low public esteem have cut the ranks of the police
force, according to authorities who also report a rapid rise in
crime.
   Gen. Zenon Trzcinski, the militia's chief commander, said this
week the burglary rate has grown the most, from 40,000 in 1979 to
100,000 in 1988 and an estimated 150,000 this year.
</TEXT>
