<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mexico-Drugs     12-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mexico-Drugs,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strains Easing Between U.S., Mexican Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Drug Enforcement Administration official
says the strain between U.S. drug agents and Mexican officials
stemming from the 1985 killing of DEA agent Enrique Camarena has
been eased by Mexico's prosecution of those involved.
   ``I think we've seen very positive signs from the new
administration (in Mexico) since last December, particularly the
president,'' Acting Deputy DEA Administrator Terrence Burke said in
an interview.
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, who took office a
year ago, has made vigorous efforts to change his country's image
as a haven for drug dealers and corruption by jailing traffickers,
arresting corrupt officials and seizing tons of drugs.
   The successful prosecution and sentencing in Mexico of Rafael
Caro Quintero, 37; Ernesto Rafael Fonseca Carrillo, 56; and 10
other men involved in the killings of Camarena and Mexican pilot
Alfredo Zavala Avelar has boosted DEA confidence that those charged
in Mexico will be brought to justice, Burke said.
   ``I think this is an extremely positive sign,'' Burke said after
Caro Quintero, Fonseca and the others were sentenced Tuesday to 40
years for their roles in the killings. Prison time for related
convictions brought Caro Quintero's total sentence to 116 years and
Fonseca's to 144.
   Fernando Arias, a spokesman for Mexican Attorney General Enrique
Alvarez del Castillo, said Caro Quintero and Fonseca would have to
serve 74 and 53 years respectively because of time remaining from
previous sentences.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday that
the United States is ``pleased that those responsible for these
brutal murders have been brought to justice.''
   ``These convictions further demonstrate the resolve of the
Salinas administration in its fight against drug trafficking,''
Boucher said. ``We look forward to continued cooperation of the
Mexican government in the battle against this common threat to the
national security and well-being of both our countries.''
   The U.S. support of Mexican actions follows years of tension
illustrated by U.S. contentions that Mexican authorities had
allowed Caro Quintero to escape to Costa Rica, where he was
captured. In an effort to pressure the Mexican government for
action, the U.S. Customs Service virtually blocked the border by
conducting full searches of all Mexicans trying to enter the United
States.
   It was revealed in July that Caro Quintero and Fonseca had
bribed Mexico City prison officials to let them live in luxury
accommodations they had built inside the prison. The two were then
transferred to maximum-security facilities.
   Camarena, 37, was kidnapped Feb. 7, 1985, in Guadalajara; Zavala
Avelar was kidnapped a few days later. Their bullet-riddled bodies,
showing signs of torture, were found March 5, 1985, wrapped in
plastic bags and buried in shallow graves on a ranch 60 miles
southeast of Guadalajara.
   The Camarena killing ``was from the beginning and has continued
to remain'' a highly emotional issue for DEA agents, said Burke.
The DEA never pulled back in Mexico, even immediately after the
Camarena killing, he said.
   ``We did just the opposite,'' he said. ``We sent additional
agents in and our signal at that time was, `You kill a DEA agent
and we'll hound you to the grave'.''
   ``We're just continuing to move ahead in our investigation until
we're satisfied that every single person who was responsible for
his death is brought to justice either in the United States or in
Mexico,'' Burke said.
   Another person charged in connection with the Camarena case,
Ruben Zuno Arce, 59, the brother-in-law of former Mexican President
Luis Echeverria, was arrested Saturday by DEA agents at Los Angeles
International Airport as he got off a plane arriving from Mexico.
   Zuno Arce pleaded ``absolutely innocent'' Monday to charges that
he plotted to torture and kill Camarena. Co-defendant Juan Jose
Bernabe Ramirez is charged with the felony murder of a federal
agent, among other things. Three other people were convicted in
1988 in Los Angeles on charges connected to the Camarena killing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
