<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Violence     12-13 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Violence,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police, Soldiers Battle Blacks; 400 Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and soldiers battled
Wednesday with more than 8,000 blacks protesting the prosecution of
neighbors for not paying electric bills. Police said about 400
people were arrested and 12 injured, including six officers.
   The clash, one of the largest in South Africa this year,
occurred when blacks began a march toward the courthouse in Ermelo,
120 miles east of Johannesburg, despite having been denied
permission for the protest.
   Police headquarters said marchers began throwing stones after
officers tried to disperse them with tear gas and stun grenades.
Officers then fired birdshot, injuring at least six people,
including a child, police said.
   The five wounded adults were held in custody to face charges of
public violence, while 397 people arrested at the courthouse were
released with a warning, police said.
   While the clash was in progress, government offices in Ermelo's
black township were firebombed, police said.
   The marchers were protesting the start of court proceedings
against 88 residents of the township for not paying electric bills.
   Earlier Wednesday, police reported three more deaths in
factional fighting between rival black groups near Durban, bringing
the death toll around the port city this month to 71. Law and Order
Minister Adriaan Vlok said 380 police reinforcements were bening
sent into the area's embattled shantytowns.
   Several dozen other blacks have been killed elsewhere in Natal
Province this month in an escalation of a political power struggle
that has claimed about 2,500 lives in three years.
   Police also reported more violence related to a six-week strike
by more than 20,000 black employees of the state transport company,
which runs rail and harbor operations nationwide. Five coaches were
set afire and a constable was thrown to his death from a moving
train near Kathlehong, east of Johannesburg.
   South African Transport Services said it fired 2,477 more
strikers, raising to 15,094 the number dismissed during the strike.
The strikers are demanding an increase of their minimum monthly
wage from $225 to $560.
   The main combatants in the Natal violence are the United
Democratic Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition, and
Inkatha, 1.5 million-member political group headed by Zulu leader
Mangosuthu Buthelezi.
   Both groups oppose apartheid, but they have been battling each
other for supremacy in Natal since late 1986.
   The United Democratic Front, which is aligned with the outlawed
African National Congress guerrilla movement, favors protests,
strikes and sanctions to pressure the white-run government.
   The relatively conservative Buthelezi does not support such
measures and has been criticized by the front for participating in
the black homeland system. Both groups concede they do not have
full control of all their supporters.
   Hundreds of residents in the townships have fled their homes,
and some are living with white friends or employers in Durban.
</TEXT>
