<SECOND>PM-Brandley Appeal, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0573,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Court Overturns Murder Conviction in Racially-Tinged Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with comment from defense attorney,
no comment from district attorney; PICKS UP graf pvs, `Among examples ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas appeals court today overturned the
murder conviction of a black high school janitor who contended his
prosecution in the 1980 rape and slaying of a white teen-ager was
racially motivated.
   The prosecution of 38-year-old Clarence Brandley was marked by
``blatant unfairness,'' the court said in granting the nine-year
Death Row inmate a new trial. But the court did not directly
address the question of racism.
   Brandley was convicted of murdering 16-year-old Cheryl Fergeson
at a high school. His first trial ended with a hung jury. An
all-white jury found him guilty in a second trial.
   ``I'm trying to hold back the tears,'' Brandley, a former high
school janitor, said from prison in Huntsville today. ``It's made
my Christmas. It's been a long time. It's something I didn't think
was coming.''
   Defense attorney Mike DeGeurin said he would ask for Brandley's
release on bail while prosecutors decide whether to seek a new
trial. If the court agrees and Brandley makes bail, ``he'll be out
before Christmas,'' DeGeurin said.
   Montgomery County District Peter Speers did not immediately
return calls for comment on the ruling and on whether he would
pursue a third trial.
   The appeals court, in a 6-3 opinion, said the state's
investigative procedures lacked ``the rudiments of fairness.''
   Among examples cited by the court were that another janitor who
testified for the state allegedly was threatened by a Texas Ranger,
and that the state suppressed information that could have
implicated someone else.
   ``The principles of due process embodied within the United
States Constitution, must not, indeed cannot, countenance such
blatant unfairness,'' wrote Judge David A. Berchelmann Jr.
   In 1987, after a 10-day hearing, retired District Judge Perry
Pickett recommended that Brandley get a new trial, ruling that the
previous two had been tainted with racism.
   Brandley's attorneys have offered evidence that police and
prosecutors had set out to prove that Brandley, the only black
janitor at the school, was guilty rather than seeking the real
killer.
   During the 1987 hearing, Pickett was told that the district
attorney and trial judge met secretly on strategy against Brandley.
   Prosecutors have denied Brandley was the subject of racial
discrimination.
   ``Thank you, Jesus!'' Brandley's mother, Minnie Ola Brandley,
said when she heard the court's decision. Mrs. Brandley, who lives
in Conroe, said she is confident a new trial will prove her son's
innocence.
   ``I think they have evidence to turn him lose,'' she said. ``My
child didn't do that. We're hoping and all we do can is pray.''
</TEXT>
