<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Everglades 1stLd-Writethru a0607 12-13 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Everglades, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Everglades-Expansion Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new to include wetlands bill; picks up graf 4 pvs,
The 107,600-acre.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush signed legislation today
clearing the way to expand Everglades National Park and ordering
the Army Corps of Engineers to restore the natural flow of water to
the Florida ``river of grass.''
   He also signed a measure providing federal matching funds to
help preserve critical wetlands in the United States, Canada and
Mexico. He said the bills will help achieve his campaign goal of
``no net loss of wetlands.''
   Bush signed the North American Wetlands Conservation Act in a
ceremony in the Roosevelt Room after signing the Everglades measure.
   The wetlands act will provide more than $70 million over four
years to help purchase and preserve wetlands, which serve as vital
feeding areas for ducks and other migratory fowl.
   Bush said the dwindling population of ducks ``is largely
attributable to the steady loss of wetland areas that we've
experienced.'' The United States has been losing wetlands at the
rate of nearly 400,000 acres a year.
   Bush does not favor a ban on development projects that destroy
wetlands, but wants any development offset with an equal amount of
acreage restored as wetlands.
   ``Even in times of serious fiscal constraints, we can still meet
our highest environmental priorities and this is one of mine,''
Bush said in signing the Everglades legislation.
   The 107,600-acre expansion will be undertaken in cooperation
with the state of Florida, which will donate 35,000 new acres to
the federal park. The government estimates it will cost $40 million
to acquire the rest of the new acreage, with Florida havin agreed
to pay 20 percent of the costs.
   The Everglades, the second largest national park in the 48
contiguous states, are home to 13 endangered species, but problems
with the flow of waters have harmed the habitat for both birds and
alligators.
   ``The woodstork, heron, ibis, egret and roseate spoonbill have
all declined dramatically over the years,'' Bush said. ``The
Florida panther, the alligator and many species of fish are
declining.''
   ``The Northeast Shark River Slough, the river of grass through
southern Florida, has been both too shallow and too deep,'' the
president said. ``Through this legislation that river of grass may
now be restored to its natural flow of water.''
   Congress first enacted legislation in 1944 to create Everglades
National Park, and it was dedicated by President Harry Truman in
1947.
   Efforts to drain and reclaim wetlands from the 1880s through the
1930s drastically reduced the natural flow of water through the
Everglades. The Army Corp of Engineers Central and Southern Florida
Project in 1948 helped reduce the damaging flow of salt water and
provided flood control, but left some areas with too much water and
others with too little.
   The new legislation will require the corps to modify the Central
and Southern Florida Project at an estimated cost of $45 million.
   It also puts limits on the use of waterboats in the Everglades,
with current users allowed to keep using the craft on existing
routes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
