<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0620 12-13 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Launch Delayed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with details from NASA statement,
date swap with Titan commercial launch, picking up at the 6th graf previous,
`During a 10-day.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA said Wednesday it had delayed
the pre-Christmas launch of space shuttle Columbia at least two
days because of lagging work at the launch pad.
   A statement said the new date of Dec. 20 is ``success
oriented,'' meaning that any minor new problem could slip the
liftoff to the 21st.
   It said additional time is needed to validate systems on
recently renovated launch pad 39A and to prepare Columbia.
   ``We feel confident about readiness for a pre-Christmas
liftoff,'' said William Lenoir, NASA's associate administrator for
space flight.
   NASA spokesman Karl Kristofferson said a lot of small problems,
many associated with new pad facilities, had put launch crews
behind schedule.
   If liftoff slipped to Christmas Eve or Christmas Day, it
probably would be postponed a few more days to free workers for the
holiday.
   With the change, the shuttle swapped launch dates with a Titan 3
commercial rocket that had been scheduled for liftoff on Dec. 20.
The Titan, which is to boost British and Japanese communications
satellites, was rescheduled for 7:20 p.m. EST Monday.
   During a 10-day mission, Columbia's five astronauts are to put a
Navy communications satellite into orbit and recover a science
satellite before it falls to Earth. The satellite has been in orbit
nearly six years and is expected to re-enter the atmosphere in
February.
   The flight duration will equal the longest shuttle mission to
date and will be a stepping stone for even longer flights as
Columbia is being modified to stay aloft for 16 days and later for
28 days.
   Loading of propellants for Columbia's in-flight propulsion
systems and auxiliary power units began a day late Monday because a
faulty connector on an electronics box had to be replaced.
   Once the fueling began, the launch pad had to be cleared of all
non-essential personnel because it is dangerous. That prevented
workers from making up lost time in other areas.
   Work was running late even before the connector problem because
of difficulties working with new systems on a mobile launch
platform being used for the first time and with the launch pad,
which recently underwent a two-year, $50 million refurbishment,
receiving 130 modifications.
   In announcing a Dec. 18 launch date, NASA cautioned last week
that the flight might have to be delayed a day or so because of the
new systems.
   Astronaut Dan Brandenstein will command Columbia's crew. The
other crew members are pilot Jim Wetherbee and mission specialists
Bonnie Dunbar, Marsha Ivins and David Low.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
