<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-DeKlerk     12-13 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-De Klerk,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profile of F.W. de Klerk</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even militant anti-apartheid
leaders acknowledge that President F.W. de Klerk, during four
months in power, has moved faster toward political reform than any
of his predecessors.
   But leading activists remain deeply suspicious of him,
suggesting he wants to ease international pressure on South Africa
without forfeiting the white minority's ultimate hold on power.
   De Klerk, 53, is viewed as an affable pragmatist, earnest but
not charismatic.
   He has pledged to phase out discrimination, and has not shied
away from confrontations with right-wing whites who want to
maintain strict apartheid. However, he maintains his long-standing
belief that South African politics must be conducted along racial
lines.
   De Klerk was a lawyer before entering Parliament in 1973. From
1978, he held a series of Cabinet posts, and in 1982 took on the
powerful job of National Party leader in the Transvaal, South
Africa's most populous and wealthiest province.
   P.W. Botha, who had headed the government since 1978, suffered a
stroke in January and de Klerk was elected to replace him as
overall leader of the party. Botha remained in the presidency until
August, when he quit after the Cabinet failed to support his
objections to a planned diplomatic trip by de Klerk to Zambia.
   De Klerk comes from a long line of National Party politicians,
going back to his great-grandfather, who was a senator.
</TEXT>
