<DOCNO> AP891213-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Mandela     12-13 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Mandela,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profile of Nelson Mandela</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unheard and unseen by the
public since 1962, Nelson Mandela is nevertheless the most
respected leader among South African blacks, who consider him the
embodiment of their quest for political freedom.
   Mandela, 71, has rejected repeated government offers to free him
if he would renounce violence. He said the government should
renounce violence, end apartheid and unban the African National
Congress.
   Mandela was regarded by many blacks as the paramount leader of
the ANC, although the highest office he held before it was banned
in 1960 was deputy president-general. He was the first commander of
its military wing, ``Spear of the Nation,'' which he helped form in
1961 to engage in a sabotage campaign.
   He subsequently toured Africa, receiving military training and
explaining the ANC's cause. He was arrested after his return, in
1962, and sentenced to five years' hard labor for leaving the
country illegally and inciting blacks to violate the law by
striking.
   In 1963, while Mandela was imprisoned near Cape Town, police
uncovered the ANC's underground headquarters on a farm near
Johannesburg and seized documents outlining plans for the guerrilla
campaign. In June 1964, he and seven co-defendants were sentenced
to life in prison.
   Mandela contracted tuberculosis at Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town
and was hospitalized in August 1988. After recovering, he was moved
to Victor Verster prison farm in the wine-growing town of Paarl,
where he has been allowed to meet with a steady flow of relatives
and political colleagues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-Acidophilus     12-13 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Acidophilus,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Warns Against Using Acidophilus Capsules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FDA is urging consumers not to use an
over-the-counter food supplement distributed by a Pennsylvania
company because some bottles contain capsules with potentially
fatal levels of stannous fluoride.
   Vitamin Specialities Co. of Wyncote, Pa., has asked its 22
retail stores in New York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania to recall
acidophilus capsules with lot number 069296 and has notified 140
mail-order customers, the Food and Drug Administration said.
   The product is manufactured by Vita-Pure, the FDA said in a
release.
   According to the product label, the acidophilus capsules supply
``friendly bacteria to the intestinal tract'' and help restore and
maintain the mucous membrane that lines the stomach and intestines.
   The company began the recall in late October after two consumers
complained of vomiting and flu-like symptoms after using the
product, the FDA said. However, FDA said it was concerned that many
consumers may still be unaware of the problem because only a small
number of bottles were returned.
   An FDA analysis found that smaller capsules were mixed with
slightly larger acidophilus capsules. The smaller capsules were
found to have an average 784 milligrams of stannous fluoride.
   Stannous fluoride, used in toothpaste, is safe in small amounts.
However, a 784-milligram dose could cause convulsions in an adult
and could be lethal for a small child, the agency said. Five
capsules could kill an adult.
   High doses of stannous fluoride can cause gastrointestinal upset
and vomiting, which could limit the amount ingested and the adverse
effects, the FDA said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
