<DOCNO> AP891213-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baker     12-13 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Appeals to Rich Nations to Make Good on Aid Promises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III
appealed to the world's wealthiest countries Wednesday to make good
on their promises of aid to Poland and Hungary so the new leaders
in Eastern Europe can ``put food on the table and goods on the
shelves of stores.''
   Baker described the plight of Poland as winter approaches as
severe.
   ``Pledges alone aren't enough,'' he told a meeting of two dozen
foreign ministers as they committed their treasuries to a
coordinated assistance program valued at up to $6 billion in the
next several years.
   Most of the aid takes the form of investment and trade credits
not to be paid out immediately. Included in the assistance is a
$200 million U.S. contribution to a $1 billion stablization fund
for Poland.
   Additionally, Baker announced the United States would provide
$200 million to a 10-nation $500 million ``bridge loan'' for Poland
that is to help tide the country past the Christmas season until
the International Monetary Fund declares it qualifies for a
comprehensive aid program.
   Except for the $200 million, which comes out of a U.S. Treasury
fund, Congress last month appropriated $938 million in U.S.
assistance.
   Baker, a former U.S. Treasury secretary, has taken the lead
within the Bush administration in encouraging Eastern European
countries to adopt market economies. As a lure, he dangles U.S. aid.
   Just before coming to Brussels, Baker went to East Germany for
talks with reformist Prime Minister Hans Modrow. He promised the
administration would consider economic support if the country
continued to revise its economy and carried out a pledge to hold
multiparty elections in May.
   Baker told the foreign ministers that ``the multiplying effects
of people power are creating a new East-West equation. Ordinary men
and women are peacefully asserting their basic human rights on a
scale unimagined at the start of the year.''
   But, Baker went on, ``It is our task to support this courageous
reform effort. After the streets emplty of demonstrators, after the
people select new leaders, after governments become the servants of
the people, after all this _ the economies must put food on the
table and goods on the shelves of stores.''
</TEXT>
