<SECOND>AM-CT--School Grenades,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenades Found in Connecticut Junior High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five teen-agers have been arrested for
bringing four military hand grenades to junior high school, police
said.
   The boys, ages 14 and 15, were also suspended after authorities
discovered the grenades Monday and Tuesday at Rogers Park Junior
High School.
   The state police bomb squad determined the grenades, about 20
years old, were used by the military to simulate battle conditions.
While the grenades do not break up and spread shrapnel when they
explode, they could kill someone, said Youth Bureau Detective
Russell Benjamin.
   He said the grenades could be less stable and more dangerous
because they are old.
   Police said the grenades were stolen from a Danbury residence,
but police do not know specifically where.
   Principal William Spielberg said a student alerted school
officials to the first grenade, and the school called police.
   Benjamin said the boys would be referred to the Danbury Superior
Court juvenile division. Two were charged with sale of explosives;
the other three were charged with possession. Their names were not
released because of their ages.
