<FIRST>r a AM-SovietDefector     12-13 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Defector,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Actress Says She Left Homeland to Pursue Dream in America</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MP3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of a Soviet acting troupe who
defected to the United States said Wednesday she loves her homeland
but came to America for more freedom.
   ``I love the people of the Soviet Union and I love the people
here. But I must ... tell you I have one dream. Without this dream,
I can't live,'' said Larisa Firsova, a 24-year-old actress with the
Central Children's Theatre of Moscow.
   Speaking in broken English and at times through an interpreter,
Firsova declined to elaborate on her dream, saying it is considered
bad luck to discuss such matters. She did acknowledge that it
includes becoming an American actress.
   She said she has applied for political asylum and it is ``almost
granted.''
   ``I was told that it's all a matter of paperwork and I should
just wait a few days,'' said Firsova, who is staying with a couple
in the area.
   She declined to be specific but said she sought political asylum
based partly on matters having to do with her husband, Vadim
Firsova, also an actor.
   The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service has said it
can't comment on the case because of confidentiality rules.
   Firsova didn't show up Monday as members of the troupe assembled
at their hotel to head for the airport. The group had been
performing as part of an exchange program with the Children's
Theater Company of Minneapolis.
   The actress appeared at the news conference in the office of
U.S. Sen. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Min., wearing snow boots, gray slacks
and a Minnesota Vikings sweatshirt.
   Members of Boschwitz's staff presented her with an American flag
that the senator had asked to be flown over the U.S. Capitol as a
token of welcome to her.
   The actress said she would attempt to help her husband emigrate
as soon as possible.
   Firsova said that, while her family did not specifically know
that she would defect on this trip, they knew of her desire to
leave the Soviet Union and supported her.
</TEXT>
