<FIRST>r w AM-US-CentralAmerica     12-13 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Central America,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Assails Salvadoran Rebels for Rejecting Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department criticized the Salvadoran
rebels Wednesday for rejecting a peace proposal by Central American
presidents, calling the decision a ``tragic, missed opportunity''
to end the bloodshed.
   The five presidents, meeting in Costa Rica earlier this week,
appealed to the FMLN rebels ``to immediately and effectively cease
hostilities ... and rejoin the previously initiated process of
dialogue.''
   A communique issued by the presidents called on the insurgents
to use the dialogue to achieve their demobilization and expressed
explicit support for the Salvadoran government.
   The rebels angrily denounced the communique, ruling out
demobilization. They said the communique gives ``unconditional
support to the principal violator of human rights in the region'' _
the Salvadoran government.
   The insurgents said they cannot be demobilized because they
constitute a ``legitimate force with popular support in the entire
Salvadoran territory.''
   State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the rebel
statement represents ``a tragic, missed opportunity to end the
bloodshed which has plagued El Salvador.''
   He contrasted the insurgents' stand with that of President
Alfredo Cristiani, who has expressed a willingness to reopen talks
with the FMLN once they end their attacks in civilian areas.
   Discussing the Nicaraguan aspect of the peace process, Boucher
noted that the presidents called for the renewal of cease-fire
talks between the Sandinistas and the Contra rebels. He said those
discussions broke down last month when the Sandinistas unilaterally
walked out.
   ``If the Sandinistas wish to further the goals of the peace
process, including voluntary demobilization, repatriation and
reintegration of resistance members under secure and democratic
conditions, they should renew their direct talks with the
resistance,'' he said.
   He added that the Sandinistas should also take immediate steps
toward further democratization, especially ending the harassment
and violence against opposition candidates and supporters and
freeing political prisoners.
   In a concession to the Sandinistas, the presidents also called
on the United States to transfer to a United Nations-Organization
of American States commission U.S. funds being provided to the
Contras for food, clothing, shelter and medical supplies.
   Boucher said U.S. officials would consult closely with Central
American, United Nations and Contra officials to determine how best
to carry out that aspect of the presidents' communique.
   ``The important thing is that we believe these people (the
Contras) continue to need food, clothing and medicine. That's
exactly what we are providing,'' Boucher said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
