<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-Pesticides     12-13 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Pesticides,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slightly More Raw Foods Free of Excess Pesticides, FDA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 96 percent of raw foods sold in the
United States in 1988 had no pesticide residues or had levels
within the legal limit, the Food and Drug Administration said
Wednesday.
   That's a slight increase over 1987, when 95 percent of the foods
sampled did not contain illegally high levels of pesticides.
   The FDA's analysis also showed that 61 percent of the foods
sampled in 1988 had no pesticide residues, compared with 57 percent
the previous year.
   Of the nearly 4 percent of foods sampled in the 1988 analysis
that contained pesticide residues above the levels allowed, most
involved residues for which the Environmental Protection Agency has
set no tolerance level, the FDA said.
   The FDA sampled 18,114 imported and domestic food products for
its latest report, about 25 percent more than in 1987.
   The analysis found more imports contained higher-than-allowed
pesticide residues than domestic foods. Of the 10,475 import
samples analyzed, 6 percent contained excessive residues, while
about 2 percent of the 7,639 samples of domestic foods exceeded the
tolerance level or contained residues of pesticides not permitted
for use on that product, the FDA said.
   The study covered 256 pesticides.
   Vegetables had the highest proportion of excessive pesticide
residues at 5.6 percent. A breakdown shows that 7 percent of
imported vegetables fall into that category compared with less than
3 percent of domestic products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
