<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FilmAwards     12-13 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Film Awards,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Driving Miss Daisy' Takes Top Prize in D.W. Griffith Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' Bruce Beresford's movie
based on Alfred Uhry's Pulitzer Prize-winning play, has won the
D.W. Griffith Award for best movie of 1989.
   Morgan Freeman, who portrays the elderly chauffeur of an
eccentric Southern Jewish matron in the movie, was named best
actor, and Michelle Pfeiffer received the best actress prize for
her role as the singer who perks things up for Beau and Jeff
Bridges in ``The Fabulous Baker Boys.''
   The annual awards, given out by the National Board of Review,
were announced Wednesday.
   ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' which also stars Jessica Tandy as Daisy
Werthan and Dan Aykroyd as her son, is the story of the 25-year
relationship between Miss Daisy and her chauffeur woven into the
fabric of change in the New South.
   Other winners were:
   _ Supporting Actor: Alan Alda, ``Crimes and Misdemeanors.''
   _ Supporting Actress: Mary Stuart Masterson, ``Immediate
Family.''
   _ Director: Kenneth Branagh, ``Henry V.''
   _ Foreign Film: ``Story of Women.''
   _ Documentary: ``Roger and Me.''
   _ Made for Television Movie: ``Roe vs. Wade.''
   _ Miniseries: ``Lonesome Dove.''
   The National Board of Review is one of the nation's oldest
motion picture associations, established in 1909. It is an
organization that recognizes film as an art form rather than a
business or simply entertainment.
   The awards ceremony will take place in New York on Feb. 26.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PhoneRescue     12-13 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Rescue,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Distance Telephone Surveyor's Call Saves Would-Be Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A random call by a phone surveyer working
the night shift in Iowa rescued an Arizona man from an apparent
suicide attempt.
   Carol Edwards, 39, was making random calls nationwide Monday
night when she triggered an answering machine at a Tempe home.
   The slurred voice of a man said, ``My car's in the garage and so
am I,'' said Juan Perez, a Tempe police spokesman.
   ``I was quite shocked at first,'' said Ms. Edwards. ``At first I
thought maybe it was I joke. I was hoping it was.'' She conferred
with her supervisor, Chuck Sitter, at Frank N. Magid Associates, a
consulting and research firm, in Marion, Iowa.
   ``We called the Tempe Police Department and they said they were
happy we did,'' said Sitter, 27.
   Within minutes of Sitter's call, Officer Alison Miller arrived
at the Tempe home and found it seemingly unoccupied although a
cassette recording repeatedly was playing the country-Western song
``I'll Be Missing You.''
   ``I thought I heard a car and went straight for the garage. It
was dark in there and I turned on a flashlight. I saw a man
kneeling beside the driver's door. His head was slumped but his
hands were hanging onto the window,'' Ms. Miller recalled, adding
that the car's fumes were ``pretty strong, like it had been running
for awhile.''
   The man apparently was attempting suicide by carbon-monoxide
poisoning and also appeared to have overdosed on drugs, said Perez.
   Police believe the 42-year-old man was having ``family problems,
marital problems,'' Perez said.
   The man was given emergency room treatment, then transferred to
a psychiatric hospital, where officials declined to discuss the
matter Wednesday.
   ``What are the chances of this person in Iowa calling a random
number in Tempe and getting a recording'' describing a suicide
attempt? Perez asked.
   ``And what are the chances of listening to the recording and not
hanging up,'' he said of Ms. Edwards. ``A lot of people hate
talking to recorders.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MoneyBags     12-13 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Bags,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Female Santa Says Money Giveaway `Was Fun'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cheerful Bostonian who flabbergasted bar
patrons by handing out money _ $100 bills, $50s and $20s _ shrugs
off the uproar she created.
   ``I'm just me. It's like I had this extra money, so I just
started giving it out,'' said Judy Kelly, 53, who describes herself
as the daughter of ``an industrial tycoon'' and a Chicago native.
   ``It was fun.''
   ``People keep asking why,'' Ms. Kelly said, smiling up at
reporters during a news conference Tuesday.
   ``It just happened. ... It's not like I was blowing the rent
money.''
   She said she was thrilled by the ``smiles that came back. ... It
was great; it was great.''
   By some estimates, she gave away $5,000 in the lounge of a motel
near Midway Airport before police asked her to stop. Her generosity
was causing traffic jams as would-be recipients stampeded to the
scene.
   The officers, called by concerned tavern owners, also advised
her to save a little money for a rainy day.
   ``I promised the police I would stop giving money away,'' she
said Tuesday, but ``I can still do things quietly.
   ``I think people should maybe read the dictionary and look up
the word `give.'''
   Until the news conference, Ms. Kelly had eluded the spotlight
since her giveaway late Saturday and early Sunday. And she did not
return telephone calls Wednesday.
   What prompted Tuesday's resurfacing?
   Hotel manager Lola Andreas at the Holiday Inn-Midway, where Ms.
Kelly was staying, asked for a contribution a children's Christmas
party the hotel sponsors for the state Department of Children and
Family Services.
   ``She said she didn't have any money, but that she could help
with publicity,'' Ms. Andreas said.
   As Ms. Kelly predicted, several reporters turned out for her
news conference at the hotel.
   ``We're using you,'' she said, teasing.
   After her performance as Mrs. Claus, Ms. Kelly was arrested
early Sunday on a misdemeanor disorderly-conduct charge after her
Jaguar stalled near the airport and she was reported trying to
direct traffic and creating a ruckus.
   Ms. Kelly was released on her own recognizance, pending
evaluation at the Bobby Wright Comprehensive Community Mental
Health Center, where officials found no reason to hold her, and
Barbara Morgan, shift coordinator at the city's Human Services
department. She said agency workers took Ms. Kelly to a motel
before dawn Sunday.
   She is to appear in court Jan. 26 on the municipal charge, which
carries a penalty of from $5 to $500, city officials said.
   Neighbors were perplexed back home in Boston, where Ms. Kelly
has lived for 10 years in a neighborhood of narrow streets with
Italian shops and restaurants.
   ``This is unbelievable, what's going on,'' said an upstairs
neighbor, Nancy, who asked that her last name not be used.
   ``I was shocked,'' said Robert Lynch, owner of the J&amp;B Variety
Store around the corner. ``She's never done anything like this
since I've known her. She's a normal, average person.''
</TEXT>
