<DOCNO> AP891213-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     12-13 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Tigers Oust Rival Militia, 60 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTICALOA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful rebel group negotiating
with the government for political power ousted a rival militia
Wednesday in a battle that killed an estimated 60 people, mostly
militiamen, residents said.
   In a three-pronged attack launched shortly before midnight
Tuesday, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam surrounded the town
of Batticaloa, residents said.
   One young woman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
rebels came down the coast road from the lagoon and the jungle late
Tuesday night. By midmorning Wednesday, she said, the shooting had
stopped.
   By sundown Wednesday, Batticaloa's General Hospital had received
26 bodies.
   ``Only one was a Tiger,'' a hospital official said. ``The rest
were from the other side.''
   Like many other people in this town of 60,000 people, he was
reluctant to speak the name of the ``other side.'' But they
acknowledged they meant the Tamil National Army, a group set up
shortly before the Indian peacekeeping forces withdrew from
Batticaloa late last month.
   ``Most of them, according to parents, were forcibly conscripted
to fight the Tigers,'' one hospital employee said.
   The Sri Lankan government has accused departing Indian troops,
at the behest of pro-Indian Tamil groups, of training and arming
the Tamil army, which the Colombo government has outlawed.
   The Indian government, which sent peacekeeping soldiers to Sri
Lanka two years ago to put down the Tamil rebellion, has denied
allegations it created the Tamil National Army.
   In addition to the 26 bodies at Batticaloa General Hospital,
three more were seen along the road leading into town.
   Young Tiger guerrillas, most in their teens and carrying shining
new AK-47 assault rifles, claimed at least 50 members of the Tamil
National Army were killed in the battle.
   Well-placed residents in Batticaloa estimate the total death
toll at 50 to 60. One said it might be as high as 90.
   ``The bodies have been pouring in all day and still they are
arriving,'' the hospital official said. ``More will come when it is
light again and people can find transport.''
   The last of the bodies to reach the hospital as darkness fell
lay on the floors of vans parked inside the hospital's front gate.
At least three had their hands tied behind their backs. In the
fading light, their wounds were not clearly visible but all
appeared to have been shot in the head or neck.
   ``My husband. I have lost my husband,'' wailed Nathivathany, in
between sobs that shook her entire body.
   Nathivathany's husband, Thayaparan, was one of the young men
whose bodies lay in a heap in the back of the van. Friends said the
young couple had been married only a short time.
   But elsewhere in the town, there was an air of calm, with
teen-age Tigers standing along the streets in twos and fours.
   Red-and-white banners erected by the Tigers proclaimed ``great
heroes days'' in the Tamil language.
   ``The Tigers were very polite when they came into town after the
shooting,'' said an English-speaking woman. ``People gave them tea
and said we had dreams for the liberation of Batticaloa.
   ``Eighteen months ago people of Batticaloa compained about our
Tamil militia _ including the Tigers _ saying they had been forced
to contribute money, provide free food and even their own
television sets,'' said the woman, also speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   But as the Tigers tried to enter the political mainstream, they
also had embarked on a public relations campaign, one that seems to
be working. The Tamil National Army does not enjoy the same support.
   Batticaola is 135 miles east of Colombo and is one of the two
eastern districts where India pulled out 10,000 of its troops in
the past two months. India has said the remaining 26,000 troops
will be out of Sri Lanka by Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
