<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Casolo 5thLd-Writethru a0663 12-13 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Casolo, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0663,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Casolo Released from Prison into Custody of U.S. Ambassador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Casolo released from prison,
details. Pickup 5th, `I am ...' Minor editing thereafter to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American church worker
accused of storing weapons for leftist rebels in El Salvador was
released from prison today into the custody of the U.S. ambassador.
   President Alfredo Cristiani said Jennifer Casolo, 28, of
Thomaston, Conn., was released after 2{ weeks in jail because of
insufficient evidence and would be deported. He said she would be
asked to remain a witness in the case.
   ``If the evidence against her becomes sufficient, she will be
summoned to return for trial,'' Cristiani told a news conference,
although he acknowledged little could be done to force her to
return.
   Shortly afterwards, reporters staking out the Ilopango prison
saw Ms. Casolo leave in a black Cadillac with U.S. Ambassador
William Walker. The Cadillac was escorted by a caravan of Jeeps.
There was no opportunity for Ms. Casolo to comment and no
indication where the caravan was headed.
   Cristiani said he thought Ms. Casolo probably had in fact
cooperated with rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, who launched a major urban offensive in San Salvador last
month.
   Cristiani said she was being released only because legally there
was not enough evidence to hold her.
   ``I am morally convinced that Miss Casolo is guilty,'' Cristiani
said. He said she was being freed only because of lack of evidence.
   The president said he had not been pressured by the government
of the United States to order Ms. Casolo's release. The United
States is a key financial supporter of the rightist government in
its war with the rebels.
   Ms. Casolo was charged with acts of terrorism, possessing
weapons of war and criminal association. She denied the charges.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said earlier today he had been
told in telephone conversations with Salvadoran officials,
including Cristiani, that Ms. Casolo would be released and expelled
from the country by Thursday afternoon.
   Cristiani ``informs me that the judge in her case has ultimately
concluded the charges against Jennifer were not fully supported by
the evidence, and that she could not thus be fairly prosecuted
under Salvadoran law,'' Dodd said in a statement released by his
office.
   Ms. Casolo went to El Salvador in 1985 to work for Christian
Education Seminars, a group that organizes tours for Americans to
learn about the 10-year-old civil war.
   Ms. Casolo and two Salvadoran friends were arrested Nov. 26
after a police raid on her house in San Salvador. From the walled
garden behind the house, police said, they uncovered 103 mortar
grenades, 213 blocks of dynamite, 405 detonators, 150 feet of
slow-burning fuse and 21,945 rounds of ammunition for Soviet-made
automatic rifles.
   Ms. Casolo is to be expelled from El Salvador, according to the
agreement reached with Salvadoran officials, Dodd said.
   On Tuesday, El Salvador's ambassador to the United States,
Miguel Angel Salaverria, said Ms. Casolo would be released if she
provided police with information about the people from whom she
rented her house.
</TEXT>
