<HEAD>Wrong Number Nets Drug Dealer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Mope' is cq in 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What appeared to be a prank call to the
police turned out to be a very wrong number for a drug dealer.
   ``It was kind of a humorous situation,'' said Ken Carter of the
Narcotics Division of the state's Department of Public Safety.
``Here we have this mope that's calling us and he has no idea of
who he is talking to.''
   Public Safety Commissioner Gene Shepard said it all began when
the phone rang in the agency's narcotics division.
   ``The guy said something like, `Is Al there?' and our agent
said, `No, this is John,''' said Shepard.
   The suspect then went on to describe a drug transaction that had
apparently been arranged with the mysterious Al. At first agents
thought it was a nuisance call, but the suspect became insistent,
Carter said.
   ``It proceeded to the point where we decided this guy was
serious, he really wanted to sell drugs,'' said Carter. ``So we
started with the role-playing.''
   After the agents went through the requisite haggling, a
transaction was set up allowing undercover agents to purchase a
small amount of marijuana.
   The buy was set up for Tuesday in Des Moines, and two men were
charged with delivery of marijuana. Carter said the transaction
involved about four ounces of the drug.
   `Once in a while, we have an interesting day around here,'' said
Shepard. ``It's not every day you arrest two people just on a wrong
number.''
</TEXT>
