<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     12-13 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed and Third Injured In Attack on Security Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gang armed with guns and
bombs attacked a security post on the Irish border Wednesday,
killing two British soldiers and seriously injuring a third, police
said.
   The attackers escaped unhurt after the attack at Derryard, an
isolated checkpoint about two miles from the Fermanagh border with
County Monaghan in the Irish Republic, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary said.
   No group claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell on the Irish
Republican Army. The group is fighting to end British rule of
Northern Ireland and unite the mainly Protestant province with the
predominantly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   ``Quite clearly several terrorists were involved in this,'' said
a senior police officer, who by custom was not identified. ``It was
a well-staged attack.''
   Police said two soldiers died and another was taken to Erne
Hospital, Enniskillen. An army spokesman said the injured soldier
was treated for shrapnel wounds.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said nine
soldiers and one police officer were on duty at the checkpoint.
   The latest deaths brought to 12 the number of British soldiers
killed in Northern Ireland in 1989. Before the attack, 60 people
had been killed in sectarian violence in Northern Ireland this
year, 21 one them members of security forces.
