<FIRST>r a AM-PetsSeized     12-13 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pets Seized,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dog and Cat Returned To Owner In Rent Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iris the dog and Whitehill the cat, seized
last week in a dispute over back rent, were back home Wednesday,
freed by a judge who decreed they were being held hostage _ sort of.
   ``The nightmare is over!'' 31-year-old Lynell Zelenka said as
she hugged Iris and Whitehill.
   Civil Court Judge Thomas Early on Tuesday ordered the release of
Zelenka's 7-year-old Saluki and 11-year-old mixed-breed cat, which
were seized Dec. 6 along with her car as security for the overdue
rent.
   Her landlord, John Chambers, says Zelenka owes him $12,000,
which he agreed to let slide while she sued over a back injury.
Chambers claims she recently settled the lawsuit and didn't tell
him.
   But Zelenka, who admits owing Chambers $6,000, ended up with
only $750 after paying legal fees and medical expenses, Early was
told Tuesday.
   Early said he hasn't decided how much rent Zelenka owes, but
ruled that Zelenka's pets have value only to her and, unlike a cow
or a horse, would bring no money if put up for sale.
   The judge said taking Iris and Whitehill was a form of hostage
taking. ``Why should the dog and the cat be pulled into the middle
of this thing and deprived of the love of their master?'' he said.
   Chambers' attorney said he will appeal.
   Back home at the apartment, Zelenka said the first order of
business was a bath for Iris. She said she rode the bus to the
Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals every day to take the
dog a daily ration of home-cooked chicken.
   ``I told her I'll spend the rest of her life making this up to
her,'' Zelena said.
</TEXT>
