<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Leningrad     12-13 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Leningrad,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famed Composer Calls on Leningrad Leader to Quit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A famed composer told Parliament on Wednesday that
the new Leningrad party chief is an opponent of President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's reform and urged him to quit.
   Rodion Shchedrin took the floor on the second day of the
Congress of People's Deputies to criticize a widely publicized
meeting in the Soviet Union's second city last month that many
Soviets believe showed Leningrad party leader Boris V. Gidaspov to
be a conservative opponent to the president.
   ``I am of the opinion that the meeting was aimed at halting the
revolutionary processes of perestroika in the country, and there
were plenty of threats hidden by fig leaves of eulogisms addressed
against our leader and his supporters,'' Shchedrin said.
   ``I think that your post is incompatible with what you have
done,'' he said, addressing Gidaspov.
   Gidaspov was chosen Leningrad party leader this year to replace
Yuri F. Solovyev, who was embarrassed in elections to the Congress
in March. Solovyev had no opposition but still lost because he
received less than 50 percent of the vote.
   Gidaspov made an innocuous speech at the outdoor meeting, which
was shown on Leningrad TV and later on a nationwide news program,
saying mainly that it was time to stop talking about reform and
start acting.
   However, other speakers and some of the banners at the rally
gave Soviets a different picture. Some speakers sharply attacked
cooperatives, the small privately held businesses that are an
important feature of Gorbachev's economic reform. Banners called
for top Communist Party officials to be brought to account for the
country's difficult political and economic situation.
   Gidaspov denied he was leading the Leningrad party organization
toward opposing Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``To make such statements before the high assembly that are
based only on personal impressions seems to me not reasonable,'' he
said.
   ``We consider the work of the Leningrad party and public
organizations as work aimed at speeding up perestroika,'' he said.
   Gidaspov had come in for more heat about the outdoor meeting at
a ``countermeeting'' of 40,000 rank-and-file Leningrad Communists
last week. When he tried to make a conciliatory speech to that
meeting, he was drowned out by shouts of ``Resign! Resign!''
</TEXT>
