<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     12-13 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>27 Killed in Shootout in Bangladesh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided the hideout of a
self-proclaimed Moslem saint whose followers captured one of their
colleagues, and at least 27 people died in the ensuing gunbattle
Wednesday, officials said.
   The captive officer and three other policemen were among those
killed in the fight that began late Tuesday in Pakundia village. It
ended at dawn Wednesday with the arrest of Matiur Rahman, a former
army major who now calls himself a Pir or saint, police officials
said.
   Twenty other people were wounded, said the officials in
Pakundia, about 50 miles north of Dhaka in Kishoreganj district.
   They said the raid was ordered to free the policeman held
captive by Rahman's supporters in the hideout, located in a
sprawling building complex. The policeman had gone to the hideout
Monday to investigate reports of ``anti-social activities by the
Pir's followers,'' an official said.
   He did not say what the anti-social activities were but it was
believed to be a reference to gambling and selling drugs.
   Rahman's 16 disciples also were arrested and 30 others
surrendered after the raid by about 700 policemen, they said.
   Earlier, at least 12 people were reported killed, but a search
team found 15 more bodies inside the hideout Wednesday, the
officials said.
   Self-proclaimed Pirs, who profess to cure physical ailments and
prescribe ways to becoming rich, abound in Bangladesh, a nation of
110 million people. About 88 percent of them are Moslems.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, a former army general, is a
follower of a popular god Hashmatullah, who claims to have
thousands of disciples. Hashmataullah is based at Atroshi in
Faridpur district, 40 miles west of Dhaka.
   Also Wednesday, about 2,000 journalists across Bangladesh went
on a 16-hour strike to protest a government ban on a daily
newspaper that supported anti-government strikes, the journalists'
union said.
   The ban on the Bengali-language Dainik Millat, which has a
circulation of 10,000, was imposed Tuesday.
   The government says frequent opposition-sponsored general
strikes are crippling the economy, and estimates the loss at about
$78 million for a day's work stoppage.
   Opposition parties demand Ershad's resignation, accusing his
administration of being corrupt and autocratic.
   Ershad, 59, has refused to step down and maintains he is willing
to hold elections without handing over power to a caretaker
government.
   Ershad took power in a bloodless coup in 1982. He resigned from
the army in 1985 and a year later was elected to a five-year
presidential term in national balloting that political opponents
and foreign observers said was tainted by widespread fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2006EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATO     12-13 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Chief Hails Baker Proposals on Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner
said Wednesday he was ``fully in line'' with new U.S. proposals for
reshaping the Western alliance in an era of a reduced security
threat from the Soviet Union.
   U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III advanced the
political proposals Tuesday in Berlin.
   Woerner spoke with reporters on the eve of a key meeting of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization. He said NATO foreign ministers
will discuss at their year-end meeting Thursday and Friday the
political and economic changes in East Europe, particularly in East
Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   Woerner said he strongly supported Baker's call for NATO to set
up an arms control verification staff, which would help Western
nations monitor compliance with future disarmament accords.
   ``We cannot and will not ignore that the historic change we see
all around us will have an impact on NATO itself,'' he said.
   The alliance ``must continue to provide security and stability
in a time of turbulence and ... must also be increasingly an
instrument that can shape political change,'' the NATO chief added.
   He said the ministers will be trying to encourage the reforms
under way in the East as part of efforts to fashion ``a new
architecture of Europe, which will allow the division of our
Continent to be peacefully overcome.''
   The meeting will cap weeks of high-level talks among the 16 NATO
nations. President Bush met with other alliance leaders last week
to brief them on his Malta discussions with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The alliance nations have been discussing ways to make sure NATO
keeps pace with the changes in the East. Bush and Baker have talked
about a New Europe and a New Atlanticism.
   In his Berlin speech, Baker said NATO's political role should be
enhanced as its military work diminishes.
   He said an agreement between NATO and the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
to reduce the buildup of conventional, or non-nuclear, weapons in
Europe was ``the keystone of this new security structure.''
   Woerner said NATO was determined to wrap up a conventional arms
treaty with the seven Warsaw Pact nations next year.
   The United States has been pressing for an agreement by June.
   Questions rose about the pace of the negotiations because of
Greek opposition to a compromise plan to exclude a Turkish port
from the area covered by the treaty. The snag has held up NATO
plans to quickly put on the negotiating table in Vienna a draft
treaty for bargaining with the Warsaw Pact.
   Woerner said work was continuing to reach a timely accord
despite the delay.
   He said the ministers ``will give further impetus'' at their
meeting to negotiations on the conventional armed forces in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
