<FIRST>u w AM-Biden-Drugs     12-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biden-Drugs,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biden Urges $1 Billion to Develop Anti-Narcotics Medications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee
called Wednesday for a $1 billion drive to develop anti-narcotics
medications, saying the Bush administration neglected that weapon
in its war on drugs.
   ``Like AIDS, drug abuse is a national health emergency that
threatens thousands of American lives and damages the fabric of
American society,'' Sen. Joseph R. Biden, D-Del., told a news
conference.
   ``While no one expects to find a magic pill that eliminates drug
addiction, expert researchers agree that we could be doing more _ a
lot more _ to develop new treatments,'' he said.
   Biden said the nation should set goals of making a
cocaine-blocking medicine available by 1997 and providing
``pharmacotherapeutic treatment-on-demand'' for heroin and cocaine
addicts by the year 2000.
   Biden said he would introduce legislation that would launch a $1
billion medications development program over the next decade,
provide drug companies with incentives to develop new treatments,
streamline government safety evaluations, call on the surgeon
general for a report on the issue and designate top priority
research areas.
   These top priority areas would include the use of
``pharmacotherapeutic'' agents on pregnant women and their fetuses,
treatments for new drugs that will appear in the 1990s and
interaction between heroin and cocaine addiction.
   Biden unveiled a report from the committee staff that pinpointed
eight new medicines that might be used to treat addiction. Some
reduce drug craving, while others merely substitute one addiction
for another. One actually blocks the pleasure addicts feel as a
result of taking their drug.
   The report said slow Food and Drug Administration procedures
combined with pharmaceutical industry inaction and insufficient
action by the administration to limit resources devoted to
searching for new treatments.
</TEXT>
