<FIRST>r w AM-D'Amato-Ethics     12-13 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D'Amato-Ethics,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Brief Asks Wider Ethics Probe of D'Amato</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Green, whose complaint led to the
congressional investigation of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, asked the
Senate Ethics Committee Wednesday to widen its probe to include a
HUD grant and D'Amato phone calls to a federal prosecutor.
   Green, a Democrat who lost the Senate race to D'Amato, R-N.Y.,
in 1986, also said potential witnesses in the investigation should
be subpoenaed to testify under oath.
   ``There are a lot of people with information who will be scared
to speak out against D'Amato, given his reputation for
ruthlessness, unless the committee puts them under oath, which in a
sense protects them,'' Green said in an interview. He also said
D'Amato should be put under oath.
   D'Amato said later he would testify before the committee ``in
any way in which they request. And I'm delighted to make myself
available and to cooperate with them in every way and any way.''
   At a Manhattan news conference on another issue, D'Amato said he
was unaware of Green's latest move, ``but it wouldn't surprise
whatever it is, and I'm delighted that we'll have an opportunity to
have all of Mr. Green's charges reviewed by the Ethics Committee.''
   He said he was confident he would be exonerated.
   Green, who currently runs the Democracy Project, a liberal
research organization in New York, said he filed the additional
papers because the committee's special counsel, Henry Schuelke III,
asked him for ``any new information, insights.''
   The phone calls Green referred to were made by D'Amato to
then-U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in 1984 and 1985. On one
occasion, D'Amato passed along a plea from the Rev. Louis Gigante
for a reduction in the sentence of his brother, Mario Gigante, a
convicted loan shark who also has been reported to be an officer in
the Genovese crime family.
   D'Amato has said he was merely trying to help the priest, a
constituent.
   In the other call, made at the behest of the late criminal
lawyer Roy Cohn, D'Amato urged Giuliani to review murder charges
against an unnamed defendant. Giuliani has said he later concluded
D'Amato was referring to Paul Castellano, then boss of the Gambino
crime family.
   D'Amato has said he was unaware of the identity of the defendant
in the latter case and that he was trying to save Giuliani's office
from being embarrassed if the charges didn't stick.
   The HUD grant was $500,000 from a discretionary fund controlled
by then-Secretary Samuel Pierce. The money was awarded to a
coalition of black ministers, including the Rev. Al Sharpton, whose
National Youth Movement was to use the money to rehabilitate a
building into a drug treatment center. The grant came one month
after the group endorsed D'Amato for re-election in 1986.
   Sharpton, who is under indictment accused of stealing $250,000
from his organization, has said, ``If we hadn't endorsed D'Amato, I
don't think (Bishop Frederick D. Washington) would have had access
to D'Amato and any funding.''
   D'Amato spokeswoman Zenia Mucha has said that the senator did
not know of Sharpton's role in the project. After Washington died
last January, the project was dropped.
   Green filed his original complaint against D'Amato last July,
and followed up with an addendum in September. He has charged that
D'Amato misused his influence to steer federal favors to political
contributors and friends.
</TEXT>
