<HEAD>Michigan GOP Chairman To Join Quayle's Staff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spencer Abraham, chairman of the Michigan
Republican Party, Wednesday was appointed deputy chief of staff to
Vice President Dan Quayle.
   Abraham, 37, will act as Quayle's chief political liaison with
GOP leaders nationwide and will oversee management and operation of
the vice president's office, a spokeswoman said. The appointment
takes effect Jan. 9.
   Abraham will retain his position as Michigan GOP chairman, which
he has held since 1983, but he will relinquish day-to-day party
operations to Executive Director David Doyle.
   When he took over, the party faced a $450,000 debt from lengthy
reapportionment battles and the 1982 election, in which Democrats
siezed control of all statewide offices. Supporters credit Abraham
with erasing the debt and improving the state party's technical and
organizational strength.
