<FIRST>u w AM-Aerospace-Education     12-13 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerospace-Education,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aviation, Space Industries Short On Skilled Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace-Aerospace Impact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies that build planes, spacecraft and
related equipment have too few skilled workers, as U.S. schools lag
behind in science and math, an industry study concluded Wednesday.
   A survey of companies belonging to the Aerospace Industries
Association showed 67 percent of the companies suffer from a
shortage of scientists and engineers and 55 percent report a
shortage of production workers. More than 80 percent said they
expect more shortages in the future.
   The problem is made more serious by rapid changes in the
technology needed in aerospace industries, by a lack of young
people preparing for jobs with a technological focus, by the
failure of women and minorities to choose such careers and by the
fact that U.S. students generally are doing poorly in science and
math, said the AIA study.
   The survey was compiled from responses of 30 major corporations,
including nine of the top 10 Defense Department contractors and
eight of the top 10 National Aeronautics and Space Administration
contractors.
   Key shortages are occurring in jobs that involve computers,
advanced materials, electro-optics and artificial intelligence, the
study said.
   Among concerns raised by aerospace companies are that employees
have insufficient hands-on experience, that schools put too much
emphasis on theoretical models, that there is a lack of emphasis on
design projects in college, and that people with advanced degrees
are academically oriented and have to adjust to the faster pace of
industry.
   Some companies also complained of deficiences in verbal and
team-building skills among high-level professionals.
   Aerospace companies are responding to the problem by giving
almost 40 percent of their total corporate contributions to
education up to the high school level, with large amounts going to
colleges and universities for research and development projects,
the report said.
   A November report by the American Association of State Colleges
and Universities concluded that the nation faces a crisis in
science education, with schools producing an inadequate number of
science and engineering graduates.
</TEXT>
