<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     12-13 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter to Investigate Nicaraguan Political Campaign Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said
Wednesday he will investigate a political campaign battle between
government opponents and supporters this week that left one person
dead and more than 20 injured.
   ``We hope to determine the causes of this violence,'' he told
reporters.
   Carter arrived at the head of a delegation of observers, invited
by both the leftist Sandinista government and the opposition, to
monitor the process leading to national elections Feb. 25. It was
his second trip here this year.
   Sandinistas and leaders of the National Opposition Union accused
each other of inciting the Dec. 10 riot in Masatepe, 30 miles south
of Managua, in which a Sandinista campaign office and a private
home were looted and two vehicles were burned.
   It was the worst outbreak of violence in the 2-month-old
election campaign for president, vice president, a new legislature
and municipal authorities nationwide.
   The Center for Democracy, a Washington-based observer group,
blamed the Sandinistas. A report by the Organization of American
States said the riot was deliberately provoked but that its
observers could not determine who was responsible.
   Carter said he is pleased that so far all sides are intent on
having free and fair elections.
   Accompanying Carter was his wife Rosalynn; former Sen. Daniel
Evans, R-Wash.; and former President Daniel Oduber of Costa Rica.
For the next three days they will travel throughout Nicaragua,
talking to OAS and United Nations observer groups about the
electoral process.
   Carter said he would like to see the money approved by the U.S.
Congress for Nicaragua's Contra rebels channeled through a
commission set up to oversee their demobilization.
   He stopped short of calling for demobilization of the Contras
before the elections, saying, ``My hope is there will be no need
for a Contra presence after the elections.''
   Carter was commenting on this week's summit by five Central
American presidents that called for disbanding the Contras and
leftist Salvadoran guerrillas.
   The Bush administration and Contra leaders want the Contras to
remain in place as a fighting force until after the elections to
make sure President Daniel Ortega keeps his promise the electoral
process will be open and fair.
   The five presidents agreed Aug. 7 in Tela, Honduras, to call for
demobilization of the Contras by Dec. 5 in exchange for Ortega's
promise of electoral fairness. But Contra leaders ignored the
deadline and Central American leaders passed it by after violence
re-escalated in El Salvavador 10-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
