<FIRST>u w AM-US-Jordan     12-13 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Jordan,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordanian Prince Worried That Middle East Now Low Priority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Hassan of Jordan said on Wednesday he
is worried Middle East peace efforts may get low priority as the
western world focuses on the sweeping changes in Eastern Europe.
   Following his half-hour Oval Office visit with President Bush
the prince said that Jordan backs the East European moves toward
political freedom and economic reform, but added:
   ``As we look at peacemaking in the Middle East region, we hope
that the Middle East does not slip on the international agenda. And
that certainly is a concern of many people in our part of the world
share.''
   ``It's been valuable to speak to the president during this
period of world transition and to state our concern and our
commitment for lasting peace in our region,'' he said.
   Hassan voiced an optimistic note for the future saying, ``I
would expect the new year period would be an interesting one for
all concerned in the region.''
   The meeting focused on the recent parliamentary elections in
Jordan as well, White House spokesman Steve Hart said.
   The meeting came at a time when Jordan's King Hussein has felt
slighted by the United States, especially over congressional
reluctance to approve arms sales for his country.
   U.S. officials have said they would like to encourage him to
have a more active role in the peace process as Secretary of State
James A. Baker III pushes regional peace talks.
   Hart said Bush regards Jordan as ``a key player in the region
and a valued friend for the United States,'' and sent his thanks
through the prince to Hussein for helping peace efforts.
   Jordan generally supports the Palestine Liberation
Organization's positions on the evolving peace efforts in the
Mideast.
   Egypt, on behalf of the PLO, has conditionally accepted a
five-point plan advanced by Baker. It is expected to lead to talks
in Washington next month with the United States and the foreign
ministers of Egypt and Israel, aimed at laying the groundwork for
talks between Israeli and Palestinian representatives.
   The plan calls for elections among the Palestinians who live in
Israel-occupied West Bank, to choose representatives for limited
self-rule to last for five years.
   After that, Egypt, Jordan, Israel and the Palestinans would hold
talks on overall settlement.
</TEXT>
