<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilReserve     12-13 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Reserve,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Executive Criticizes Foreign Oil Leasing Idea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent oil executive suggested Wednesday
the Energy Department drop consideration of a plan to cut the cost
of building U.S. emergency oil reserves by leasing, rather than
buying, oil from foreign producers.
   ``I have a little problem with going with hat in hand'' to OPEC
or other foreign producers to, in effect, ask for help in filling
the emergency reserve, Pete Silas, chairman of Phillips Petroleum
Co., told a department hearing.
   ``If it's a good program, it ought to be funded'' by U.S.
taxpayers, he added.
   Silas said putting leased OPEC oil in the U.S. Strategic
Petroleum Reserve would only add complications in the event of a
serious U.S. dispute with a leasor country.
   ``It may end up in a confrontation where you'd have to
nationalize'' the leased oil, Silas said.
   The Phillips chairman was responding to questions from Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins, who told Silas his department was
considering a variety of ways of reducing the cost of filling the
oil reserve, which now hold 580 million barrels of oil in a series
of underground salt domes in Louisiana and Texas.
   Watkins indicated his department, in considering the oil reserve
question as part of a broader national energy strategy, had not yet
decided whether the less costly leasing option would enhance or
detract from U.S. energy security.
   The department had disclosed earlier this year that Saudi
Arabia, the No. 1 foreign supplier of oil to the U.S. market, had
expressed interest in leasing oil for the emergency reserve,
although no specific proposals had been discussed.
   Watkins told Wednesday's hearing ``many nations of the world are
approaching us rather aggressively'' about participating in a
leasing program. He did not name any of the countries.
   Donald E. Milsten, director of the Maryland Energy Office and
vice chairman of the National Association of State Energy Offices,
told Watkins his association was concerned about the leasing idea
but had not yet formed a firm opinion.
   The strategic reserve ``might not be seen as a serious defense
mechanism'' in an oil supply emergency if part of the stockpile was
leased rather than owned by the U.S. government, Milsten said.
</TEXT>
