<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Unrest     12-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Unrest,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weapons Cache Discovered Next to Red Cross Apartments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded at least 10
Palestinians on Wednesday in clashes throughout the occupied lands,
Arab journalists and hospital officials said.
   The army meanwhile reported finding a cache of knives, axes and
PLO flags outside a building housing Red Cross relief officials in
Nablus in the occupied West Bank. News reports said the weapons
were put there by a Palestinian gang.
   Nablus is a center of anti-Israeli unrest.
   ``Something seemed suspicious about the house, and we went into
the yard and underneath some leaves found a knife, and then axes,
PLO flags and all sorts of equipment,'' said an Israeli soldier on
Israel television.
   TV said the weapons apparently belonged to a Palestinian gang
who took advantage of immunity the army granted to the apartment
grounds used by the Red Cross.
   Repeated phone calls to the the Red Cross went unanswered, but
an army spokesman said the group denied any connection to the
weapons and praised the army's action.
   The find came as Nablus merchants observed the second day of a
three-day strike in memory of four Palestinian activists slain by
troops on Dec. 1, Israel television said.
   The brother of one of the slain activists was shot and wounded
Wednesday as troops searched his Nablus home, Arab reporters said.
   Nine other Palestinians were wounded in clashes around the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed one Palestinian wounded in Nablus and said
the military was investigating the other reports.
   At least 631 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis during
the two-year Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule. Forty-three
Israelis have also died, and Palestinians have killed 155 of their
fellow Arabs on suspicion of collaborating with Israeli authorities.
