<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-MassGrave     12-13 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Mass Grave,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass Grave of Children Discovered in Northern Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Wednesday announced the discovery
of a mass grave with the remains of 135 children of North African
Jewish immigrants who died in a 1957 epidemic, Israel television
reported.
   The report came after a day of prayers and accusations by other
Jews from Yemen on the Saudi Arabian peninsula. They feared the
grave could hold the bones of about 600 children from their
community that were reported missing in the 1950s shortly after
their arrival in Israel.
   The discovery of the mass grave reopened one of the most
mysterious chapters in the history of immigration to the Jewish
state. There has never been an authoritative explanation of the
disappearance of the Yemenite children.
   One theory is that they were taken to collective farms and lost
contact with their parents. Another is they were dispersed to other
immigrant camps.
   However, news reports said the remains in the mass grave were
instead those of North African children who died during the
epidemic.
   The unmarked mass grave was discovered last week in a cemetery
in Kfar Yona, a village 20 miles north of Tel Aviv, when
gravediggers tried to dig in an unused portion of the cemetery.
   The find was leaked to the press by a gravedigger who said he
feared the children's remains might not be treated properly, Israel
TV reported.
   Dozens of Yemenite families flocked to the gravesite Wednesday
shortly after its discovery was announced on Israel radio.
   Almost 47,000 Yemenites, nearly the entire Jewish community,
were brought to Israel as part of ``Operation Magic Carpet.'' That
program ended in 1950.
   Yisrael Kessar, a legislator from the left-of-center Labor Party
and a Yemenite immigrant, called on Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
to order an investigation into the discovery after it was announced.
   However, police investigators said the remains were of children
of North African immigrants who died in a nearby hospital and were
hastily buried in a mass grave without a marker for ``economic
reasons,'' Israel radio reported.
   Most of the North Africans were from Morocco, Tunisia, Libya and
Algeria. There was no report of what sickness killed them, but
various epidemics swept through Israeli camps in those years,
including cholera and tuberculosis.
   The mass grave is next to the sites of two such camps.
   Nissim Atiya, a gravedigger who buried the victims in 1957, said
the children's families were notified of their deaths, and ``it was
all done officially.''
</TEXT>
