<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Honecker,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker No Longer Honorary Citizen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deluge of indignities continued for Erich
Honecker, the disgraced former Communist Party chief, when the East
Berlin city government decided Wednesday to take back his honorary
citizenship.
   The official news agency ADN said the City Council voted
unanimously, on grounds Honecker had misused his office, to relieve
him of the honor bestowed in 1982, when his power was unquestioned.
   Honecker has been under house arrest at an exclusive compound
outside East Berlin since Dec. 5 and is the object of a corruption
investigation. He was forced out as party chief Oct. 18, then lost
the presidency, all his other important jobs and his party
membership.
   A West German tourist agency said Honecker's vacation retreat on
the Schwerin Lake would be open to tourists in March. The Hansa
agency of Hamburg said in a news release Wednesday the two-house
complex 120 miles north of East Berlin could accommodate 45 to 55
beds.
   Among its features will be two small restaurants, a wine and
beer bar, a small bathing area with rowboats and bicycles.
   Hansa and the East German government travel agency, will run the
operation together, with 50 percent of the rooms reserved for West
German tourists and the remainder for East Germans, the news
release said.
