<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-China     12-13 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-China,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Continue to Assail Bush on China Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic House members continued their
attack on President Bush's decision to send high-level officials to
confer with Chinese leaders, complaining Wednesday that the White
House refused to allow one of those officials to come to Capitol
Hill to defend the action.
   ``It seems the Bush administration is willing to send Mr.
Eagleburger 6,000 miles to apologize to the Chinese leaders, but it
was not willing to send him two miles to Capitol Hill to explain
this action to Congress,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger had been invited
to testify about the trip before a hearing convened by two House
Foreign Affairs subcommittees. Eagleburger made the surprise visit
to Beijing last weekend with National Security Adviser Brent
Scowcroft.
   The State Department said Eagleburger could not testify because
he was filling in for Secretary of State James A. Baker III, who is
in Europe. However, spokesman Richard Boucher said Eagleburger had
briefed several members of Congress on the mission.
   Democrats vowed to press early next year for punitive sanctions
against the Chinese government in retaliation for its violent
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing last June,
saying they could prevail even if Bush vetoes the bill.
   Gejdenson was harshly critical of the Eagleburger-Scowcroft
visit, contending they apologized ``for being offended by the
savage squelching of those who courageously sought basic freedoms
in Tiananmen Square.''
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, defended Bush.
   ``I don't know of a soul who believes that the Scowcroft mission
went to Beijing to apologize to the Chinese,'' he said. ``This
Congress and this administration have no intention of kowtowing to
illegitimate Chinese actions.''
   However, Leach said he believes the United States has an
obligation to take whatever steps it can to persude the Chinese
lift the ``yoke of political oppression'' The weekend mission, he
said, can be seen as a test of the ability of outside parties to
``help extricate a proud nation from an embarassing corner.''
   ``President Bush is prudentially betting that a historically
xenophobic China is more likely to temper its stridency at home and
abroad if it isn't perceived to be capitulating to the pressure of
foreign powers,'' Leach said.
   As House members wrangled over the issue, Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, weighed in on behalf of those who contend
Bush made a serious blunder in sending Scowcroft and Eagleburger to
Beijing.
   Mitchell, in a speech before the Commonwealth Club in San
Francisco, said Bush compounded his blunder when he moved to lift
sanctions he had imposed against China by executive order.
   Those moves, Mitchell said, include renewing subsidies for wheat
sales to China, permitting Chinese engineers to return to the
United States to work on upgrading Chinese fighter planes and a
possible lifting of a ban on exporting communications satellites.
   ``These actions represent an embarrassing eagerness to please
the Chinese government and an awkward reluctance to support the
aspirations of the Chinese people,'' Mitchell said. ``It should be
the other way around.''
</TEXT>
