<FIRST>u w AM-US-China 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0653,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Approve VOA Correspondent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with China approving correspondent.
Picks up 8th graf pvs `The next ...' SUBS 14th graf pvs `Meanwhile, it
...' with 6 grafs UPDATE with source saying satellite deal will be finalized
Friday, Mitchell comment Picks up 15th graf pvs `White House ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has approved a new Voice of America
correspondent to replace the newsman expelled after the government
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, the State Department
announced Wednesday.
   The foreign ministry conveyed its approval to the U.S. Embassy
in Beijing three days after a high-level U.S. delegation returned
from a surprise trip to China.
   The delegation discussed ways to mend the strained ties between
the two governments that have existed since hundreds of people were
killed in June when the Chinese military advanced on the
demonstrators in Tianamen Square.
   ``We welcome'' the decision to approve Stephanie Mann Nealer's
accreditation, which has been pending since September, the State
Department said in a statement. Nealer is head of the VOA's East
Asia and Pacific News department.
   VOA correspondent Al Pessin and Associated Press newsman John
Pomfret were expelled from China after being accused of spreading
rumors and lies about the military crackdown.
   VOA Director Richard W. Carlson said he didn't know whether the
Chinese decision on VOA was related to the weekend talks in Beijing
led by National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   ``We think this is a positive step,'' Carlson said.
   The next move, Carlson said, is for China to stop jamming the
Mandarin and Cantonese language VOA broadcasts to China, as they
have since June. The four-hour English-language broadcasts are not
jammed, he said.
   The Bush administration, criticized by some members of Congress
for the recent overtures to Beijing while Chinese authorities
continue to harshly suppress pro-democracy dissidents, has made
clear it would welcome any reciprocal gesture from China.
   The first such gesture came when China's official news agency
announced Monday, the day Scowcroft returned, that China would not
sell Syria medium-range M-9 missiles that have been a subject of
U.S. concern.
   After Scowcroft returned, the administration revealed it was
considering lifting a ban on satellite exports to China. Bush
refused Wednesday to reply when asked if he was prepared to lift
the ban, but a spokesman said there had not been a final decision.
   The Hughes Aircraft-manufactured communications satellites fall
in the category of items on the government's sensitive munitions
list that were automatically included in a suspension of U.S.
exports to China imposed to protest the crackdown.
   On Capitol Hill, a source said the satellite deal would be
approved Friday. The source, who has been following the
administration's deliberations, spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell called word of the
concessions to China an indication of ``an embarrassing eagerness
to please the Chinese government and an awkward reluctance to
support the aspirations of the Chinese people. It should be the
other way around.''
   Mitchell noted that Bush said after the June crackdown that
there could not be business as usual with any government that would
take such action.
   ``Yet that is exactly what appears to be happening,'' Mitchell
said in a speech to the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco.
   On the House side, members of the Asia subcommittee harshly
criticized the trip to Beijing and lambasted Deputy Secretary of
State Lawrence Eagleburger for declining to appear before the panel
to report on his talks in Beijing.
   Meanwhile, it was revealed that a third administration official,
White House personnel director Chase Untermeyer, joined Scowcroft
and Eagleburger on the China trip to make personal contacts for the
president.
   White House spokesman Steve Hart said Untermeyer's main mission
was to speak to two Chinese friends of Bush, one a mid-level
government official and the other a former member of government.
   Untermeyer, Hart said, was ``simply to hear their thoughts about
the changes going on in China'' since the June demonstrations.
   Bush served as liaison officer, then the highest-ranking U.S.
representative in Beijing, in 1974-75.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AgingAircraft     12-13 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aging Aircraft,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Strips Old DC-9s to Look for Wear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM STRADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir is taking apart three of its older
planes to search for age-related structural flaws in an
around-the-clock effort to get a head start on an expected
tightening of aircraft safety standards.
   ``We're trying to look in places you normally can't look at to
see what we can do to prevent a problem in the future,'' said USAir
spokesman John Bronson.
   A task force comprising representatives of the Federal Aviation
Administration, airlines and aircraft manufacturers began studying
the safety of older planes last year in the wake of several
age-related accidents. It began its work in October 1988, six
months after a section of the fuselage of an Aloha Airlines jet
peeled off over the Pacific Ocean.
   Jack Naughton, director of aircraft heavy maintenance for USAir,
said Wednesday that FAA inspection recommendations are likely to
become mandatory in February. Naughton called the Aloha Airlines
accident, which killed a flight attendant and injured dozens of
passengers, the catalyst for the closer look at older planes.
   USAir selected three DC-9s, each about 20 years old, for the
program. The airline has completed what it calls an inch-by-inch
inspection of one DC-9 and returned it to the USAir 400-plane fleet.
   The second plane in the program is at an airline maintenance
hangar at Pittsburgh's airport. Mechanics are to have it finished
within a month.
   The 22-year-old DC-9, built for Delta Airlines in 1967 and
bought by USAir a decade later, has been stripped of its paint and
cabin furnishings. Three shifts of 18 mechanics each work day and
night, searching for flaws not readily revealed by more common
inspection techniques.
   The thick smell of primer floats inside the hangar and there is
a constant whir of machinery and ping of hammers on rivets.
   Mostly, the mechanics are looking for evidence of corrosion,
which airline officials believe leads to fuselage cracks.
   Standing over a table beside the 107-foot-long plane, mechanic
Harry Garman worked Wednesday to replace corroded metal from
underneath the aircraft.
   ``We'll either treat it or we'll replace it, depending on the
depth of it,'' Garman said.
   ``It's kind of like your rusty fender on a car,'' he explained.
``If it's just a little bit of rust, you clean it up and paint it,
but if it's real deep, you replace that area.''
   Working on a scaffold alongside the plane, Charlie Slack placed
a metal reinforcing strip above the plane's windows from front to
rear. Tests have shown that area to be more susceptible to stress
cracks than other parts of the plane.
   USAir estimates the procedure will cost about $1 million per
plane. After the first three DC-9s are completed, airline officials
will review the program and make any necessary adjustments before
continuing.
   George Mason, the airline's vice president of heavy maintenance,
said 29 planes are scheduled to be completed in the next four
years. A total of 50 of USAir's 74 DC-9s will be stripped and
inspected, he said.
   Mason said he's not worried that patching up the aircraft might
make USAir's fleet look less sky-worthy.
   ``It all in your perspective,'' he said. ``When you see an
airplane at the gate that has patches on it, should you be
concerned _ or should you be concerned if you see an airplane that
doesn't have them?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-APArts:FilmReview     12-13 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Film Review,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Glory''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Glory'' opens Dec. 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On July 18, 1863, despite fatigue and poor rations, the 54th
Massachusetts Colored Volunteer Infantry marched across a half-mile
of sand on a South Carolina beach to lead the ill-planned attack on
Fort Wagner in Charleston harbor. The regiment lost more than 40
percent of its men.
   The story of the 54th, the first black regiment from the North
to fight in the Civil War, and its youthful white colonel, Robert
Gould Shaw, unfolds in ``Glory,'' Edward Zwick's masterful movie
for Tri-Star Pictures.
   Zwick presents a powerful, moving tapestry of war's
senselessness. The screenplay by Kevin Jarre is partly based on the
books ``Lay This Laurel'' and ``One Gallant Rush,'' and letters
Shaw wrote home to his parents. The movie _ narrated by Matthew
Broderick as Shaw _ is largely seen through his eyes.
   Young and privileged, but disillusioned and battle-scarred after
the gory and indecisive Battle of Antietam, Shaw returns to his
wealthy, powerful and abolitionist parents in Massachusetts just in
time for a lavish party and an offer from the governor to take
command of an all-black fighting regiment.
   He rises in rank from captain to colonel and musters his men,
who include his childhood friends Cabot (Cary Elwes), who is white
and becomes a major, and Tom (Andre Braugher), a second-generation
free black who volunteers as an enlisted man.
   Much of ``Glory'' focuses on the basic training of a ragtag
group of runaway slaves and free men, who are denied all the basic
supplies given to white soldiers, including proper shoes and the
coveted blue uniform, and are asked to accept less pay.
   They have much to learn about soldiering and about human
relations, in a fight for freedom and the restoration of the union.
   As Trip, an embittered runaway, Denzel Washington (``Cry
Freedom,'' ``The Mighty Quinn,'' ``Power'') does a star turn. His
hatred, desires, feelings are worn on his face, such as when he's
flogged for supposedly trying to desert. Not one word is uttered;
he merely locks eyes with Broderick (``Biloxi Blues,'' ``War
Games'') and allows a single tear to fall. Broderick, meanwhile,
shows clear repulsion and sorrow. Why? Because the whip _ a symbol
of the servitude from which the men had fled _ had been used on
Trip in the past: His back is a jungle of ugly scars.
   ``Glory'' becomes Trip's story _ as well as Shaw's _ as the
runaway undergoes a radical self-realization. In the end, the 54th
becomes the only family he's ever known.
   Zwick, the Emmy-award winning director of ``Special Bulletin''
and ``thirtysomething,'' stresses visual acting in ``Glory.''
Action speaks louder than words, and he focuses on facial
expressions and body movements rather than histrionics, gimmicks or
slick words.
   He also is spare with dialogue. When the 54th marches past the
white regiments _ who regarded the blacks as a joke and less than
men _ to lead the assault against Fort Wagner, only four words are
spoken by the once hostile whites: ``Give 'em hell, 54.''
   Ultimately, color no longer is the issue. The men are fellow
soldiers about to die. And like ``Gallipoli'' and ``Hamburger
Hill,'' the overriding issue becomes the utter futility of war.
   The battle scene at Fort Wagner is beautifully choreographed,
the men running along the beach, the U.S. flag full and billowing.
It is poetic and yet powerful.
   ``Glory'' makes good use of battle scenes. They are exciting,
frightening and realistic. At James Island, the 54th gets its first
taste of fighting. After firing a few rounds and watching a
Confederate unit retreat, more Confederates appear through the mist
like gray ghosts and the battle soon becomes hand-to-hand combat.
Dan Lerner was second unit director, and Bob Minor coordinated the
stunts.
   ``Glory'' is bound to be a contender at Oscar time. It also has
a haunting but overused score by James Horner, with choral work by
the Boys Choir of Harlem. The music is lovely but unfortunately the
filmmakers use the same refrain so often that just about every
scene becomes a climax.
   There are good performances by Morgan Freeman (``Street Smart,''
``Driving Miss Daisy''), Jihmi Kennedy as a stuttering enlisted man
and John Finn as the fierce no-nonsense Irish sergeant-major who
whips the 54th into shape. Braugher, whose theater credits include
``Much Ado About Nothing'' and ``King John'' at the New York
Shakespeare Festival, makes his film debut in ``Glory,'' and is
someone to watch. Jane Alexander appears as Shaw's mother.
   The Freddie Fields production has a running time of 122 minutes
and is rated R.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
