<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Comoros     12-13 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comoros,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mercenary Says President was Accidentally Slain by Bodyguard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French mercenary widely
blamed for killing the leader of the Comoros Islands said the
president was accidentally shot by his own bodyguard during an army
attack, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
   Meanwhile a French news agency said French and South African
officials met with the mercenary, Bob Denard, on Wednesday in an
attempt to persuade him to leave the remote islands off southeast
Africa.
   Denard, who heads the mercenary-led Presidential Guard on the
islands, said President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane was fatally
shot on Nov. 26 during an assault by army troops, The Star
newspaper reported from the Comoros capital of Moroni.
   The report did not say why the army was attacking the nation's
leader.
   Denard, in a statement read to journalists Tuesday night, said
he was in the room with Abdallah at the presidential palace when
the shooting occurred. But he again denied any responsibility for
the killing, The Star reported.
   The mercenary, a veteran soldier of fortune who has fought in
Africa and Asia, declined to answer questions or elaborate on the
circumstances of Abdallah's death other than to say a bodyguard
actually shot the president.
   Denard and 30 other French and Belgian mercenaries use the
Presidential Guard to control the islands despite widespread
opposition by residents, who have taken to the streets in protest.
   The mercenary said he was prepared to leave the islands if he is
allowed to go ``with honor.'' He is negotiating with the French and
South Africans, the largest aid donors to the Comoros, and wants
financial compensation in exchange for leaving.
   The French news agency Agence France-Presse, in a report from
Moroni, quoted unidentified sources as saying French and South
African officials met with Denard for 20 minutes Wednesday morning.
   There was no information on what was discussed, but the agency
said a sticking point is Denard's demand for a guarantee he will
not be prosecuted in France for his role in an unsuccessful 1977
coup in the West African country of Benin.
   Comorans widely blame Denard for Abdallah's death. According to
various sources, the two men argued about several matters just
before the shooting.
   Denard helped engineer a coup that ousted Abdallah in 1975, the
year the island nation became independent from France.
   Denard then led a 1978 coup that restored Abdallah to power. He
and his fellow mercenaries have remained a leading force on the
islands ever since.
   In Paris, President Francois Mitterrand said at Wednesday's
weekly Cabinet meeting that ``any idea of French military
intervention is excluded'' in the Comoros, government spokesman
Louis Le Pensec told reporters.
</TEXT>
