<DOCNO> AP891213-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BeaverBattle     12-13 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beaver Battle,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schoolchildren, Residents Champion Embattled Beavers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HATFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Town officials, fearing that beaver dams
would flood recently repaired Linseed Road, decided to rub out the
rodents but found themselves having to take on schoolchildren and
The Beaver's Club.
   Pupils at Breor Elementary School in this small town about 20
miles north of Springfield fired off a batch of letters last week
accusing selectmen of being cruel and asking, ``please don't kill
the beavers.''
   About six beavers live in a marshy field next to the road,
according to Micki Seigel, who lives in the area and has printed up
bumper stickers saying, ``I love the Linseed Road beavers.''
   This week, a pupil's letter reached The Beavers' Club of Hampden
and Hampshire Counties, a Holyoke-based service group, asking them
to help their namesakes.
   Selectman Chairman George Zgrodnick Jr. said Wednesday he
remains convinced that trapping is the best solution to protect the
$350,000 worth of repairs on the road.
   ``I don't know much about beaver dams, but I know they're bad,''
Zgrodnick said.
   He defended his decision not to call in an engineer before
authorizing the trapping, but said an engineer would be called in
this weekend to assess the potential for damage.
   Zgrodnick said selectmen told people opposing trapping that if
they could find another way to deal with the problem ``very, very
quickly, go ahead.''
   Beaver Club President Charles Davignon said his group was not
interested in joining the political fray, but was willing to
consider a request for help if a compromise is agreed on, such as
installing special drainage pipes.
   Club members visited Seigel this week at Running Gutter brook. A
small beaver lodge and dam have turned the field by the road into a
shallow pond now covered with ice.
   Seigel said her main objective was to buy time until the field
froze over.
   ``I am not an animal rights activist,'' she said. ``It just
seemed, why kill them if you don't have to.''
   The beavers appeared this summer and the issue of the road
threat surfaced this fall, said Zgrodnik, who said he did not
recall who first brought it up.
   Some in town said they weren't sure how the issue got so
controversial.
   ``We were kind of caught surprised ourselves when we started
reading in the newspapers and we started checking into it,'' said
Water Commissioner Robert Osepowicz.
   Even if beaver dams block storm drains, water will drain through
slits cut into the curb, Highway Superintendent Marshall Pease was
quoted as saying in a local newspaper last week.
   Pease had no comment Wednesday. ``All the answers come from town
hall,'' he said.
   Tom Decker, a biologist with the state Division of Fisheries and
Wildlife, said about 1,400 beavers are killed in Massachusetts each
year during the season between Nov. 15 and Feb. 28.
   ``We get hundreds of nuisance complaints,'' Decker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0192 </DOCNO>
