<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MsSanta?     12-13 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ms Santa?,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historical Court Decides Mr. and Mrs. Claus Share Honors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a decision Solomon might admire, a judge
Wednesday authorized Mrs. Santa Claus to share equal gift-giving
Christmas rights with her famous husband, and declared their sleigh
``community property.''
   Furthermore, Mrs. Claus' title is now ``Ms.,'' and she is
``emancipated from any household duties'' so that she may accompany
her jolly spouse on his airborne tours of the world, according to
the ruling by Municipal Court Judge George T. Choppelas.
   Christmas generosity symbolized by Santa Claus is a ``universal
phenomenon'' and should have no gender strings attached, the judge
added, undoubtedly with an eye to his political future.
   A courtroom jammed with spectators, reporters and photographers
broke into cheers and applause at the conclusion of a rather unruly
and holiday-happy 60th session of San Francisco's mock Court of
Historical Review.
   The just-for-fun court is a 14-year San Francisco tradition
staged in a real City Hall courtroom, with a real judge, real
lawyers, clerks and stenographers. Only the witnesses are phony.
   Everybody has a good time with such questions as who invented
the martini, is chicken soup Jewish penicillin, and where did chop
suey come from.
   ``Thank you for not starting without me,'' said the judge to the
trial advocates, San Francisco Supervisor Angela Alioto, who said
Santa was a woman, and Public Defender Jeff Brown, who said he must
remain a male. Brown, who will run for re-election, let his
witnesses carry the case.
   The stage was set by a reading of Clement Moore's ``A Visit From
St. Nicholas,'' by a local talk show personality.
   Looking on with interest were Municipal Court Judge Diane Wick,
dressed as a female Santa, and lawyer Robert J. McCarthy,
pillow-paunched with a tatty white beard and wig. He sat on the
lady Santa's lap.
   ``It's obvious that Santa Claus is a woman,'' claimed Alioto,
insisting that the Italian female Santa Claus, ``Befana,'' leaps
down chimneys to dole out toys to good kids, and chunks of coal to
the bad ones.
   The lady Santa testified hotly that the idea of a male Santa
Claus ``is a fraud and a hoax,'' furthered by the male chauvinist
persuasion.
   Completing her testimony, Santa laid several brightly wrapped
gifts before the judge.
   ``Bribery!'' hollered the male Santa.
   Tradition requires that Santa Claus remain a man, testified San
Francisco City College history professor Lee Dolson, who wondered
whether Alioto was arguing that the Italian Santa might have
resulted from a sex change operation.
   ``I think that Santa Claus is the personification of Christmas,
and Santa Claus as a man ... (he) embodies the spirit of Christmas,
which is giving, caring and hope,'' testified psychiatric hospital
adminstrator Franco Diamond. ``The thought of Santa Claus as a
woman _ I shudder ...''
   Nobody in the courtrroom shared the shudder, and the judge ruled
that everybody wins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0668 12-13 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Raise Specter of `Fourth Reich'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with more comment, details, minor editing.
No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk of reunification raises the specter of a
``Fourth Reich,'' Communists said Wednesday, but West German plans
for hundreds of millions of dollars in aid are the latest sign the
two countries are coming together.
   A Munich newspaper quoted Willy Brandt, the former West German
chancellor, as saying the Soviets prevented a potential bloodbath
in Leipzig on Oct. 9, when protest against the old hard-line
leadership of East Germany reached its peak.
   Manfred Gerlach, interim president of East Germany, told church
leaders a new constitution expected next year would provide for
individual states within a federal system, another sign of the
Communists' continuing loss of power.
   Indignities continued for Erich Honecker, the disgraced former
Communist Party chief deposed Oct. 18. The East Berlin City Council
took back the honorary citizenship bestowed on him in 1982.
   In West Germany, the ultra-right Republican Party said it would
try to organize an East German sister party to enter candidates in
free parliamentary elections planned for May.
   About 1,000 high school students, teachers and parents
demonstrated in East Berlin against mandatory instruction in the
Russian language.
   Several thousand students and parents in the northern city of
Stralsund demanded that teachers who belong to the Communist Party
be fired, and 2,000 people in Schwerin demonstrated against German
reunification, the official news agency ADN reported.
   For several weeks, at least a half-dozen new projects involving
the two Germanys have been announced every day, many initiated by
West Germans. The East German government has acknowledged the
``German question,'' but has publicly insisted no formal union will
occur.
   On Wednesday, the Communist Party newspaper Neues Deutschland
said East Germany must adhere to ``socialist, anti-fascist,
pacifist and all international leftist traditions, especially those
of Lenin.''
   It said a West German ``pocketing'' of East Germany was not on
the agenda, and rejected ``a Fourth Reich, however that would be
formed'' _ a reference to Adolf Hitler's Third Reich.
   Other newspapers took a similar line against reunificiation,
including Neue Zeit, published by the Christian Democrats, who
recently broke with the Communist Party.
   Neue Zeit said demonstrators in Leipzig who called for
reunification were expressing outdated ``megalomaniac dreams of
Greater Germany.''
   New Forum, which has 200,000 members and is the largest
opposition group, officially opposes reunification, but increasing
calls for one German state at its Monday night rallies in Leipzig
have threatened to split the movement.
   In an interview with East German television, President Richard
von Weizsaecker cautioned against attempts to speed reunification
and against ``heating up'' the already volatile political situation
in East Germany.
   The Soviet Union opposes reunification and Secretary of State
James A. Baker III has urged a cautious approach, but signs of a
virtual de facto union grow daily.
   On Wednesday, West Germany said it was providing $540 million to
East Germany for 17 environmental cleanup projects. East Germany
has one of the most polluted environments and some of the most
fouled rivers in Europe, and experts say help is needed urgently to
prevent an ecological catastrophe.
   Mayor Walter Momper of West Berlin and his East Berlin
counterpart, Erhard Krack, announced agreements Wednesday ranging
from joint subway tickets to Western investment in East Berlin.
   Economics Minister Christa Luft of East Germany said she expects
Parliament to pass a law on joint ventures within three months.
West German businesses have been preparing for huge investments.
   West Germans have seized most of the initiative to date,
prompting East German warnings against a wholesale national sellout
to the rich, capitalist nation.
   East German cities also have appealed to West German sister
cities for aid, however. West German cities have sent food,
medicine, heaters and even scaffolding, municipal officials said at
a conference in Cologne.
   On Thursday, Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann of West Germany
is to meet with Premier Hans Modrow, bringing a three-point
economic aid plan with him.
</TEXT>
