<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Kids&amp;Guns     12-13 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kids &amp; Guns,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Program Launched to Reduce Gun Violence Among Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first comprehensive program to teach
kindergartners and high schoolers alike about the dangers of guns
was launched Wednesday by Dade County's public schools.
   The special curriculum was developed following a record 43
gunshot deaths last year in Dade County of children 18 and under;
so far this year, at least 48 children have been killed in
gun-related incidents in Dade, school officials said.
   The program was made necessary by an increase in the prevalence
of guns in society, said Michael Krop, a member of the Dade County
School Board.
   ``We now feel compelled, unfortunately, to teach kids about
guns,'' Krop said earlier at a news conference at Coconut Grove
Elementary. ``Essentially our message to young people is, `You
don't touch a handgun.'''
   That message will be reinforced in the classroom with
discussions aimed at helping students recognize unsafe situations
and know how to react when encountering guns.
   A video also will be shown to middle and senior high students
focusing on the trauma of a gunshot death or injury _ through the
experiences of other kids. One teen-ager describes the trauma of
accidentally shooting his father; also interviewed were a football
player left paralyzed and a girl who lost a leg in gun attacks.
   Brochures and a video were being prepared for parents to help
them insure the safety of their children.
   Wednesday was declared ``Gun Safety Awareness Day'' by Dade
County Public Schools, the nation's fourth-largest school district.
   ``Today's youngsters are at a greater risk of gun violence than
any previous generation,'' Barbara Lautman, executive director of
the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence in Washignton, D.C., said
Friday at the news conference. ``We want the Dade County program to
serve as the national standard for education to reduce gun
violence, death and injury among youth.''
   In 1987, one out of every 10 children who died in the nation was
killed with a gun, and gun accidents were the fourth leading cause
of accidental death for children, according to Ms. Lautman.
   A new state law aimed at protecting children from accidental
shootings also authorized the development of a gun-safety program
in public schools. The measure, which took effect in October,
requires gun owners to take reasonable precautions to keep loaded
weapons away from children 15 and younger; the law provides for
jail time and fines for gun owner's carelessness.
   Dade's program to prevent gun injuries and deaths among children
is tailored by age groups. For example, at the elementary level the
emphasis will be on role-playing, while in the sixth through 12th
grades, students will focus on issues surrounding gun violence,
including conflict resolution activities and the role of the media.
   The curriculum was developed following discussions in April led
by volunteers from the Dade County Youth Crime Watch with some 400
middle and senior high students about guns and gun violence.
   Among the findings, released Wednesday, were that students have
mixed opinions on whether guns are good or bad, with black and
Hispanics most aware of and involved with daily handgun violence;
students believe guns are more common today than at previous times;
and that anti-gun messages need to show more the pain and loss
suffered by victims of gun violence.
   Dwayne Dupuch, a second grader at Coconut Grove Elementary, said
he had never been around a gun but he knew what they could do.
``Kill,'' he said without hesitation. And what had he learned so
far about them?
   ``Not to touch guns,'' said the shy 7-year-old.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
