<FIRST>r i AM-NIreland-Attack 1stLd-Writethru a0697 12-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed, Third Injured In Attack on Security Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band of 10 to 12 raiders
attacked a security post near the Irish border with guns and bombs
Wednesday, killing two British soldiers and seriously injuring a
third, police said.
   No group claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell on
guerrillas of the Irish Republican Army fighting British rule in
Northern Ireland.
   The gunmen escaped unhurt after the attack at Derryard, an
isolated checkpoint about two miles from the Fermanagh border with
County Monaghan in the Irish Republic, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary said.
   The victims were members of the 1st Battalion of the King's Own
Scottish Borderers.
   Six other soldiers and a police officer survived unhurt.
   A police statement gave this account:
   A truck backed up to the checkpoint. As soldiers approached, men
inside opened fire and threw grenades, killing one soldier.
   As the men were firing, a van was driven into the checkpoint and
abandoned. A short time later, it exploded, killing another soldier
and wounding a third.
   The truck sped away. An army patrol spotted it headed for the
border. The patrol fired but the men escaped, abandoning the
vehicle at the border.
   About four hours before the attack, 12 masked gunman with a
truck and van took over a nearby house. They left shortly before
the attack, taking a tractor that had not been recovered.
   The deaths brought to 12 the number of British soldiers killed
in Northern Ireland this year. Up to Wednesday, sectarian violence
in Northern Ireland had killed 60 people this year, including 21
members of security forces.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to unite the
Protestant-dominated province with the 95 percent Catholic Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
