<FIRST>u i AM-Gabon-Plot     12-13 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gabon-Plot,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Alleged Conspirator Dies in Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBREVILLE, Gabon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of plotting to
assassinate President Omar Bongo has died, the second alleged
conspirator to die in custody, the official Gabon news agency AGP
reported Wednesday.
   The agency, citing medical sources, said Doukakas Nziengui died
Tuesday afternoon at Libreville's central hospital of ``excessive
arterial tension.''
   In Strasbourg, France, a group called the International
Committee for Respect and Application of the African Charter of
Human Rights charged that Nziengui died in prison while being
interrogated.
   A second man accused in the case, 39-year-old Richard Anton of
France, died in early November in prison of malaria, the news
agency said.
   Gabonese officials announced in October that they had foiled a
plot to kill Bongo on Sept. 23, saying the conspirators intended to
arrest the prime minister, defense minister and parliament speaker
and take control of the government of this former French colony in
West Africa.
   They said Nziengui, who worked for the Gabon Energy and Water
Co., guided mercenaries on their arrival in the country for the
assassination and paid their hotel bills with his credit card.
   A former Gabonese government official living in Paris, Pierre
Maboundou, was accused of directing the assassination plans.
   Bongo has ruled Gabon, an oil-exporting country, since 1967. He
has not allowed any opposition groups to operate since declaring a
one-party state in 1968 and has been re-elected unopposed four
times, most recently in November 1986.
</TEXT>
