<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hungary     12-13 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hungary,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Says It First Tested ``Limits of Soviet Tolerance''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian Prime Minister Miklos Nemeth said
Wednesday that his country was the first East bloc nation to
``probe the limits of Soviet tolerance'' and that one major goal
now is to avoid an explosion.
   Nemeth's comment came as he cut a scheduled three-day British
visit to 12 hours because of the pace of events at home.
   He cautioned that a proposed austerity budget will provoke
opposition, but said tough measures are Hungary's only hope of
developing a market-oriented economy.
   ``This program is not being applauded by the people ... tensions
will emerge,'' he said, speaking through an interpreter at a news
conference.
   ``What everybody needs to comprehend now is that the future of
the country is at stake. Stability and avoiding an explosion _ this
is one of the main lines of Hungarian policy.''
   Nemeth reacted coolly to a suggestion that Hungary is being
cautious about distancing itself politically from the Soviet Union.
   ``Hungary was the first to probe the limits of Soviet
tolerance,'' Nemeth said, referring to the dissolution of the
Communist Party before the rapid changes in East Germany, Bulgaria
and Czechoslovakia. ``And don't forget, in Hungary this was not
done in the streets.''
   The Hungarian Communist Party disbanded itself in October and
formed the the Hungarian Socialist Party, which espouses democratic
principles. In Hungary's first democratic elections for 41 years
due next year, the party will compete with others for power.
   Nemeth, 41, a reformist member of Hungary's former communist
party, came to Britain as 24 industrialized nations coordinating a
big aid program to Poland and Hungary met in Brussels, Belgium.
   His visit was part of an aggressive campaign for Western aid. He
also wants access to Western high technology denied to communist
countries during the Cold War.
   Western countries have pushed for austerity as a condition for
aid.
   ``We are not able to do it on our own,'' Nemeth said. ``Hungary
is not looking simply for smiles and pats on the back. We need
financial assistance.''
   During his visit, Nemeth conferred with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and said she promised managerial assistance. Britian has
set up two $40 million ``know-how'' funds, one for Poland and one
for Hungary.
   But to unlock aid promised by the International Monetary Fund
and the 24 donor nations, Hungary must adopt the austerity
measures. A Hungarian decision is expected next week.
</TEXT>
