<DOCNO> AP891213-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Economy     12-13 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Economy,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks Quick OK for Economic Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday appealed to
Parliament for fast approval of its plans for economic reform but
said it doesn't need special powers to bypass lawmakers as proposed
by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   Deputy Finance Minister Marek Dabrowski told a news conference
that if the austerity measures, tight budget and anti-inflationary
plans succeed, Poland's 900 percent annual inflation rate will
disappear by mid-1990.
   Walesa caused a sensation Tuesday when he said Parliament should
simply grant the government wide powers to put into effect whatever
economic measures it deems necessary to combat the nation's $39
billion foreign debt, widespread shortages of goods and industrial
production problems.
   ``Time is running out,'' Walesa said when he made the proposal.
Parliamentary debate on all the laws could delay the program, he
said.
   However, government spokeswoman Malgorzata Niezabitowska said at
the news conference with Dabrowski that the government was
surprised by Walesa's proposal. She said it will not seek special
powers because it would rather have Parliament approve the
legislation, although ``in a speeded-up way.''
   ``The success of the whole difficult project depends to a great
extent on social support. Thus, the opinion of society's
representation, of Parliament, is of great significance to us,''
said the spokeswoman.
   However, when pressed, she said she could not exclude the
government accepting special powers if Parliament decides to give
them.
   The economic plan of the Solidarity-led government has been
praised by the International Monetary Fund, and Poland and the IMF
will complete ``in the nearest days'' a letter of intent outlining
the program, the official said.
   The IMF would grant about $700 million in loans to Poland in
exchange for the reforms.
   The agreement would also open the door to a broader flow of
credit and financial aid, with promised help from Western countries
already exceeding $3.2 billion, Dabrowski said.
   If the government's plans succeed, the pace of price rises,
currently more than 50 percent a month, should fall to an average
25 percent a month in the first quarter of 1990, said Dabrowski.
They should fall 2 to 3 percent more each month for the rest of
that year, he said.
   Inflation will be cut through reduced government spending and
tax increases to balance the budget, limits on wage increases
through tax penalties, an end to government subsidies to force
inefficient enterprises to close, and making the Polish zloty fully
convertible against hard currencies in Poland.
   The effect will be ``dramatic,'' the deputy minister said. It
may cut real incomes by 20 percent, industrial production by 5
percent, and the gross national product by 2 to 3 percent, he said.
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki's government has been working
around the clock this week to prepare by Sunday more than a dozen
pieces of legislation to radically transform the economy beginning
Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
