<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica-Soviet     12-13 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America-Soviet,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Wants Cuba in Central American Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet diplomat Yuri Nosenko said
Wednesday that Cuba should take part in the Central America peace
process and help negotiate a cut in the flow of arms to the region.
   ``The time has come in which Cuba must return to the Central
America family in order to negotiate a reduction in the flow of
arms to Central America,'' Nosenko told The Associated Press in an
interview.
   Nosenko is from the Soviet Foreign Ministry's Latin American
Department.
   He said he came here to take a closer look at a summit of five
Central American presidents. The meeting concluded Tuesday with a
call for the demobilization of Salvadoran leftist guerrillas and
U.S.-supported Nicaraguan Contras and an end to all help for
insurgents in the region.
   The presidents asked the superpowers not to interfere in Central
America.
   ``If Cuba takes part directly in the negotiations we can know
its position and try to gain some kind of accord,'' Nosenko said
before returning to Moscow.
   He refused to elaborate, but said the United States and the
Soviet Union should guarantee the accords reached by the Central
American presidents.
   ``I think the United States and the Soviet Union are very close
in their positions, because both countries want a diplomatic
solution to the crisis in this region,'' Nosenko said.
   Nosenko reiterated that the Soviet Union stopped all arms
shipments to Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government last year.
   However, the United States said last week that a Soviet ship
with a cargo of helicopters was due Dec. 18 at Corinto, Nicaragua,
on the Pacific coast.
</TEXT>
