<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--BatmanVideo     12-13 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Batman Video,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Batman' Video Breaks Rental Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Home Video's ``Batman'' has set
records in the video rental business, with 9.8 transactions counted
in two weeks, according to the New York research firm of Alexander
&amp; Associates.
   The somber comic book hero's clash with the Joker rang up an
estimated $21 million in rentals from its Nov. 17 release until
Dec. 4, eclipsing ``E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial,'' by more than 3
million ``turns,'' said Robert Alexander, the firm's president.
   ``Batman'' also helped carry the video industry to its best week
overall, said Alexander, who counted 94.8 million video rentals for
the week ending on Dec. 4.
   The previous high was 91.8 million in rentals, set in the last
week of November 1988, when ``E.T.'' was released.
   When it comes to video sales, however, it appears that MCA Home
Video's ``E.T.'' probably will outperform ``Batman.''
   Analysts estimate that about 4.2 million copies of ``Batman''
have been sold, with about 1.3 million representing sales to video
rental operators.
   Retailers indicated that ``Batman'' sales are about half the
pace of ``E.T.''
