<FIRST>r a AM-RitterInvestigation     12-13 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritter Investigation,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Attorney Acknowledges Investigation of Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The district attorney acknowledged Wednesday
that he is investigating charges that the Rev. Bruce Ritter,
founder of the Covenant House for homeless youth, improperly spent
the shelter's funds.
   After nearly two days of silence amid news reports that Ritter
provided an apartment, money and gifts to a young male prostitute
and took him on trips, Manhattan District Attorney Robert
Morgenthau issued a statement saying the probe was in its
``earliest stages.''
   ``No determination has been made as to the truth of the
allegations, nor can such a determination be made until the
investigation has been concluded,'' Morgenthau said.
   But he said, ``Press reports of leaks attributed to unnamed law
enforcement officials are inaccurate, may unfairly damage
reputations and can only impede the investigation.''
   Spokesmen for Covenant House denied the young man's allegations.
``We categorically deny any kind of (illicit) relationship between
Father Ritter and this youth,'' said James Harnett, the shelter's
chief executive officer.
   The New York Post reported Wednesday that investigators had the
youth wear a recording device during a conversation with Ritter in
an effort to confirm the illicit sex allegations.
   A law enforcement source told The Associated Press the youth's
name was Timothy Warner, 20.
   It is not clear whether Warner managed to record anything but
Harnett said Ritter suspected at the time that he was ``possibly
being set up.'' He added that he was not concerned about anything
Ritter may have said.
   ``I think it was outrageous and disgusting for the district
attorney to outfit this kid with a wire to try to entrap Father
Ritter,'' Harnett said. ``I can tell you Father Ritter is a lot
calmer about this than I am.''
   The law enforcement source, who spoke to The Associated Press on
condition of anonymity, said the probe began after Warner took his
allegations and ``documentation'' to the district attorney's office.
   The source said the young man worked in Covenant House's
computer operation and was able to obtain printouts about
expenditures that he gave investigators.
   Investigators are looking into the matter as possible financial
misconduct, the source said.
   Morgenthau said Covenant House staffers are cooperating fully
with the investigation and no subpoenas have been necessary.
   Ritter, 62, a Franciscan priest, brought Warner to New York from
New Orleans in February after the young man told the priest he
wanted to escape prostitution. Ritter called the allegations
``scurrilous'' lies and said the young man had emotional problems.
   The Post, meanwhile, reported that a female employee at Covenant
House had said Ritter might have been involved with a second youth.
Officials of the district attorney's office refused to comment.
   Ritter has hired a criminal defense attorney, Stanley Arkin.
   ``There is no case and there never was any case'' against
Ritter, Arkin said.
   John Cardinal O'Connor, who had been silent on the case, issued
a statement in support of Ritter. ``In all my personal association
with Father Ritter and those who work with him, I have seen nothing
but self-sacrifice and commitment to the most abandoned in society.
   ``As archbishop of New York, I have held Father Ritter's work in
high esteem,'' O'Connor said.
   Ritter's Covenant House opened in 1969 after six teens showed up
at his apartment looking for a place to stay, according to
spokesmen for the shelter. Since then the organization has grown
into an $85 million-a-year operation with seven shelters in the
United States, one in Toronto, and four in Latin America.
   The organization gets more than 90 percent of its funds from
private donations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
