<FIRST>r a AM-Brandley 1stLd-Writethru a0718 12-13 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brandley, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Overturns Brandley Conviction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Montgomery County ..., with 2 grafs comment
from prosecutor; INSERTS 1 graf after 13th, `Brandley's attorney . ..,
with status of bail motions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas appeals court set aside the
conviction of death row inmate Clarence Lee Brandley on Wednesday,
more than two years after a judge ruled the black man was unfairly
tried in the slaying of a white teen-ager.
   ``This will make this Christmas as bright as can be. It was
worth the wait,'' Brandley said from the visiting area of death
row, where he spent nearly nine years and once came within six days
of execution before getting a stay.
   ``It's been a long time,'' Brandley, 38, said after he was told
the court's decision. ``I'm very thankful. I didn't know what it
was going to, when it was going to be. It's a prayer that's been
answered. It's going to take some time to sink in _ to soak in.''
   In a 6-3 decision, the appellate court said Brandley did not get
a fair trial when a jury convicted him of the 1980 strangulation
and rape of a teen-ager at Conroe High School, where Brandley was a
janitor.
   His first trial ended with a hung jury. An all-white jury found
him guilty in a second trial. Brandley's attorneys and supporters
contended the conviction was racially motivated.
   Then on Oct. 9, 1987, after a 10-day evidentiary hearing moved
from Conroe to Galveston, retired state District Judge Perry
Pickett recommended that Brandley get a new trial because the
previous two had been tainted with racism.
   In Wednesday's decision, the Austin-based appeals court said the
state's investigation of the slaying led to a trial that lacked
``the rudiments of fairness'' and ordered Brandley released to the
custody of the Montgomery County sheriff for a possible new trial.
   Montgomery County District Attorney Peter Speers said Wednesday
he was ``obviously disappointed'' with the court's ruling.
   ``I felt the conviction should have been upheld,'' said Speers,
who declined to comment further until he had reviewed the court's
decision. He planned a Thursday afternoon press conference,
possibly to discuss whether he will pursue a third trial.
   Prosecutors have maintained that Brandley is guilty and denied
allegations that he was the subject of racial discrimination.
   Brandley is the third Texas inmate in a year whose conviction
has been set aside in cases that have drawn national attention.
   The court set aside the capital murder conviction of Randall
Dale Adams, whose case was the subject of the movie ``The Thin Blue
Line,'' for the 1976 slaying of a Dallas police officer. The court
later set aside the robbery conviction of Joyce Ann Brown, a Dallas
woman who prosecutors say will be tried again for her alleged part
in the 1980 robbery of a fur store.
   The court said the outrage over the teen-ager's murder ``cannot
justify the subversion of justice that took place during the
investigation, which ultimately affected the trial of her accused
perpetrator.''
   Brandley's attorney, Mike DeGeurin of Houston, said he would ask
the court to set bail for his client and hoped Brandley would be
home for Christmas.
   The appeals court refused Wednesday afternoon to set bond, and
DeGeurin's bail motion in a Galveston district court was not ruled
on by late Wednesday afternoon from the 122nd district court in
Galveston.
   Brandley's attorneys offered evidence that police and Montgomery
County prosecutors had set out to prove that Brandley, the only
black janitor at the school, was guilty, rather than seeking the
real killer.
   Another janitor who testified for the state allegedly was
threatened by a Texas Ranger, and the state suppressed information
that could have implicated someone other than Brandley, according
to examples of improper investigation cited by the appeals court.
   ``I'm sitting here screaming having a fit, I'm so happy,'' said
Rose Upshaw of the Free Clarence Brandley Coalition, a 200-member,
Houston-based group that has fought to keep Brandley's case in the
public eye. ``We're just excited. We just can't believe it.''
   ``Thank-you Jesus!'' said Brandley's mother, Minnie Ola
Brandley, when she was told of the court's decision. ``Pray for us
and let's hope everything works out.''
   ``I'm thrilled to death for Clarence and his family,'' said
James Beathard, a fellow inmate. ``But I hope nobody out there
makes the corny comment that the system works. The system failed
Clarence. It's been eight years. And there are more and more of
these cases coming up.''
</TEXT>
