<FIRST>u a AM-LongtimeFugitive     12-13 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Longtime Fugitive,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parole Board Votes to Release Woman Who Escaped, Spent 10 Years on
Lam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who walked away from prison nearly
12 years ago and lived a model life until her arrest last year was
granted parole Wednesday and is to be released Friday.
   ``I just ask for forgiveness,'' Kay Smith, 38, told the state
parole board during a 15-minute hearing. ``I just want you to know
I have changed my way of thinking.''
   Mrs. Smith was serving a 12-year sentence for the armed robbery
of a jewelry store when she escaped. While a fugitive, she earned a
high school diploma, overcame drug and alcohol abuse, remarried and
began a successful career in real estate.
   The Department of Probation, Parole and Pardon Services board,
which rejected Mrs. Smith's request for parole in May, voted 6-1
for parole on Wednesday.
   The Severn, Md., woman is to be released Friday from the Women's
Correctional Center in Columbia.
   ``I'm sure it's going to be hard to stay in a little cell,''
knowing freedom is imminent, Mrs. Smith said at a news conference
after the vote.
   The board stipulated that Mrs. Smith will be supervised by
Maryland authorities until March 1996. She also must make
restitution to the jewelry store she robbed of $4,300 in cash and
jewelry in 1974.
   In January 1978, Mrs. Smith, then known as Pamela Rodgers,
walked away from a work-release center in Columbia, and embarked on
her new life.
   In May 1988, police tipped by her ex-husband, Daniel Rodgers,
arrested the South Carolina native at her new home in Severn. Only
then did her second husband, Ray Smith, and her sons, Daniel
Rodgers, 19, and James Rodgers, 18, learn her past.
   After her capture, South Carolina allowed Mrs. Smith to serve
her time at a prison in Jessup, Md., so she could be near her
family. She was brought to Columbia this week for the parole
hearing.
   Mrs. Smith said she plans to recruit and train real estate
agents, and try to lead a normal life without fear of the law. ``I
hope to just be settled and have a routine day with a routine job
and a routine home life,'' she said.
   Mrs. Smith expressed regret over her past, saying, ``I wish that
I could take it all back but I can't.''
   Marion Beasley, the lone dissenter in Wednesday's parole board
vote, noted that Mrs. Smith was indicted on five counts of armed
robbery and twice fled custody _ the first time in October 1975
when she walked out of a Greenville corrections facility. She was
captured the same day.
   But a police officer in Greenville who worked on Mrs. Smith's
case and the solicitor who prosecuted her last year for the escape
charge both wrote letters to the board recommending her for parole.
</TEXT>
