<FIRST>u w AM-US-Casolo 2ndLd-Writethru a0739 12-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Casolo, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casolo Release Evokes Celebration, Could Improve Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador-Casolo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lede and INSERTS 3rd graf: ``Ms Casolo,'' to reflect
her arrival in Miami</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of Jennifer Casolo said Wednesday the
announcement by Salvadoran officials of her release proved her
innocence. A senator said the move averted a rift in
U.S.-Salvadoran relations.
   Casolo, 28 and a native of Thomaston, Conn., had been accused of
storing weapons for leftist rebels in San Salvador, where President
Alfredo Cristiani said the church worker would be freed and
expelled despite his being ``morally convinced that Miss Casolo is
quilty.''
   Ms. Casolo arrived in Miami Wednesday night.
   Salvadoran officials said prosecutors had failed to develop
sufficient evidence linking Ms. Casolo to a cache of weapons found
buried behind her house the day of her arrest Nov. 26.
   ``You don't know whether to laugh because you're happy or cry
because you're happy,'' said Susanna Wallace of the Christian
Education Seminar in San Antonio, Texas, the lay church group that
sent Casolo to El Salvador to conduct non-partisan tours of the
country for church workers and visiting officials.
   Wallace, who wept as she spoke of Casolo, said, ``We hope this
helps stop the persecution of church workers that's going on in El
Salvador. ... This confirms our standing all along of her
innocence.''
   Casolo's father, John Casolo, speaking at a news conference
Wednesday in the Wethersfield, Conn., office of Sen. Christopher
Dodd, thanked volunteers and officials ``for bringing our daughter
home.'' Her mother, Audrey Casolo, added, ``I am deeply grateful to
each and every one who has believed in Jennifer and her innocence.''
   Dodd, who had spoken by telephone several times with Cristiani
over the last several days, said the decision to free Casolo was a
favorable development in relations between the two countries.
   ``I welcome this announcement for the signal it sends about the
legal system in El Salvador _ a system that has not exactly
distinguished itself for fairness or even humaneness in recent
years,'' Dodd said.
   Dodd, a moderate Democrat who has supported military aid to
Cristiani's government, praised Cristiani's handling of the matter
and stressed that he had made no threats or promises about his
support for continued U.S. aid.
   ``There were no deals. There are no conditions on aid,'' Dodd
said.
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said the release of Casolo,
``certainly avoids what could have been a disaster in terms of
their relationship with the United States.''
   He added, ``The result, whether it was judicially motivated or
politically motivated or both, is very positive.''
   But other congressmen said the resolution of Casolo's case does
not resolve problems for church workers still held in El Salvador.
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., who visited Casolo in prison, said:
   ``There are many individuals who do not receive such fortunate
treatment and who do not have the benefit of so many friends in
America. Our relief at Jennifer's release must not diminish our
concern for the many other church workers she leaves behind.''
   And Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. and an opponent of military aid to
El Salvador, predicted that persecution of other church workers
would not end.
   ``One has to ask: If the government did not have the evidence to
bring her to trial, why did it see fit to deport her?'' he
commented.
   Friends and officials viewed the decision to expel Casolo as
necessary to protect her.
   Steve Gans, a Brandeis University classmate of Casolo's, said,
``It's not a fair result in the sense that any sort of guilt would
come with that.''
   Wallace said she was ``very sensitive to how she feels about
leaving the country.'' Casolo has been in El Salvador since 1985
and has said she wanted to stay, even if that meant standing trial.
   Dodd said he too regretted the expulsion but added that, ``in
terms of personal safety, (it) is probably in Jennifer's best
interest.''
</TEXT>
