<DOCNO> AP891213-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DrugLegalization 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Legalization, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0730,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Levels Harsh Criticism of Drug Legalization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 7th graf: ``Vice President,'' with Quayle comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett on Wednesday described the
views of those who advocate the legalization of drugs as ``stupid
and morally atrocious.''
   ``It doesn't make any sense,'' Bennett, director of the Office
of National Drug Control Policy, said in an interview.
   ``It is becoming something of a fashion to believe this in
certain circles of opinion. But even though it's fashionable, it's
still every bit as dumb and compassionless as it was before.''
   Bennett pressed his counter-offensive against the increasingly
outspoken ranks of those arguing for drug legalization a day after
U.S. District Judge Robert W. Sweet said drugs _ including cocaine
and heroin _ should be legalized, taxed and dispensed by the state
because the war on narcotics is being lost.
   Sweet, a Republican and former prosecutor appointed by President
Carter as a trial judge in the Southern District of New York, said
it was ``time to abolish the prohibition _ to cease treating
indulgence in mind-alteration as a crime.''
   Bennett, who denounced such views in a speech at Harvard
University on Monday, said Wednesday that he is unswayed by the
growth in the number of legalization advocates or by the fact that
they cut across the political spectrum and include, for the first
time, a federal judge.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, visiting Kansas City, said the judge
was ``simply out of step with mainstream America ... We totally
reject the idea that the way to solve the drug problem challenging
America is to simply roll over and legalize it. It's not going to
happen in the Bush administration.''
   ``Judges aren't any more immune to ignorance than people in
other professions,'' Bennett said.
   ``If he doesn't like his work, if he's tired of sentencing
people, he should find another line of work,'' Bennett said about
Sweet. ``It's better to have clogged courts ... than crowded,
jammed pediatric wards of cocaine babies, which we will have a lot
more of if we take his proposal seriously.''
   The legalization argument ``is as stupid and morally atrocious
as it ever was,'' Bennett said.
   Sweet, in Tuesday's speech before the New Yrk Cosmopolitan Club,
said the result of drug legalization ``would be the elimination of
the profit motive, the gangs, the drug dealers. Obviously, the
model is the repeal of Prohibition and the end of Al Capone and
Dutch Shultz.''
   Sweet was harshly criticized by other officials, including Sen.
Alfonse D-Amato, R-N.Y.
   ``Judge Sweet is absolutely wrong,'' D'Amato said. ``If his
policy were accepted, he would be consigning millions of more to
lives of addictions. He would be responsible for the deaths of
millions more. ... It is a policy that is irresponsible.''
   Sterling Johnson Jr., the special New York state prosecutor for
narcotics, agreed with D'Amato.
   ``This is a classic case of Sweet going sour,'' Johnson said.
   Pat Walsh, Sweet's secretary, said the judge was conducting a
trial Wednesday and was not available for comment.
   The ranks of drug legalization advocates include conservative
political commentator William F. Buckley, economist Milton Friedman
and Baltimore's Democratic Mayor Kurt Schmoke.
   President Reagan's Secretary of State George P. Shultz rattled
the Bush administration by stating similar views in a speech given
at Stanford University and excerpted in the Wall Street Journal in
October.
   Bennett said he doesn't believe the arguments will ``change the
basic views of most Americans. They've seen it up close. Anybody
who has seen a child go through this is not likely to be moved by
this abstract argument.''
   Bennett said he opposes legalizing any kind of drug, even
marijuana, despite the fact that he doesn't believe it's more
harmful than alcohol.
   ``The last thing I would want to do is recommend the wider use
of a drug that makes young people stupid. ... We have enough of a
problem with liquor, thank you.''
   But he's not advocating a return to Prohibition: ``We can't go
back. Society's made a judgment it's OK. But we certainly don't
have to compound the problem.''
</TEXT>
