<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Apartheid     12-13 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Apartheid,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Calls for Lifting Sanctions to End Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain said Wednesday the way to end
apartheid in South Africa is by gradually lifting economic
sanctions as the government dismantles its segregation system
rather than imposing a trade embargo.
   Attempts to isolate the government of South African President
F.W. de Klerk are not the answer, British Ambassador Sir Crispin
Tickell told the General Assembly's Special Session on Apartheid.
   ``Nor are sanctions. ... They certainly weaken the South African
economy, and in doing so they increase misery and poverty, in
particular among the most vulnerable parts of the community,'' its
black majority, he said.
   ``Their political effect is to increase resistance to change
rather than to encourage it,'' Tickell said. ``When Mr. de Klerk
does take the necessary steps, we believe it would then be right to
lift some of the measures imposed by the international community,
so as to acknowledge progress and encourage South Africa to proceed
further down the path of dialogue.''
   Tickell's advice received polite applause; in the 159-member
General Assembly, the overwhelming majority of nations believe
South Africa is implementing limited reforms only in response to
the limited sanctions imposed so far.
   Most nations favor a total, mandatory trade embargo against
South Africa, butthe United States and Britain have used their veto
power in the Security Council to consistently block such moves.
   A General Assembly call for all nations to sever economic,
military, sports and cultural links with South Africa also has met
with partial success.
   Apartheid has established a racially segregated society in which
the 28 million South African blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
