<FIRST>r a AM-ManMauled     12-13 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Man Mauled,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy Awaited on Man Mauled by Dogs</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   DULZURA, Calif. _ The death of a man apparently mauled by a pack
of dogs could lead to a criminal investigation of the animals'
owners, whose fearful neighbors had complained about marauding
dogs, the sheriff's office said.
   Preliminary findings of the autopsy Wednesday will be available
Thursday morning, but if it attributes 69-year-old Roy Johnson's
death to the dogs, the criminal probe would ensue, Sheriff's Lt.
John Tenwolde said Wednesday.
   ``A lot of questions need to be asked before we can speculate
about what the outcome is going to be,'' Tenwolde said.
   On Tuesday, Johnson was attacked near the Charles Duarte Ranch,
where the dogs apparently lived, while he was walking to work.
   Duarte was unavailable for comment, but his wife, Cindy, said:
``It has never happened before. I can't imagine what happened.''
   Bill Delany, caretaker of the Monahan Ranch where Johnson
worked, found the body after driving to pick up his newspaper at
his mailbox off the highway.
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Delany said. ``He appeared to have been
eaten alive. That's the only way to describe it. He was eaten
alive. I just knew he was gone.''
   John Slough, an off-duty San Diego policeman who lives nearby,
went to investigate what he thought was a dogfight and found two
dogs picking at the body. They attacked him and he shot and killed
one and wounded another, police said.
   Sally Hazzard, head of the San Diego County Animal Control
Department, said seven dogs licensed to Duarte had been impounded.
   Hazzard said the dog wounded by Slough was being treated by
department veterinarians. She said all the dogs would remain in
department custody.
   ``The department has had contacts with Mr. Duarte and his dogs
prior to the unfortunate incident and all documentation relative to
those contacts have been forwarded to the sheriff's homicide
unit,'' Hazzard said.
   Johnson had complained in the past about the unrestrained dogs
and family members said he had been bitten on at least one other
occassion.
   His friends and relatives also said the dogs' owners have
refused repeated requests to keep their pets fenced in or on
leashes.
   Muriel Curtis, a neighbor, said she no longer walks along the
dirt roads because of the dogs.
   ``Those dogs were so vicious that, even when they were behind a
fence, my dogs panicked,'' Curtis said. ``I had to give up my walks
because those dogs were so threatening.''
   San Diego police investigator Pete Solomonsen, who is married to
Johnson's niece, Deanne, said the dogs often run in a pack of six
to 12, menacing neighbors and passers-by.
   Delany said: ``The dogs always chase my truck, and they've
attacked me on my horse.''
</TEXT>
