<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-13 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia's Croatian Republic Endorses Free Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAGREB, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communist congress endorsed a
multiparty system and free elections for Croatia Wednesday, opening
the way for a non-communist government in Yugoslavia's
second-largest republic for the first time in 44 years.
   The congress also elected Ivica Racan, 49, as new leader of the
Croatian Communist Party. Racan, who has publicly advocated radical
democratic reforms within communist Yugoslavia, received 41 votes
in a secret ballot in the Central Committee. The only other
candidate, Ivo Druzic, received 29 votes.
   Dragutin Dimitrovic, a member of the party's decision-making
Central Committee, said the party by its actions ``is showing its
readiness to put its platform to the public for approval.''
   Twelve burgeoning political opposition movements already exist
in the central Yugoslav republic and seek official legalization.
   Parliamentary elections are scheduled in April.
   Yugoslavia is in its worst crisis since the communists
consolidated power in 1945. The question of pluralism instead of
continued one-party rule is straining already tenuous ties between
some republics and a moribund economy heightens tensions.
   The liberal northern republic of Slovenia was until now the only
of Yugoslavia's six constituent regions to openly advocate
introduction of Western-style democracy.
   The communist leadership of Serbia, the largest republic,
vehemently opposes introduction of a multiparty system both in
Serbia and federally.
   Last month, Serbia severed all business and official ties with
Slovenia.
</TEXT>
