<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessTeacher     12-13 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Teacher,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Was Homeless Gets Teaching Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An electrician who slept on the streets after
losing his job and his family said he won a position as a teacher
at a technical school because he refused to give up hope.
   Allen Delano Johnson, 42, said he learned where to get free
coffee and find shelter while living on the street, but kept
thinking there must be a way out.
   ``I can still remember that I wanted to find a job. But how? I
stunk and was dirty,'' Johnson said recently. ``Who in his right
mind would hire me?
   ``I finally went to a shelter because I knew the people who ran
them knew how to help me get back on my feet.''
   Johnson isn't homeless any more. He learned new skills through
Jubilee Soup Kitchen's career development program, and teaches
commercial and residential electrical installation at Triangle Tech
School.
   Johnson said he found his life going into a tailspin after
returning to his native Lorain, Ohio, in 1984 from the San
Francisco Bay Area, where he'd worked as an electrician for years.
   His electrical contracting business in Lorain failed, and a
breakup with his wife, June, followed.
   Johnson came to Pittsburgh almost three years ago because he had
relatives in the city, but said he was unable to break into the
skilled electrician's field.
   ``Then, when I filled out applications for lower paying jobs,
they would look at my trade experience and tell me I was
overqualified,'' he said. ``I finally got some odd jobs through a
temporary job placement service by lying on my application and
saying that my only skill was as a dishwasher.''
   Johnson took his first step back when a caseworker introduced
him to Jubilees' 12-week career program.
   He was offered the job at Triangle Tech even though he had no
teaching experience.
   Ralph Hathaway of Triangle Tech said Johnson's positive attitude
was a deciding factor when he hired him to start work Oct. 2.
   ``He wasn't mad at the world because of what happened to him,''
he said. ``He just wanted to put it all behind him and get on again
with his life.''
   Johnson said he's trying to restore relationships with his sons
_ Aaron, 23; Anthony, 20; and Allen, 18 _ all in California after
losing touch with them.
   ``It's hard for me to pick up my relationships with them again
because I'll have to tell them what happened to me,'' he said.
``That's hard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
