<FIRST>u a AM-Salvador-Casolo 4thLd-Writethru a0780 12-13 1037</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Casolo, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0780,1064</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jennifer Casolo Arrives In U.S. After Salvador Deports Her</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0797 with `a' category code. Eds: SUBS grafs 6-10, `President
Alfredo ..., with 10 grafs to UPDATE with quote from mother, travel plans
changed, details and quote from Miami news conference, Conn. preparations
for homecoming; picks up 11th graf: `Christiani told ...; SUBS 21st graf:
`Christiani said ..., to DELETE outdated first reference to Dodd.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut woman accused of storing arms in her
garden for leftist rebels returned to the United States on
Wednesday night after being freed from prison and deported from
war-ravaged El Salvador.
   ``I don't think I've suffered as terribly as thousands of
Salvadorans have suffered here,'' Jennifer Casolo, 28, said in El
Salvador before boarding a commercial flight to Miami 2{ weeks
after she was jailed on terrorism charges.
   Accompanied by U.S. Ambassador William Walker at Comalapa
International Airport, Casolo insisted on her innocence when she
was allowed to speak briefly with a few pool reporters.
   She said she signed a release statement acknowledging she was
arrested and imprisoned on suspicion of having stored weapons and
ammunition for rebels, but added, ``My position was always that I
was innocent.'' Casolo said she believed her release supports that
contention.
   She telephoned her parents in Thomaston, Conn., from the
airport. Walker said she told ``them she'll be home for
Christmas.'' He also said she had expressed the desire to return to
El Salvador someday.
   ``She sounded confident, her voice was loud and clear,'' said
her mother, Audrey Casolo, after talking with her daughter. ``She
sounded like a happy person. She said she loved me very much.''
   President Alfredo Cristiani said earlier there was not enough
evidence to continue holding Casolo.
   She was released into the custody of the ambassador, who picked
her up in a black Cadillac escorted by Jeeps on Wednesday at the
women's prison at Ilopango on the eastern outskirts of the capital.
   The caravan went to the airport and entered through a restricted
entrance. Reporters were not allowed access either at the prison or
airport.
   Casolo was put on an Eastern Airlines flight to Miami and
ushered to an undisclosed location upon her arrival, said the Rev.
Daniel Long, chairman of Christian Education Seminars, who traveled
with her on the plane.
   ``It was a very emotional time for her, being taken straight
from the prison to the airport and deported, because of her love
for the people and the country of El Salvador,'' Long said.
   She decided late Wednesday to remain in Florida and not return
immediately to her home in Connecticut, according to staffers for
Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who has followed the case.
   Her travel plans beyond that were undecided, but church
officials at the Miami International Airport news conference said
Casolo planned to hold a news conference sometime Thursday.
   In Connecticut, friends and well-wishers in her hometown
prepared for her homecoming. Susan Abbott, a close high school
friend of Ms. Casolo's, put up a sign on the town green that said,
``Welcome Home, Jennifer. We Love You.''
   Cristiani told a news conference he thought Casolo probably had
cooperated with rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, who have fought U.S.-supported governments for 10 years and
launched a major urban offensive in San Salvador last month.
   ``I am morally convinced that Miss Casolo is guilty,'' he said.
The case against Casolo will proceed and she was asked to remain
available in case judicial authorities need to question her
further, Cristiani said.
   ``Evidence _ be it incriminating or exculpating _ will continue
to be gathered,'' the president said. ``If the evidence against her
becomes sufficient, she will be summoned to return for trial.''
   He acknowledged that little could be done to make her come back
to El Salvador.
   Casolo and two Salvadoran friends were arrested Nov. 26 in a
police raid on her house. She was charged with terrorism,
possessing weapons of war and criminal association, all of which
she denied. There was no immediate word on the cases against those
two Salvadorans.
   In the walled garden behind the house, police said, they dug up
103 mortar shells, 213 blocks of dynamite, 405 detonators, 150 feet
of slow-burning fuse and 21,945 rounds of ammunition for
Soviet-made automatic rifles.
   She said she did not know how the materiel got into the yard of
her rented home on the northwestern edge of San Salvador.
   Cristiani denied his rightist administration was pressured to
free Casolo by the United States, the key financial supporter of
his government.
   ``The judge's decision to release her is strictly judicial,'' he
said. ``It is a political decision that we have made to deport
her.''
   Judge Guillermo Romero of the criminal court handled the case.
   Cristiani said he spoke with Sen. Dodd, who telephoned several
times to ask about the case, but ``at no time did Sen. Dodd try to
exert pressure. Indeed, his position was that, if there was
sufficient proof against her, her trial should go forward.''
   Dodd said earlier Wednesday he was told in telephone
conversations with Salvadoran officials, including Cristiani, that
Casolo would be freed and expelled by Thursday afternoon.
   A statement issued by his office said Cristiani ``informs me
that the judge in her case has ultimately concluded the charges
against Jennifer were not fully supported by the evidence, and that
she could not thus be fairly prosecuted under Salvadoran law.''
   Casolo spent five years in El Salvador, working for Christian
Education Seminars, which organizes tours for Americans to learn
about the civil war.
   Salvador Ibarra, her defense lawyer, filed a writ Monday
requesting her release for lack of evidence. Cristiani said the
judge ruled favorably on the writ.
   Her last U.S. residence was in Seattle, and Rep. Jim McDermott,
D-Wash, said Wednesday: ``I am glad for Jennifer's sake that she
has been released because there were serious questions about the
ability of the Salvadoran judicial system to provide her a fair
trial.
   ``There are many individuals who do not have the benefit of so
many friends in America. Our relief at Jennifer's release must not
diminish our concern for the many other church workers she leaves
behind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
