<FIRST>r i AM-Sikh-Bombing     12-13 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sikh-Bombing,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Wanted in Japanese Airport Bombing Extradited to Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sikh wanted in connection
with a 1985 bombing that killed two baggage-handlers unloading a
Canadian jet at Narita Airport near Tokyo was extradited to Canada
on Wednesday.
   Inderjit Singh Reyat, 37, who worked in Canada as an auto
electrician before moving to Coventry, England, in 1986, appeared
briefly in Supreme Court in Vancouver after arriving on a flight
from London.
   Reyat was arrested in England in February 1988 and fought
extradition until the House of Lords, Britain's highest legal body,
refused to consider his appeal.
   He faces two charges of manslaughter and five counts of
possessing explosives.
   Evidence presented during his extradition battle indicated a
bomb exploded and killed two Japanese baggage handlers on June 23,
1985, as luggage was being unloaded at Narita from a Canadian
Pacific Air flight that had just arrived from Vancouver.
   The evidence indicated the suitcase bomb was to be transferred
to an Air India flight to Bangkok, Thailand, and Bombay, India.
   On the same day, an Air India flight from Toronto and Montreal
to Bombay via London blew apart off Ireland, killing all 329 people
on board.
   Sikh separatists have waged a campaign of violence against the
Indian government, demanding an independent homeland for their
religious minority.
</TEXT>
