<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Clayburgh Adv14   12-13 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Clayburgh, Adv 14,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, Dec. 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jill Clayburgh Fights Back in CBS Movie `Fear Stalk'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jill Clayburgh, as a strong-willed soap opera
producer, rashly decides to fight back when a psychopathic computer
hacker undermines her life in the CBS movie ``Fear Stalk.''
   Her character, Ally Maynard, shuns the advice of friends and
battles this dangerous man on his own terms.
   ``He steals her purse and belongings and gets the information he
needs to tap into her life through the computer,'' said Clayburgh.
``He takes her money, he victimizes her. Then, against advice, she
fights back. It escalates into a deadly competition. He's never
been challenged before.''
   ``Fear Stalk'' also stars Stephen Macht as her boyfriend and the
soap's director, and Sada Thompson as her mother. It will be
telecast Sunday.
   ``Ally has computers in her office and home,'' said Clayburgh.
``The scripts for the soap opera come in to her by computer. Ellen
Weston, who wrote the movie, worked in soaps while she put herself
through law school. She creates an interesting milieu. She creates
a sort of parallel between what's going on on the soap opera and
what's happening to me.''
   Early in her career, Clayburgh worked on the soap opera ``Search
For Tomorrow.''
   ``It's so hard to learn all those lines,'' she said. ``But for
my first six months I was in bed and communicated only by blinking
my eyes. I had been in an accident. When I finally came out of the
coma, I kept saying, `Oh, thank you, doctor. Thank you for saving
my life.' The cast and crew called me `Grateful Grace.'''
   She completed work on ``Search For Tomorrow'' at 12:30 p.m. and
had the rest of the day to appear in plays and audition for
commercials.
   Clayburgh made ``Fear Stalk'' on location in Los Angeles and was
preparing to return to her home north of New York City. She wanted
to get back in time to see daughter Lily, 7, perform in ``The
Nutcracker'' with the Stamford Ballet. Clayburgh is married to
playwright David Rabe and has a 4-year-old son, Michael, and a
17-year-old stepson, Jason.
   She has starred in such feature films as ``An Unmarried Woman,''
``Silver Streak,'' ``Starting Over,'' ``Luna,'' ``First Monday in
October,'' ``I'm Dancing As Fast As I Can,'' and ``Portnoy's
Complaint.''
   Her last film, ``Shy People'' in 1987, took her to Louisiana.
She played a photojournalist doing a story in the bayou country.
``It was incredibly difficult because we had to go in and out by
boat,'' she recalls. ``It was humid and the mosquitoes were
terrible. But I loved the people and the wonderful Cajun culture.''
   Lately, she's been working more in television. She has a movie
for ABC, ``Unspeakable Acts,'' based on a child abuse case. She
plays a psychologist who finds a way to interview the children
without influencing their testimony.
   Past TV movies include ``Hustling,'' ``Griffin and Phoenix: A
Love Story,'' ``Miles To Go'' and ``Who Gets the Friends.''
   ``I've been offered series but I've turned them down,'' she
said. ``I'm not ready yet to put in that much time away from the
kids. I am looking into a few comedy series for the future. I'm
very happy doing TV movies, however, and I may not do a series at
all.
   ``Doing a series is steady work and comedy is a lot of fun.
Comedy is something you don't get in a TV movie. Also, the idea of
working with an audience doing a series is very appealing.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
      Elsewhere in television:
   NEXT, A BRADY CHANNEL? _ ``The Bradys'' are coming back to
television in a new hour-long series for CBS. The show, created by
Sherwood Schwartz, is one of those phenomena that just keeps coming
back. It first aired on ABC as ``The Brady Bunch'' in 1969-74.
``The Brady Bunch Hour'' was on ABC in 1977. ``The Brady Kids'' was
an animated Saturday morning series on ABC from 1972-74. ``The
Brady Brides'' ran on NBC in 1981. There have been several movies,
including ``A Very Brady Christmas'' last year on CBS.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday PMs, Dec. 14</NOTE>
