<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv14   12-13 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 14,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Dec. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Workers Will Want More in 1990, Says Chamber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Losing the fight to prevent an increase in the
minimum wage has left the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in a somewhat
sullen mood about the immediate economic consequences.
   It will, the chamber says, result in the loss of hundreds of
thousands of job opportunities, ignite a new round of wage
inflation, raise the deficit, compromise U.S. competitiveness and
force some companies to forego expansion.
   The chamber was in the forefront of opposition to the increase,
which takes the hourly minimum to $4.25 from $3.35, and it still
smarts from the defeat, saying it resulted when ``sound economics
fell victim to political expediency.''
   More recently it expressed its ire in The Business Advocate, a
monthly newspaper delivered to members and opinion leaders, saying
the inrease will have a ripple effect on workers in higher-paying
jobs.
   ``When wages at one level increase, employees at higher levels
place a new and greater value on their services,'' said Bob Martin,
director of the chamber's Employee Relations Policy Center.
   He said numerous studies concur in his finding that the increase
will cost jobs. He cited one by the Congressional Budget Office
that indicated between 125,000 and 800,000 jobs would be lost if
the rate were raised to $4.55 as once proposed.
   Congress and the White House agreed, however, to a lesser
increase, bringing the minimum to $3.80 on April 1, 1990 and to
$4.25 one year later. It also permits a lower, short-term training
wage for some teenagers.
   Martin cites a 1981 report by the Minimum Wage Study Commission,
named by former President Carter, that found that each 10 percent
increase in the minimum wage has the potential to raise the
nation's payroll by 0.76 percent.
   Since the new law will raise the wage 27 percent, the Business
Advocate article concludes that labor costs will rise by about 2.05
percent, or more than $46 billion.
   Martin did express satisfaction that ``though we lost the last
battle, we saved businesses more than $9 billion by holding off a
wage increase for the past three years,'' and that it helped push
through a training wage.
   The latter, opposed by organized labor, will allow employers to
pay a lower minimum wage for three months to first-time workers
under age 20. The training wage of $3.35 would begin April 1, 1990,
rising to $3.61 a year later.
   While the minimum wage puts a base under minimum wages in much
of the nation, it is already exceeded in other areas, with some
food outlets already paying $6 an hour or even more for unskilled
workers.
   The chamber article didn't address another criticism of the
higher minimum, one made by William Dunkelberg, dean of Temple
University's business school, that the increases might not be as
effective as believed in reducing poverty levels.
   Dunkelberg testified during hearings held prior to the law's
signing on Nov. 17 that many earning the minimum are not primary
breadwinners in their families but instead are relatively
comfortable people earning second incomes.
   Regardless of who gets the minimum wage, and the automatic
increases that lift it over the next two years, the chamber said it
expects those earning above the minimum are likely, as a
consequence of the law, to want more.
   ``Expect wage pressure,'' it warned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Dec. 14.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Flight103-Lockerbie Adv17   12-13 1174</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Lockerbie, Adv 17,1204</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Town Torn Between Forgetting and Remembering Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1 of Dec. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crater of Pan Am Flight 103, the
deepest, most visible scar on the town where it fell, is
disappearing under new homes.
   At the end of November, contractors began building 11 houses in
Sherwood Crescent where the falling wreckage of the Boeing 747
killed 11 residents of Lockerbie last Dec. 21, the final deaths of
a terrorist bombing that killed the 259 passengers and crew of
Flight 103.
   ``Some people needed an awful lot of sustaining just to get to
this week,'' said Malcolm McGeorge, who directs a team of social
workers in the town.
   ``The frustration that it has taken so long to rebuild has been
very great, crushing for some people. Others have little interest,
because they don't really want to go back, but feel they have to go
back because so much effort has been put in by so many people.''
   The crater has been filled and the street restored. Burnt shells
of houses have been pulled down, and only muddy vacant lots betray
the extent of the destruction.
   The construction reflects the determination to wipe out all
traces of the disaster. Along the sidewalk of Sherwood Crescent,
however, a lone pot of flowers testifies to a town torn between
remembrance and forgetting.
   Lockerbie lost its quiet obscurity just after 7:03 that cold
Wednesday night, when explosives hidden in a radio-cassette
recorder shattered the Pan Am jet ``Maid of the Seas.'' At 36
seconds past 7:03, the Eskdalemuir Observatory 15 miles from
Lockerbie recorded seismic shocks, apparently caused by the falling
wreckage.
   The main part of the fuselage, with enough jet fuel to push a
747 from Scotland to New York, exploded in Sherwood Crescent.
Shattered metal and flaming fuel spewed over dozens of houses, and
debris blocked traffic on the four-lane north-south highway.
   A forward portion of the fuselage landed across town in Rosebank
Crescent. The plane's nose fell 3 miles from town, across the road
from the stone church at Tundergarth.
   ``The night it happened, one of the first things I saw was the
body of a child hanging in a tree,'' said Ronnie Hall, who lives in
the Rosebank area. ``That child will never leave me.''
   The town's population of 3,500 nearly doubled with the influx of
a thousand police officers, 700 military personnel, 500 other
volunteer and support workers, and hundreds of reporters,
photographers and camera crews.
   Sheep now graze placidly where the plane's nose fell and the two
shattered houses in Rosebank Crescent have been rebuilt, but the
memories remain.
   ``When you think the number of houses (in Rosebank) that face in
that small area where 61 bodies were found ... there must be more
than a hundred people who could not avoid seeing that mayhem,''
McGeorge said.
   Sandy Pelling, assistant director of social work for the
Dumfries and Galloway Regional Council, recalled one family that
``identified with the young boy that was lying in their garden for
two days _ they started grieving for him, they wanted to know his
name.''
   Robert Hunter, whose home was 120 yards from the Sherwood
Crescent crater, brought his family back to the house two days
after the disaster. ``We wanted back in, to settle the kids if
nothing else,'' he said.
   Repairs put them out of the house for six weeks, however, and it
was 10 months before the job was complete. But they never thought
of moving, he said.
   Before talking with a reporter, Hunter shooed his daughters out
of the parlor. Talk of the disaster upsets them, he said, and with
the onset of winter he realized his older daughter, now 5, had
become afraid of the dark.
   ``We do talk about it with them on their own. They understand
what happened,'' he said.
   In the months after the disaster, some adults as well as
children had difficulty sleeping, McGeorge said.
   ``There were reports of children not sleeping or having
nightmares or playing what their parents thought were rather
bizarre, unsavory games _ playing airplanes and crashing them and
so on,'' he said. ``But that's definitely understandable, and
people were encouraged to understand that was OK, that it was a way
of dealing with it.''
   He said there have been no reports of children developing
serious behavioral problems.
   ``I think the people with the serious and lasting problems are
in the uniformed services ... just because of what they had to do
in the recovery of bodies,'' McGeorge said.
   The torn bodies reawakened some men's memories of combat
service, in one case going back to World War I, he said. For some
women, the disaster brought back moments of great personal loss _
of a husband, a child or parents.
   ``One of the things you hear people say is that they don't feel
safe anymore. If it happened once it can happen again,'' McGeorge
said. ``Some of them are quite unable to use public transport _
buses or trains. Airplanes are just out of the question.''
   McGeorge said some residents have admitted fearing the dark, or
the noise of a passing truck or express train. When one Lockerbie
man took a train to London, his wife kept the television on all day
expecting news of a rail disaster.
   Reflecting on the work in Lockerbie, Pelling talks about ``the
timelessness of disaster'' for survivors.
   ``It is there, it has happened, it is always going to be
there,'' he said. ``While they desperately want to get this episode
behind them and feel they are going forward, they are not going to
be able to shake off the night of the 21st in quite as easy terms.''
   Agencies that came to help are thinking now of leaving.
   ``I think we should melt away. We're another scar of the
disaster,'' said Alex McElroy, who directs the Community Support
office set up by the regional council.
   McElroy's office runs by two clocks, one set on U.S. Eastern
Standard Time because some of its contacts are with authorities and
insurors in the United States as well as with relatives of the
American victims.
   The approach of the anniversary made memories unavoidable. On
the afternoon of Dec. 21, the town will dedicate a monument in the
Dryfesdale Cemetery bearing the names of the 270 dead. A memorial
service will be held that night outside the town hall, used a year
ago as a temporary mortuary. Some American relatives of victims
plan to attend.
   ``We're hoping that after the 21st we can get back and have our
town to ourselves,'' said Valerie Moloney, who works with a
childrens' group formed after the disaster.
   Hugh Young, a member of the district council, agreed. ``I think
they see it as a watershed, a time for looking forward again. I
think people hope (the anniversary) will be an end to the media
attention.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
