<FIRST>s i BC-Flight103-TownProjects Adv17   12-13 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Town Projects, Adv 17,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Not Limiting Rebuilding to Crash Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Flight 103-Lockerbie, b0543</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wrenching disaster of Pan Am
Flight 103 had an unexpected side effect for this small market town.
   The rebuilding effort has given residents the impetus to push
for some renewal projects.
   Beyond paying to rebuild destroyed homes and other essential
repairs, the local government has borrowed money to refurbish
dozens of units of public housing.
   Residents also pushed for better lights and street repairs, and
got them. And now they are pressing plans for a park on the site of
an abandoned factory.
   ``We just took a good look at ourselves and decided we were
being badly done by,'' said Ronnie Hall, vice chairman of a
residents committee in the Rosebank area.
   ``We're grasping the opportunity, because now the regional
council is very sympathetic to requests from Lockerbie,'' Hall
said. ``I think they are things we should have pushed for years
ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
