<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Flight103-Investigation Adv17   12-13 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Investigation, Adv 17,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Suspect Named in International Hunt for Pan Am Bombers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Flight 103-Lockerbie, b0543</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 12 months, police have doggedly sought the
bombers of Pan Am Flight 103 but said little officially about the
progress of their international manhunt.
   Here's what they have confirmed and what news reports have said
following the explosion and crash that killed all 259 people on the
plane and 11 on the ground last Dec. 21:
   _One week after the disaster, Britain's Department of Transport
confirmed a bomb blew up the Boeing 747 and said investigators had
found evidence of a powerful plastic explosive.
   _In February, Scottish police said the bomb was planted in a
Toshiba radio-cassette player and probably checked in as hold
baggage in Frankfurt, West Germany, where Flight 103 originated.
West German police had seized similar bombs in October 1988 and
arrested 16 members of a Palestinian group. All but two were soon
released, including Marwan Khreesat, who some people believe
assembled the bomb in Frankfurt.
   _News reports have frequently pointed to the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, a radical Palestinian
group based in Syria, as the leading suspect. The group's leader,
Ahmed Jibril, repeatedly has denied involvement but has also
reportedly boasted he was paid by Iran to avenge the downing of an
Iranian airliner by a U.S. warship. Hafez Dalkamoni, one of
Jibril's top aides, is one of the two suspects still held in West
Germany.
   _Some news reports said the bomb was smuggled to Malta, checked
onto an Air Malta flight to Frankfurt and transferred to Pan Am
without an accompanying passenger. Others say the bomb began its
journey in Larnaca, Cyprus, in a suitcase switched with one
belonging to U.S. intelligence officers returning home after
looking for American hostages in Lebanon.
   _A court in Uppsala, Sweden, last month identified Mohammed Abu
Talb, a member of the Palestine Popular Struggle Front, another
radical faction, as a suspect in the Flight 103 bombing. Scottish
police were permitted to remove clothing from his Sweden apartment,
reportedly to compare with shreds of clothing found in the
wreckage. Abu Talb is awaiting verdicts, due Dec. 21, on charges of
murder and attempted murder in connection with four bombings in
northern Europe. Court documents show he was in Malta in October
1988.
   _U.S. Rep. James Traficant Jr. of Ohio released portions of a
report, said to have been prepared for Pan Am's insurance
underwriters, that alleges the terrorists got the bomb aboard the
plane through a CIA-protected drug smuggling ring at Frankfurt
airport. The CIA called the allegations nonsense.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
