<DOCNO> AP891213-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Drugs-Cancer Adv17   12-13 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs-Cancer, Adv 17,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parents of Dying Girl Struggled To Get Morphine To Ease Her Pain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Drug Diversion, b0547</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX19 of Dec. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dewey and Matilda Houck have seen the
drug war from the other side, fighting a sometimes futile battle to
obtain painkillers for a 5-year-old daughter being destroyed by
cancer.
   They raced to hospitals at all hours of the day and night to get
prescriptions for morphine that were good only for 48 hours,
searched the area for pharmacies that would risk the possibility of
a break-in to carry the drug, and tried to comfort their terrified
daughter when she asked the unanswerable question: ``Why does this
have to happen to me?''
   ``It is tragic enough to lose a child, but it's awful to live
with the terror of her agony,'' Matilda said in an interview at her
home in this Washington, D.C., suburb.
   Kendra Laurel Houck was born Oct. 28, 1983; she died March 3,
1989. A six-month failure by doctors to diagnose her neural
blastoma meant that when it was discovered in August 1986, the only
options left were experimental treatments. The doctors told the
Houcks their only child would have had a good chance of recovery
had the cancer been diagnosed earlier.
   Instead, for the next 2{ years, the family suffered through
experimental treatments, enjoyed a 10-month remission, doled out
dosages first of codeine and Demerol and later morphine, celebrated
Kendra's fifth birthday and learned all about the nation's drug
laws.
   Two days after Halloween 1988, Kendra's condition deteriorated
dramatically.
   ``From that day on, it became morphine ... and even that wasn't
real effective,'' said Dewey.
   ``She would be screaming on morphine,'' said Matilda, a gentle
woman whose voice wavered as she tried to restrain tears. ``It just
wasn't cutting the pain. She was conscious and in agony.''
   By the time Kendra died, her eyes pressed open day and night by
a brain tumor, she was taking more than 100 milligrams of morphine
every four hours.
   To Dewey, ``the real issue ... is access'' to morphine.
   The Houcks found that very few pharmacies carry the drug out of
fear of robberies; those that do generally have very little on hand
for the same reason. Dewey said pharmacies refused to tell him over
the phone whether they carried morphine because they feared a
holdup.
   The prescriptions were good only for 48 hours, which meant that
in times of need, they would race to Children's Hospital in
Washington to get one from the doctors who knew Kendra's condition.
But they could not get the morphine there because Kendra was at
home, not in the hospital.
   Eventually, they found a pharmacist who knew their situation and
would have the morphine ready when they needed it. He sold it to
them at cost.
   Even then, the price was $494 for a typical three-day supply,
Matilda said.
   ``I felt like the sick and dying are paying the price for our
drug war,'' she said.
   These are not radical, anti-establishment people. They did not
attempt illicit street buys of heroin for Kendra's pain _ something
experts say would not have helped her _ or marijuana for her nausea.
   ``That would have been an option to us had we chosen to do it in
an outlaw way,'' Dewey said, but it would have been ``100 percent
inconsistent'' with their lifestyle. In addition, he said, they
were concerned how Kendra's mix of drugs, had it included heroin or
marijuana, would have affected her.
   Merely handling the morphine seemed odd to Dewey.
   ``It was strange to fool with this stuff that was verboten,'' he
said. ``We had jugs full of it and we could not get enough'' for
Kendra.
   After Kendra died, the nurse immediately cleared out all the
leftover controlled substances, destroying them in the presence of
another health-care professional.
   ``I didn't understand why I couldn't just flush it down the
toilet with the Valium'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891213-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-The'80s-TenYears 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Ten Years, 1st Ld-Writethru,0979</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Year by Year, an Eventful Decade in Review</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads b0778-0779-0780, sent Dec. 5. UPDATES 1989 with new entries;
CORRECTS death tolls in 1980 MGM fire to 87 sted 84; in 1987 Dona Paz sinking
to more than 3,000 dead sted 1,600; CORRECTS damages in 1989 San Francisco
quake to $7 billion sted $17 billion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1980s began in crisis: the crisis of the hostages, the
crisis of Afghanistan, the crisis of striking shipyard workers in
Poland. The decade is now ending with the unexpected: the sight of
communism's walls crumbling, of new powers rising in the world, of
hostages still held.
   Here is a chronology of an eventful 10 years, years of tumult,
disaster and accomplishment:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<NOTE>AMERICA HELD HOSTAGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 4 _ President Carter announces sanctions, including grain
embargo and boycott of Moscow Summer Olympics, to protest Soviet
intervention in Afghanistan.
   APRIL _ More than 125,000 exiles begin arriving in U.S. from
Cuba during boatlift operation between Cuban port of Mariel and Key
West, Fla.
   APRIL 24 _ U.S. military operation to rescue 52 American
hostages in Iran fails. Eight U.S. servicemen killed when two
aircraft collide in Iranian desert.
   MAY 18 _ Mount St. Helens volcano in Washington state erupts,
hurling ash and darkening skies for hundreds of miles. Blast kills
57 people and causes over $3 billion in damage.
   JULY 27 _ Iran's exiled shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, dies in
Cairo.
   AUG. 14 _ Electrician Lech Walesa leads strike at Gdansk
shipyard to start Polish worker revolt against Communist state.
Eventually 10 million Poles join independent trade union Solidarity.
   SEPT. 20 _ Iran-Iraq border skirmishes escalate into war.
Eight-year conflict eventually leaves more than 1 million dead,
including thousands of civilians.
   OCT. 11 _ Earthquake in Algeria kills 6,000 and leaves 400,000
homeless.
   NOV. 4 _ Ronald Reagan elected 40th president of United States,
defeating incumbent Jimmy Carter.
   NOV. 21 _ Fire at MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas kills 87 people.
   DEC. 8 _ Former Beatle John Lennon shot to death in New York
City.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<NOTE>YEAR OF ASSASSINS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 20 _ On day Reagan inaugurated, American hostages freed
after 444 days of captivity in Iran.
   MARCH 30 _ Reagan seriously wounded in assassination attempt.
   APRIL 12 _ Shuttle Columbia, world's first re-flyable spaceship,
launched into space.
   MAY 13 _ Pope John Paul II wounded by gunman as he greets
visitors in St. Peter's Square in Rome.
   JUNE 7 _ Israeli air strike destroys Iraqi nuclear reactor
outside Baghdad. Israel said Iraq planned to manufacture plutonium
for nuclear bombs.
   JUNE 12 _ Major league baseball players begin 50-day strike.
   JULY 29 _ Prince Charles, heir to British throne, marries Lady
Diana Spencer.
   AUG. 3 _ Air traffic controllers go on nationwide strike, and
11,500 are fired two days later after defying Reagan's 48-hour
back-to-work ultimatum.
   SEPT. 25 _ Sandra Day O'Connor sworn in as first woman to sit on
U.S. Supreme Court.
   OCT. 6 _ President Anwar Sadat of Egypt is shot to death by
Moslem extremists.
   DEC. 13 _ Martial law declared in Poland; Solidarity banned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<NOTE>YEAR OF INVASION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   APRIL 2 _ Argentina invades British-held Falkland Islands.
Fighting costs more than 1,000 lives before Britain recaptures
islands June 14.
   JUNE 6 _ Israeli troops invade southern Lebanon, site of
Palestinian guerrilla strongholds, and drive all the way to Beirut.
   JUNE 30 _ Proposed U.S. Equal Rights Amendment banning sex
discrimination dies after reaching deadline without necessary
ratification by 38 states.
   AUG. 21-SEPT. 1 _ Palestine Liberation Organization forces pull
out of Beirut.
   SEPT. 14 _ Bomb blast kills newly elected Lebanese President
Bahshir Gemayel. Gemayel's brother Amin succeeds him.
   SEPT. 16-18 _ Some 600 Palestinians are massacred in Beirut
refugee camps by Lebanese Christian militiamen allowed in area by
Israeli authorities.
   SEPT. 21-NOV. 21 _ National Football League shuts down during
eight-week players' strike.
   SEPT. 24-30 _ French, Italian and U.S. peacekeeping forces
arrive as Israeli army withdraws from Beirut.
   SEPT. 29 _ Seven people in Chicago area die of cyanide poisoning
in Tylenol tampering case, which remains unsolved.
   NOV. 10 _ Soviet leader Leonid I. Brezhnev dies.
   NOV.-DEC. _ Worst recession since Great Depression of 1930s ends.
   DEC. 2 _ Retired dentist Dr. Barney Clark becomes first
recipient of permanent artificial heart. He lived 112 days.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<NOTE>SUPERPOWER CHILL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   MARCH 8 _ Reagan denounces Soviet Union as ``evil empire.''
   APRIL 18 _ U.S. Embassy in Beirut destroyed by truck bomb and 63
people die, including 17 Americans.
   JUNE 18 _ Sally Ride, aboard space shuttle Challenger, becomes
first American woman in space.
   AUG. 21 _ Former Philippine Sen. Benigno Aquino assassinated in
Manila as he returns from three years of U.S. exile.
   SEPT. 1 _ Korean Air Lines Flight 007 shot down in Soviet
airspace over Sakhalin island by Soviet fighters, killing all 269
people aboard.
   OCT. 5 _ Nobel Peace Prize awarded to Solidarity's Walesa.
   OCT. 22 _ ``No nukes'' demonstrations across U.S. and Europe to
protest planned deployment of new medium-range missiles in Western
Europe.
   OCT. 23 _ Truck bomb explosions at U.S. and French compounds in
Beirut kill 241 U.S. servicemen and 58 French paratroopers.
   OCT. 25 _ U.S. troops invade Caribbean island of Grenada, oust
leftist leadership.
   NOV. 23 _ Soviets walk out of arms control talks, protesting
deployment of new missiles in Western Europe.
</TEXT>
