<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MediaOutlook     12-13 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Media Outlook,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Times Mirror Says Op Profit Rise Unlikely in 1989, NY Times Co. Has
Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weak advertising market for newspapers in the
Northeast is part of the reason for Times Mirror Inc.'s declaration
that it is unlikely to have higher operating earnings this year and
for a big charge against fourth quarter earnings at The New York
Times Co.
   Times Mirror executives told securities analysts on Tuesday that
higher circulation costs at its Los Angeles Times newspaper and a
settlement of a legal dispute also figured in its projection of a
possible decline in operating earnings for 1989. If operating
earnings decline, it would be the first such drop at Times Mirror
since 1982.
   Separately, The New York Times Co. announced a $44 million
charge against fourth quarter earnings, due to its investment in
its forest products operation and estimated costs related to
expected voluntary union staff cuts at The New York Times, its
flagship newspaper.
   The staff cuts, which are expected to involve mainly production
workers, were attributed to weak advertising volume in the New York
region and further automation of printing and production facilties.
   Analysts who follow the newspaper business have said they expect
ad revenue growth for newspapers to remain sluggish next year,
particularly in the Northeast where the economy appears weaker than
in other regions.
   Times Mirror, a media and information company based in Los
Angeles, owns the Los Angles Times and several Eastern newspapers,
including Newsday, New York Newsday, The Hartford Courant and the
Baltimore Sun newspapers.
   The company's earnings from operations were up 7 percent for the
first nine months of 1989 to $1.62 a share from $1.58 a share a
year earlier.
   But Robert F. Erburu, the company's chairman and chief
executive, told analysts at PaineWebber's 17th annual media
conference that it was was unlikely the company would ``continue to
show year-to-year improvement in operating earnings'' for the full
year.
   Erburu cited the difficult operating environment facing the
company's newspapers in the Northeast, the costs of trying to sign
up new subscribers after the Nov. 2 closing of the rival Los
Angeles Herald Examiner and a $5 million settlement of a legal case
involving Times Mirror's cable TV operations.
   David Laventhol, president of Times Mirror, said while the Los
Angeles Times was turning in a ``solid year'' with increases in
both retail and classified advertising, the company's Eastern
papers were reporting ad revenues barely even with a year ago, with
classified advertising lineage down 7 percent.
   For 1988, Times Mirror earned $331.9 million, or $2.58 a share,
on revenue of $3.33 billion. Operating earnings amounted to $2.27 a
share.
   Times Mirror said it has stepped up its cost-containment program
to offset some of the volatile economic and market conditions
expected next year.
   ``We have good reason to believe that we can show improvement in
1990 barring an economic downturn,'' Erburu said.
   In addition to newspapers and cable operations, Times Mirror
owns four television stations and publishes magazines and books.
   In a news release Tuesday, The New York Times Co. said 35 cents
of its 57 cent per share charge in the fourth quarter stemmed from
a determination that it would not fully recover an equity
investment in its forest products operation. The market for
newsprint has been glutted with supply.
   The remaining 22 cents per share of the charge stemmed from
estimated expenses of voluntary union staff reductions at The New
York Times. The company has been in talks with its printers and
plans to talk with other unions for production workers about staff
reductions, spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said.
   The reductions stem from weak advertising volume in the New York
region and automation of newspaper production in the composing
room, the planned closing of a printing facility at Carlstadt,
N.J., and the opening of an automated printing and distribution
facility in Edison, N.J., in late 1990.
   The company did not estimate earnings for the fourth quarter
ending Dec. 31.
   For the first nine months of 1989, the company earned $285.6
million, or $3.63 a share, on $1.30 billion in revenue.
   The New York Times is a diversified communications company that
publishes newspapers and magazines, operates television stations
and syndicates news and feature stories worldwide. It also owns
substantial interests in paper mills and has a stake in the
Paris-based International Herald Tribune.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
