<DOCNO> AP891213-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChevyDealers     12-13 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chevy Dealers,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevy Urges Dealers to Order More Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. bulletin sent to Chevrolet
dealers apparently turned into more orders for cars to be built in
January, a company spokesman says.
   The bulletin said dealer orders through Nov. 22 were far below
scheduled production and warned of plant shutdowns if the pace
didn't pick up.
   ``The bottom line is whatever signals we sent to the dealers in
late November clearly had an effect,'' said Chevrolet spokesman
Ralph Kramer.
   As of Tuesday, the 4,800 Chevrolet dealers had ordered about
75,000 cars from the January production of nearly 91,000, Kramer
said. That was up substantially from the 24,130 cars that dealers
had requested as of Nov. 22, he said.
   ``It is critical that all dealers immediately analyze their
product needs and submit orders immediately,'' said the bulletin,
quoted in a story in Monday's Automotive News trade journal.
``Adequate order banks are necessary to maintain uninterrupted
production.''
   ``There's no kidding about it,'' Kramer said. ``We're scratching
for every order we can get and our dealers are scratching for every
sale that they can get.''
   Frank Anderson, owner of Sir Walter Chevrolet-Geo in Raleigh,
N.C., said his business never received the bulletin. He said he has
been trimming orders for 1990 vehicles because of costs of keeping
them on hand.
   GM officials have contacted his dealership nearly daily ``giving
us the opportunity to order some more vehicles,'' Anderson said. He
has resisted large-scale orders, opting instead to keep his
inventory in the 45- to 50-day range.
   ``I think in their (GM's) selling, they couldn't hesitate to
mention the fact that there may be some plant closures in January
and February, even in some of the hotter lines,'' Anderson said.
``As we see it right now, that's their problem. Our immediate
problem is selling vehicles.''
   Chevrolet and Geo sales for the first 11 months of this year
were 1,262,158 cars, down 7.3 percent from the same period last
year.
   Last week, GM announced that some of its car- and truck-making
plants in Canada and the United States would close briefly in
January because of slumping dealer orders.
   Even before the 1990 model year got off to its official start on
Oct. 1, dealers were saying they planned to cut orders from
manufacturers by up to 30 percent.
   Ron Tonkin, president of the National Automobile Dealers
Association, has urged the 20,000 members of his organization to
cut orders even more to avoid costs of holding large inventories of
cars on their lots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
