<DOCNO> AP891213-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL     12-13 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Board Meets Against Backdrop Of Buyout Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover turmoil continued to cloud the future of
United Airlines as directors of parent UAL Corp. gathered for
today's regularly scheduled board meeting at the company's
Chicago-area headquarters.
   A new employee buyout plan that UAL's management drafted was
received cooly by leaders of United's pilots and flight attendants,
and ripped by the powerful Machinists union.
   Their response apparently has left Chairman Stephen Wolf without
a firm proposal for raising UAL's stock price and staving off
disgruntled investors.
   Opposition from the Machinists helped scuttle a $6.75 billion
pilot-management bid for the nation's second-largest airline in
October and their support is considered important to the success of
a revised offer.
   The Machinists represent about 25,000 of UAL's 70,000 workers.
   The plan floated by UAL management in meetings with employee
groups would value UAL at $240 a share, or $5.43 billion, the
Chicago Tribune reported Tuesday, quoting unidentified sources.
   The plan envisions UAL employees owning about two-thirds of the
stock and public stockholders about one-third, the Tribune said.
   UAL management would invest $30 million for a 2 percent stake in
the company and be granted options for another 6 percent, the
report said.
   ``If that's the deal, it's unacceptable. We will oppose it,''
said Brian Freeman, an adviser to the Machinists, in a telephone
interview from his Roseland, N.J., office.
   Freeman said UAL representatives had not met with the Machinists
regarding a revised buyout plan. He said the Machinists objected to
the price and other terms of the deal outlined in the Tribune but
he would not elaborate.
   UAL's stock climbed $2.75 to $176.75 in early New York Stock
Exchange trading.
   The Machinists' biggest complaint about the earlier,
$300-a-share UAL buyout plan was that it would require an
unacceptable level of borrowing. The deal, which had been approved
by UAL's board, failed when lenders backed away, citing the
Machinists' opposition.
   The failed bid would have given UAL workers 75 percent of the
company with management owning 10 percent and British Airways PLC,
15 percent.
   James Conley, a spokesman for the Machinists in Washington, said
the union also objected to any transaction involving UAL's two top
officers, Wolf and Executive Vice President John Pope.
   Representatives from UAL and from the United chapters of the Air
Line Pilots Association and the Association of Flight Attendants
declined comment on the Tribune report.
   UAL officials have said the pilots were given the proposal more
than a week ago. United pilots have not publicly stated their
opinion of the plan but their leader, Frederick Dubinsky, said last
week his union would not be rushed into a transaction.
   Patricia Friend, president of the United flight attendants'
union, said they were given the proposal last week and are still
studying it.
   UAL's board is under pressure from the investor group Coniston
Partners, which owns 11.8 percent of UAL's stock, to sell or
otherwise restructure the company to boost share prices.
   Keith Gollust, a general partner in Coniston, declined comment
Tuesday on whether the New York-based partnership would support the
reported buyout plan.
   Coniston has threatened to launch a drive for shareholder
consent to dump 13 of UAL's 15 directors and create a five-member
board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
