<DOCNO> AP891213-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RamadaRestructuring     12-13 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ramada Restructuring,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramada Shareholders Approve Restructuring Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Approval of a corporate restructuring
plan by Ramada Inc. shareholders has cleared the way for the sale
of Ramada's 825 hotels and formation of a new company to operate
its Nevada and New Jersey casinos.
   The restructurng plan was approved Tuesday at a special
shareholders' meeting in Scottsdale. Under the plan, Ramada would
sell its international hotel business to New World Hotel Holdings
Ltd. of Hong Kong for $540 million.
   A new company, Aztar Corp., would be formed at the same time to
operate Ramada's three casinos.
   The transaction was approved by the Nevada and New Jersey gaming
commissions Tuesday.
   ``Assuming that everything goes as scheduled, we will close the
entire transaction next week,'' said Richard Snell, Ramada's
chairman and chief executive officer, after the meeting.
   More than 96 percent of the 30 million shares that were voted
approved the plan, under which each shareholder would receive $1 in
cash and one share of Aztar stock for each share of Ramada stock.
   Ramada's original restructuring plan, which the company scrapped
in October, included an offering of $400 million in debt
securities, including $230 million in subordinated debt, or ``junk
bonds,'' to finance the new company.
   Under that plan, shareholders would have received approximately
$7 plus one share of Aztar stock for each share of Ramada stock.
   The company announced in October that it would not go forward
with that plan because of ``unfavorable conditions'' in the
junk-bond market, which has been depressed and unstable for months.
   The new plan includes a $170 million offering of debt securities
and eliminates the junk-bond offering. Under the plan, each
shareholder would receive $1 in cash plus one share of Aztar stock
for each share of Ramada stock.
   Ramada spokesman Joe Cole said that under the new plan, Ramada
would assume $230 million less in new debt, but would pay out $240
million less to its stockholders.
   ``It will be a less leveraged, stronger company,'' Cole said.
   Fewer than 200 employees will lose their jobs once the
transaction is completed, Snell said.
   ``The main reduction is in the hotel group,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
