   Numerous violations of environmental laws by
oil and gas developers go undetected under a federal leasing
program, and even when found rarely result in penalties, according
to an internal Interior Department investigation.
   The report by the department's Inspector General's Office said
that the federal Bureau of Land Management's scrutiny of oil and
gas leases is inadequate to force lease operators to comply with
environmental requirements or assure proper royalty payments to the
government.
