<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0719EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-13 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell today against all major foreign
currencies in nervous European trading, dealers said.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Dealers said they were flabbergasted by the dollar's tumble,
which went beyond all expectations and has left most year-end
trading strategies in shambles.
   ``There is a big uncertainty, people didn't expect that,'' said
a dealer at a Munich bank. ``The question is now whether there is
any interest by the central bank to support the dollar.''
   Dealers said they had not seen any central bank intervention
early today.
   The market was waiting for today's release of November U.S.
retail sales figures, traders said.
   Even if the sales figures were better than their modest
expectations, dealers said bearish sentiment on the dollar was
likely to persist at least until the end of the year.
   ``The only thing that could really help the dollar is a major
crisis in the East, like chaos in East Germany or if (Soviet leader
Mikhail) Gorbachev is toppled,'' said a Frankfurt trader.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.77 yen to a closing 143.70 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 143.80 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.7233 West German marks, down from 1.7335;
1.5650 Swiss francs, down from 1.5765; 5.8900 French francs, down
from 5.9275; 1.9410 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,280.00
Italian lire, down from 1,285.75; and 1.1605 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1625.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6085 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6027 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $417.25 a troy ounce,
down from $417.50 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $417.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $416.80, up from $416.75 bid late
Tuesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong fell $1.08 to close at a bid $414.73.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.68 a troy ounce, down
from Tuesday's $5.70.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
