<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-13 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Hit New High, Dollar Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed above
38,000 points for the first time today, while the dollar declined
against the Japanese yen for the second consecutive day.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shot up 258.89 points, or
0.68 percent, ending the day at 38,062.42, a new high.
   It took only 16 trading days for the index to gain more than
2,000 points. It first climbed above 36,000 points on Nov. 21.
   The Nikkei index's gain today was prompted by rises in the
futures market, said Yoshio Shimoyama, a senior dealer with Nikko
Securities Co.
   He said the Nikkei also rose on index-buying, or purchases of at
least 1,000 shares in all of the Nikkei's 225 items, transactions
that cost billions of dollars.
   ``Favorable economic factors, such as the yen's recent recovery
against the dollar and gains on overseas stock markets, reassured
participants and almost erased their worries,'' Shimoyama added.
   But some market players, especially institutional investors,
remained cautious, resulting in just moderate trading. First
section volume was estimated at 800 million shares, unchanged from
the previous day.
   Among gainers were high-tech, trading house and construction
issues.
   The dollar closed at 143.70 yen, down 0.77 yen from Tuesday's
144.47-yen close. It opened at 143.80 yen and ranged between 143.35
and 143.90 yen.
   The dollar, which had gained 1.75 yen in a seven-day rise, now
has lost 0.95 yen in the last two days.
   ``It was only the West German mark that moved actively,'' said
Yutaka Nakamura, a Daiwa Bank trader.
   ``Although some market players in Sydney and Tokyo sold the mark
for profit-taking, the mark weakened only temporarily and continued
to soar, especially against the dollar,'' he said.
   The dollar's weakness against the mark resulted in the yen
rising against the dollar, although dollar-yen trading was thin,
Nakamura said.
   Spot trading amounted to $8.42 billion, up from Tuesday's $3.87
billion.
</TEXT>
