<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Chrysler     12-13 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chrysler,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Not Building Subcompacts Until Mid-1990s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will rely on a stripped-down
version of a compact car to fill a void left when the company stops
making subcompacts, a Chrysler executive said.
   The nation's No. 3 automaker will stop building its Dodge Omni
and Plymouth Horizon subcompacts when it shuts down its Jefferson
Avenue assembly plant in Detroit early in February.
   ``You'll see that low-end replaced by a value-oriented P-car,''
Chrysler marketing Vice President John Damoose said Tuesday.
   The P-car is the Dodge Shadow and Plymouth Sundance built at the
company's Sterling Heights assembly plant.
   Damoose said the subcompact replacement probably wouldn't go
into production until after cars derived from the LH and LX
platforms are introduced, scheduled for the fall of 1992.
   According to Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly industry
newsletter, subcompact cars made up 13.1 percent of the total U.S.
car market. The Omni and Horizon, the only subcompacts built by
Chrysler, comprised 8 percent of the automaker's car sales of about
959,128 through Nov. 30.
   Damoose spoke to reporters as he outlined Chrysler's plans for
the North American International Auto Show in Detroit next month.
At that event, Chrysler will show off its new Dodge Stealth sports
car, which goes on sale in October; the new Dodge Monaco, being
built in Canada; a LeBaron sedan, and a new Jeep.
   Damoose said Chrysler planned to build 25,000 to 30,000 Stealth
cars to compete in the same market as the Mazda RX-7 and the Nissan
300ZX. No price for the car has been set.
   Also, the company will have on hand six concept vehicles, which
are used to show off design and engineering developments but aren't
necessarily headed for assembly lines.
   On other matters, Damoose said:
   _Chrysler is studying the effect of Plymouth advertising
featuring entertainer Tina Turner, which was introduced earlier
this year. He said the research should be completed next month.
   He said he didn't know if the advertising had helped sell
Plymouth cars.
   ``Nobody has ever talked about Plymouth advertising in their
lives. Now they are,'' he said. So far this model year, Plymouth
dealers have sold 75,426 cars and minivans, down 4.7 percent from
the same time last year.
   _Chrysler production planners are forecasting that the company
will hold its 13.8 percent share of the U.S. car and light truck
market in 1990. That will come as sales for the entire industry
tumble to about 14.2 million vehicles.
   Chrysler's 1990 sales estimate is the lowest of the Big Three.
General Motors Corp. officials predict that about 15 million
vehicles will be sold next year and Ford Motor Co. executives put
the volume at about 14.7 million, slightly lower than sales this
year.
   ``Our strategy is to hold share and do it profitably,'' Damoose
said. ``Whether it's going to take any more incentives is anybody's
guess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
