<FIRST>u f PM-ManufacturersPresident     12-13 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manufacturers President,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hanover Picks New President From Chemical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical Banking Corp. President Thomas S.
Johnson has been named the new president and apparent heir to the
chairmanship of rival Manufacturers Hanover Corp.
   Johnson's appointment, which becomes final at a board of
directors meeting Tuesday, comes as Manufacturers struggles through
a major restructuring resulting from problems with its portfolio of
loans to Third World countries.
   Analysts have said that Manufacturers needed new blood in its
management team, as well as a successor for John F. McGillicuddy,
59, who has been chairman and president of the bank for nearly two
decades and says he plans to retire in a few years.
   In a statement Tuesday, McGillicuddy said, ``We look to Tom
(Johnson) as my successor. He is an outstanding individual, a
proven leader and a talented executive with a wide range of
experience in financial services.''
   At Chemical Bank, Johnson, 49, was the second-highest ranking
officer since 1983, heading all corporate and institutional
business, including commercial banking and corporate finance. He
faced a longer wait there before taking the reins from Chairman
Walter V. Shipley, who is in his early 50s.
   Prior to joining Chemical in 1969, Johnson served as a special
assistant to the comptroller in the Defense Department.
   McGillicuddy said Johnson's initial main role at Manufacturers
would be to complete the reorganization of its global wholesale
bank.
   Manufacturers posted a $789 million loss in the third quarter
after adding $950 million to its reserve against possible losses on
loans to developing countries.
   As part of its restructuring, Manufacturers also has sold a
controlling stake of its CIT Group financial services unit to
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. of Japan, issued new shares and made
cutbacks in staff.
</TEXT>
