<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0009 12-13 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: Leads grafs 1-6 to RECAST to reflect earlier reports of meeting;
picks up 10th graf pvs bg'ng, Eastern reportedly ...; SUBS last graf to
edit to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent meeting between Eastern Airlines and
its striking Machinists union has prompted a federal bankruptcy
judge to postpone until Jan. 26 consideration of contempt charges
against union leaders.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland on Tuesday granted the
union's request that the hearing be deferred. The potential
contempt charges stem from a disturbance Nov. 26 between pickets
and working employees at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.
   Sheldon Engelhard, an attorney representing the Machinists, said
the hearing should be put off because of recent negotiations
between union leaders and management.
   Charles E. Bryan, president of Machinists District 100, told The
Associated Press last week that he met in Washington on Nov. 30
with Eastern vice presidents Tom Matthews and Al Gibson. The
three-hour meeting was led by federal mediator Harry Bickford.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said it was the first such
meeting since an informal session Oct. 13, and he and Bryan said
both sides agreed to more meetings. Bryan said all parties agreed
not to describe or give details of the sessions.
   In a separate development Tuesday, Eastern and a committee
representing major creditors agreed to postpone until sometime next
week a meeting that had been planned for Wednesday, Matell said.
   Eastern reportedly is close to selling its Latin American routes
to AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, for $300 million to $400
million. There has been speculation that a deal would be announced
at the meeting with creditors.
   Miami-based Eastern has been operating as a smaller airline with
replacement workers since March 4, when the Machinists struck and
pilots and flight attendants walked out in sympathy. Eastern filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on March 9; the carrier is
expected to submit a revised plan of reorganization at next week's
session with creditors.
   The Machinists continue to walk picket lines, but the pilots and
flight attendants called off their sympathy strikes shortly before
Thanksgiving.
   Seven striking Machinists were arrested Nov. 26 on charges of
unlawful assembly when they refused to leave the Atlanta airport
after a group of pickets pelted cars with rocks and injured a
working Eastern employee.
   At that time, Lifland issued a show-cause order citing ``willful
defiance'' of a July 17 temporary restraining order prohibiting the
Atlanta pickets from threatening or injuring Eastern workers.
   The Machinists cited in the order could face fines and court
costs if found in contempt. They include Bryan and Robert Taylor
and Charles Pecca, Machinist officials based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
