<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-13 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Markets Open Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with
wheat and soybeans mostly lower and corn mostly higher.
   The slight drop in soybean values largely reflected weakening in
the soybean meal and oil markets and expectations for continued
slow export demand, analysts said.
   Contracts for soybean deliveries next fall gained slightly,
though, on reports of severe dryness in southern Brazil, the
world's second-largest soybean producer.
   Wheat was down slightly amid perceptions of slackening demand
and ideas the market was due for a downward correction after its
recent gains. The Agriculture Deparment's rejection of several bids
for export wheat also weighed on futures.
   Corn futures were mostly higher in line with the cash market,
following Tuesday's USDA announcement that the Soviet Union had
bought about 100,000 metric tons of U.S corn.
   Sharply lower precious metal prices contributed to the markets'
overall bearish cast, said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent to 1{ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.12 a bushel; corn
was { cent lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.34\ a
bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent higher with March at $1.56{ a
bushel; soybeans were \ cent lower to 2{ cents higher with January
at $5.76} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle futures were .05 cent to .17 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in December at 76.70 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to .15 cent higher with January at 83.37
cents a pound; live hogs were .45 cent lower to .03 cent higher
with December at 50.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .43
cent to 1.15 cents higher with February at 51 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled narrowly mixed on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
