<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     12-13 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0308</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead today, getting
more mileage out of the rally it began on Tuesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 23.89 points
Tuesday, rose 16.43 to 2,768.56 by noontime today on Wall Street.
   That brought the average to within striking distance of the
record closing high of 2,791.41 it reached on Oct. 9, before it
took a 190-point drop four days later.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 766 up, 536 down and
585 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders drew some encouragement from the Commerce
Department report that retail sales rose 0.8 percent in November,
exceeding advance estimates.
   But interest rates rose a bit following the news, and investors
still seemed to be cautious about the outlook for the economy in
1990 and the prospect that corporate profits might remain weak.
   Energy stocks were actively traded, running into some resistance
after their recent rally inspired by cold weather in many parts of
the United States and forecasts of higher oil prices in the months
ahead.
   Among the volume leaders, Texaco rose ] to 57{; Unocal gained ]
to 31; Exxon added [ to 51]; Phillips Petroleum was unchanged at
25~, and Amoco slipped \ to 55].
   In the blue-chip industrial sector, Philip Morris rose ] to 43[;
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph | to 45}, and Coca-Cola 1] to 80~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .96 to 195.40. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 1.22 at 378.63.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 92.23 million shares at
noontime, up from 77.62 million at the same point Tuesday.
</TEXT>
