<FIRST>r f PM-PSNH-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru f0065 12-13 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSNH-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0065,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislative Leaders Endorse Northeast Buyout of PSNH</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with comments from legislative news conference; CORRECTS
name to Public Service Company sted Co. in lead; minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northeast Utilities made major gains today
in its bid to buy Public Service Company of New Hampshire, the
first big investor-owned utility to go bankrupt since the
Depression.
   State Senate President William Bartlett, whose support was seen
as key to Northeast's success in a special legislative session
scheduled for Thursday, now will support the $2.3 billion buyout.
   And Public Service _ which had held out hope of winning the
right to reorganize itself _ threw in the towel.
   House Speaker Douglas Scamman announced at a news conference
that Republican leaders in both houses had united behind the
Northeast plan after winning agreements intended to protect
consumers and other New Hampshire utilities.
   ``We're very confident they have protection and future (power)
supply'' based on the agreements,'' Scamman said. The changes will
be amendments to the Northeast takeover bill scheduled for a vote
Thursday.
   Despite the developments, the vote still is too close to call,
the No. 2 Republican in the Senate said.
   ``I won't make any prediction,'' Majority Leader Edward Dupont
said. He said he hadn't decided how he would vote.
   Democrats, heavily outnumbered in the Legislature, continued to
oppose the Northeast plan.
   ``We have come to no agreement,'' House Democratic Leader Mary
Chambers said this morning.
   Connecticut-based Northeast proposes seven annual rate increases
of 5.5 percent, the first taking effect Jan. 1. Northeast says the
plan is ``Seabrook neutral,'' meaning it would not change
regardless of whether Public Service's Seabrook nuclear power plant
operates.
   The $6.3 billion plant, which plunged Public Service into
bankruptcy reorganization in January 1988, is idle for lack of a
federal operating license. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission could
issue a license as early as January, but appeals in federal courts
are certain.
   Public Service, New Hampshire's largest electric utility, had
been viewed recently as a distant second in the takeover
competition. At a morning news conference, John Duffett, president
and board chairman, attributed the utility's decision to drop out
of the competition mainly to political opposition and Public
Service's inability to win support from key creditor groups.
   Northeast, far and away the leading contender before today, had
been seen as having little chance of winning legislative backing
without support from Bartlett. As late as Tuesday night, Bartlett
continued negotiating for further concessions from Northeast.
   Legislative Democrats, and some Republicans, say the Northeast
plan would be a windfall for investors without protecting consumers.
   Republican Gov. Judd Gregg and other supporters of the agreement
say the plan is far from ideal, but is the best that could be
achieved under difficult circumstances _ and has the important
benefit of avoiding years of legal wrangling and uncertaintly about
rates.
   Gregg, whose office had no comment this morning, charged Tuesday
that the Democrats' real agenda in opposing Northeast is stopping
Seabrook.
   Democrats are espousing ``the old agenda of let's kill Seabrook
at any cost, even if the cost is that New Hampshire consumers end
up paying a lot more for energy and may not have the available
supply they need in the future,'' Gregg said.
   Chambers denied it.
   ``The Seabrook issue is really a minor issue in all of this,''
she said Tuesday. ``This plan gives absolutely no protection to
consumers and permits the company to make incredible profits.''
   Republicans outnumber Democrats 3-1 in the House and 2-1 in the
Senate, but Chambers said Tuesday she doubted that Republicans had
sufficient votes to pass the Northeast plan. Gregg disagreed,
predicting the plan would pass.
   Even if the Legislature passes the Northeast plan, it would need
approval by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge James Yacos and various
government agencies.
   Any changes to the plan presumably would require the approval of
Public Service creditors, whose representatives had accepted the
Northeast plan as it stood before today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
