<FIRST>r f BC-BlueArrow-Manpower     12-13 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Blue Arrow-Manpower,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blue Arrow Plans To Change Name To Manpower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue Arrow PLC, the world's largest employment
services company, said Wednesday it is taking steps to change its
name to Manpower PLC, adopting the identity of the giant American
agency it acquired in 1987.
   The company's board of directors on Tuesday voted unanimously to
recommend the change to shareholders, it said.
   Blue Arrow Chairman Mitchell Fromstein, former head of Manpower,
obtained control of Blue Arrow management in a boardroom coup
earlier this year.
   ``Since Manpower Inc. represents over 75 percent of the
company's revenues and profits, and is the multinational brand
among the company's holdings, it is appropriate to make this
change,'' Fromstein said. ``It should surprise no one.''
   The smaller Blue Arrow bought Manpower, based in Milwaukee,
Wis., in an acrimonious $1.34 billion takeover battle two years ago.
   In January, Fromstein emerged as Blue Arrow's chief executive
after a fight among the company's directors and major U.S.
franchisees over the management practices of Antony Berry, then
chairman and chief executive.
   Fromstein was named to replace Berry as chairman in April.
   Blue Arrow has suffered a series of financial embarrassments
since the Manpower takeover, including the disclosure of a
questionable loan to a Berry associate and the cover-up by its
financial advisers of the failure of an 837 million-pound stock
sale used to fund the takeover.
</TEXT>
