<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Flight103-Security Adv17   12-13 1079</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Security, Adv 17,1119</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Legacy Makes Terrorism Fact of Life for Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airlines worldwide have tightened security since
the Pan Am jumbo jet terrorist explosion over Lockerbie, Scotland,
spending large amounts of money on defenses that range from
bomb-sniffing dogs to baggage X-ray gear.
   But two more big passenger planes have crashed in the year since
then in presumed terrorist sabotage, and experts warn that another
Lockerbie could happen tomorrow.
   The Flight 103 bombing that killed 259 people in midair Dec. 21,
1988, has made terrorism a sobering and expensive fact of life for
the airlines, especially the big U.S. carriers that fly overseas.
   Sophisticated bombs timed to explode during flight have replaced
hijacking as terrorists' favored mode of operation.
   The burly guards, body searches, bomb detectors and dogs trained
to smell hidden explosives have become increasingly familiar
staples of air travel, helping to drive ticket prices higher.
   The Federal Aviation Administration sent a key directive to U.S.
airlines a month after the Lockerbie crash, requiring specific
measures for inspecting baggage and screening passengers. For
example, the FAA has ordered installation of sophisticated
explosive-detection gear in 40 airports by next October.
   ``The aviation industry has taken steps to ensure better
controls,'' said Don W. Walker, president of Business Risks
International, a consulting firm. But, he said, ``terrorism is
escalating worldwide; the terrorists are generally one step ahead
of what airlines are able to do.''
   In July 1988, the airlines intensified anti-terrorist defenses
in response to the Navy's downing of an Iran Air jetliner. But
terrorists sneaked a sophisticated explosive through Pan Am's
security system six months later.
   After the Pan Am bombing, the airlines again strengthened
security. Then, last September, a UTA French Airline DC-10 exploded
over Niger, Africa, in a suspected bombing that killed 174 people
including seven Americans.
   In November an Avianca Airlines Boeing 727 crashed near Bogota,
Colombia, in what authorities called a suspected bombing by drug
traffickers retaliating for a government crackdown.
   Airlines once declined to discuss security. But in the aftermath
of the Lockerbie disaster, the airline industry has started making
security a subtle part of its marketing campaign to attract and
reassure passengers.
   For example, extensive publicity has been given to the so-called
thermal neutron analysis explosive detectors that the FAA has
required. Pan Am and Trans World Airlines have been the first to
install the new devices.
   The company that makes them, Science Applications International
Corp., said they will be ``an important working model for other
airlines to learn from as the FAA security program goes forward.''
   Still, most carriers still won't talk specifically about how
much money they spend, although it is in the millions of dollars.
They also criticize the government for not absorbing more of the
cost.
   ``The airline industry is the surrogate target for the
government,'' said Homer Boynton, director of security for American
Airlines, the largest U.S. carrier. ``The government ought to give
us more help and more assistance.''
   But Fred Farrar, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, called security ``a cost of doing business.
Traditionally, the airlines have paid the cost of equipment needed
for security reasons.''
   Like jet fuel and passenger food, airline security is an expense
that comes out of revenues or as a special surcharge added to
ticket prices that passes the bill to travelers. Pan Am, for
example, adds $5 to the cost of a one-way trans-Atlantic ticket.
   Boynton said American is the only major U.S. airline that uses
its own employees for all security work. Most big carriers have
their own security divisions but also contract with outside
companies for passenger screening in airports and other protective
services.
   American, which operates a growing number of flights to Europe,
spends $11 million to $12 million a year on security, Boynton said.
   Its program is partly modeled on that of Israel's El Al
Airlines, which has a reputation for the toughest security measures.
   Spokesmen for American, Pan Am, Trans World Airlines, Eastern
Airlines, British Airways and Japan Air Lines, queried by the
Associated Press, all said their carriers strengthened what they
called already-tight security after Lockerbie. Representatives of
UTA and Avianca said those airlines stepped up security after
disaster struck them.
   While financially strong airlines such as American can afford
top-quality security as well as newer, safer jets, there is concern
that weaker carriers could be tempted to cut corners.
   Pan Am, for example, lost $158.3 million for the first nine
months of this year, compared with a loss of $21 million in the
same period in 1988. In every financial quarter since Lockerbie,
Pan Am has largely blamed its poor financial condition on falling
trans-Atlantic passenger traffic resulting from the crash. In a
recent ABC News special broadcast, some former security employees
of Pan Am alleged serious deficiencies in the airline's screening
system. According to ABC, the Pan Am security supervisor in
Frankfurt, West Germany, where Flight 103 originated had a criminal
record, unknown to the airline.
   The former employees charged that Pan Am's security was
compromised by cost-cutting and concern about on-time performance.
   Because it has been sued by a number of relatives of Lockerbie
crash victims, Pan Am cannot respond specifically to the
allegations about its Alert Security Co., said Pan Am spokesman
Jeff Kriendler. He called the charges ``false and misleading'' and
``a vindictive effort to discredit a former employer.''
   ``We strongly reject any suggestion that Pan Am or Alert would
have deliberately compromised the safety of passengers and crew
members to effect on-time departure or to cut costs,'' Kriendler
said.
   Last August, President Bush created the Presidential Commission
on Aviation Security and Terrorism, scheduled to make
recommendations to him next spring. The seven-member panel, headed
by former labor secretary Ann McLaughlin, plans to evaluate
aviation security, the handling of terrorist threats against air
travel and whether the public should be told of them, and the
government's treatment of terrorists' victims.
   At its first hearing, on Nov. 17, former FAA security director
Billie H. Vincent told the panel that air security is ``seriously
deficient'' in high-threat areas such as Europe and the Middle East.
   Other experts agree.
   ``We are way behind in taking the necessary measures that will
help to prevent this kind of tragedy happening again,'' terrorism
expert Paul Wilkinson recently told a news conference in London.
``Another Lockerbie could happen tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Dec. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
