<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-13 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Finish Mostly Higher on Weather Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in light-volume
buying linked largely to weather concerns.
   Bitter cold temperatures in the nation's midsection are stirring
fears of damage to the winter wheat crop in the Great Plains and
spurring demand for soybean meal among cattle producrs.
   ``When the weather gets cold, they have to increase the energy
component in the feed mix, so they feed the cattle more meal,''
said Joel Karlin, an analyst with Research Department Inc. in
Chicago.
   The soybean market was further supported by fears that the
continuing dry weather in southern Brazil, the world's
second-largest soybean producer, would stretch into a drought.
   The corn market rallied slightly on commercial buying, possibly
indicating that new export sales are in the works, Karlin said.
   At the close, wheat futures were { cent to 2 cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.14 a bushel; corn
futures were unchanged to 2\ cents higher with December at $2.33 a
bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 6 cents higher with
January at $5.80\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
