<DOCNO> AP891213-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChryslerDowngrade     12-13 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler Downgrade,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moody's Drops Chrysler Debt Rating 1 Notch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moody's Investors Service Inc. on Wednesday
dropped its debt ratings for Chrysler Corp. and its financial
subsidiary by one notch amid concern over vehicle sales,
competition and capital expenditures.
   Fitch Investors Service Inc. said it was reviewing Chrysler's
securities and Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said no change was likely.
   Movement in security ratings indicate increasing or decreasing
faith in the creditworthiness of a company.
   Moody's said in a news release that it was lowering a variety of
Chrysler securities because of ``concerns that Chrysler's operating
performance will remain under pressure over the intermediate
term,'' or three to four years.
   Moody's rating for Chrysler's senior debt was lowered to
``Baa2'' from ``Baa1.'' Moody's analyst Carol Verschell said that
was toward the lower end of the company's investment-grade ratings.
   Chrysler spokesman Tom Houston read a statement saying: ``We're
disappointed in the action that Moody's has taken. But we believe
that it will not have any material effect on Chrysler ... borrowing
costs.''
   Moody's also said Chrysler's share of the light truck market,
which includes the company's popular minivans and Jeep vehicles,
will come under increasing competitive pressure.
   Chrysler's announcement earlier this month to sell Chrysler
Technologies Corp., which includes Gulfstream Aerospace Inc., will
provide some cash, Verschell said, but the timing of the sale and
the amount are uncertain.
   At Fitch, auto analyst Mary Anne Sudol said her firm's ratings
for a variety of Chrysler securities were either the same or
slightly higher than Moody's new ratings. All Chrysler ratings were
under review, she said.
   ``There will be some action, but I don't know when it will
come,'' Sudol said.
   Nancy Stroker of Standard &amp; Poor's said her company affirmed the
``BBB'' rating of Chrysler securities, roughly the same level as
Moody's. ``We don't expect to have any kind of rating change,'' she
said.
   Verschell said Moody's was not reviewing the ratings of General
Motors Corp. or Ford Motor Co. securities.
   Moody's announcement of lower Chrysler's ratings came before the
company reported that sales of its North American-made cars and
trucks fell 25.1 percent in early December, compared with the same
time last year.
   Through Dec. 10, Chrysler's vehicle sales were running 6.7
percent behind last year's pace. The automaker's financial
subsidiary is Chrysler Financial Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
