<FIRST>r f AM-PostStrike 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Post Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Agreement Reached to Settle Cereal Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative contract settlement was
reached Wednesday between negotiators for Post Cereal and about
1,000 workers who struck 39 days earlier.
   Richard Powers, president of Local 374 of the United Cereal,
Bakery and Food Workers, said union officials were recommending
that members approve the proposal at a ratification vote scheduled
for Thursday afternoon.
   ``I'm sure the membership will support us,'' he said. ``We're
just pleased that this thing is coming to an end.''
   Workers may be back at work as early as this weekend, with most
returning on Monday, union officials said.
   Contract talks had snagged on the company's proposal to increase
worker contributions to the medical insurance plan, something
Powers said was addressed in the new contract. On Sunday, union
members rejected the company's last proposal by more than a 2-1
margin.
   Negotiators met for about two hours Tuesday and again on
Wednesday.
   ``We sincerely hope that employees will ratify this new offer so
production can resume,'' said Kathy Beiser, a spokeswoman for Post,
a division of Kraft General Foods. ``We believe that ratification
and a return to work are in the best interest of all concerned
parties.''
   The strike has shut down operations at the main plant of Post,
Battle Creek's No. 2 employer behind Kellogg Co.
   Analysts say the shutdown has added to the problems facing Post
as it suffers falling sales and a declining market share in the
ready-to-eat cereal industry.
</TEXT>
