<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Tambrands     12-13 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tambrands,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tambrands Selling Two Units in Restructuring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tambrands Inc. on Wednesday said it will sell its diagnostics
and cosmetics businesses and cut its work force as part of a
restructuring program that will allow the company to focus on its
feminine hygiene products.
   Costs associated with the restructuring will cause Tambrands to
take an after-tax charge of about $65 million against its
fourth-quarter earnings.
   ``We have a profitable core business whose positive results have
been burdened by the cost of unrelated and non-essential
activities,'' said Martin F.C. Emmett, chairman and chief executive.
   He said the restructuring program ``will enable us to focus on
our Tampax tampon business worldwide ....''
   The company, which has its headquarters in Lake Success, N.Y.,
estimates it will cut 100 to 200 employees from its current total
of 700 salaried workers, Paul E. Konney, Tambrands senior vice
president, said.
   The charge against earnings will cover the costs of trimming the
payroll, consolidating some facilities, and revaluing Tambrands'
investments in Latin America and China, its diagnostics and
cosmetics businesses and certain other assets.
   Konney said he couldn't comment on how the fourth-quarter charge
will affect earnings. The company is due to report its
fourth-quarter and full-year results in mid-February.
   He also said the company hasn't estimated the proceeds from the
planned sales of its First Response home diagnostics and Physicians
Formula hypoallergenic cosmetics businesses.
   Tambrands' stock has periodically been bid higher on takeover
speculation in recent months. Konney declined to comment on whether
the restructuring program came in response to a takeover threat.
   Through three quarters of this year, Tambrands earned $61
million, or $2.72 a share, down from $71 million, or $3.17 a share,
a year earlier. Nine-month revenue totaled $449 million this year,
up from $428 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
