<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-13 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices tumbled in worldwide trading
Wednesday, while the dollar finished mixed against other major
currencies in choppy, hectic dealings after rebounding overseas.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $408.10 a troy ounce, down $9.80 from late
Tuesday. Republic National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for
gold at $408 an ounce, down $9. The plunge in gold also helped
depress other precious metals, such as silver.
   Dealers attributed gold's decline largely to profit-taking from
its recent steady rise and to technical market factors. They noted
particularly strong selling by Middle East investors.
   In currency trading, Zlatko Glamuzina, chief currency dealer at
the New York office of Banco di Sicilia, likened Wednesday's
trading to ``a tug of war between the bulls and the bears.''
   ``The bulls would like to see the dollar go up and they say it
has reached its bottom, but the bears are trying to pulling it
lower and seem to be winning the battle overall,'' Glamuzina said.
   The dollar got a boost from rumors that Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev had resigned, although they were swiftly denied by the
Soviet Embassy in Washington, currency dealers said. Also
supporting the dollar were reports of intervention by some central
banks to push down the value of the surging West Germany mark, they
said.
   Putting a damper on the dollar, however, was speculation that
the Federal Reserve was easing interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.77 Japanese yen to close at 143.70 yen.
It traded at 144.13 yen in London, and at 144.05 yen in New York,
up from 144.00 yen late Tuesday.
   The dollar was stronger against the British pound. Sterling
bought $1.5955 in London, down from $1.6027 Tuesday; and $1.6000 in
New York, down from $1.6085 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.7280 West German marks, down from
1.7322; 1.5645 Swiss francs, down from 1.5732; 5.9070 French
francs, down from 5.9185; 1,289.00 Italian lire, up from 1,284.75;
and 1.1597 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1625.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday, included:
1.7390 West German marks, up from 1.7335; 1.5965 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5765; 5.9475 French francs, up from 5.9275; 1.9430 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,296.25 Italian lire, up from
1,285.75; and 1.1585 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1625.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $411.25 an ounce from
$417.50 Tuesday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold slipped to $411.00 an
ounce from $416.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.08 to close at a bid $414.73
an ounce.
   Silver prices also fell sharply. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery settled at $5.544, down from $5.672
late Tuesday. Silver fell in London to $5.59 an ounce from $5.70.
</TEXT>
