<FIRST>s f BC-BorderRebound Adv17   12-13 0981</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Border Rebound, Adv 17,1010</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>El Comeback: Retailers on Border Enjoying Return of Mexican Shoppers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McALLEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's reviving economy is on display at
La Plaza Mall, where the parking lot is full of license plates from
across the border.
   In this city 10 miles north of the Rio Grande, and all along the
U.S.-Mexico frontier, one fact of international trade stands out:
Mexican shoppers have returned to the United States to visit and
shop, recovering from the brutal 1980s that brought ``la crisis.''
   The Banco Nacional de Mexico says Mexicans are spending as much
and possibly more money on the U.S. side of the border than they
did 10 years ago.
   As a result, McAllen's La Plaza Mall has the highest sales per
square foot of any of the 70 U.S. shopping centers owned by the
Indianapolis, Ind.-based Melvin Simon and Associates, said Tom
Jenkins, southern regional manager with the firm. La Plaza's
average merchandise sales of $404 per square foot is more than
double the firm's national average of $189 per square foot.
   The company's No. 2 mall is El Paso's Cielo Vista, with sales of
$338 per square foot, Jenkins said.
   He attributes much of the border malls' success to the crowds of
Mexican shoppers returning over the past two years.
   ``The Mexican nationals, what they're looking for is quality,''
Jenkins said. ``They are not looking for sales.''
   ``We have a lot of Monterrey traffic that drives, a lot of
traffic from Mexico City that fly and the regular bus traffic that
come across,'' said Tommy Joyner, executive director of the McAllen
Chamber of Commerce.
   That is a vast improvement over just a few years ago. After huge
oil revenues and massive public spending and borrowing led to a
brief boom from 1979-81, a sudden drop in oil prices in 1981
fractured the Mexican economy.
   Mexicans watched the peso diminish from a value of 26 to the
dollar at the beginning of 1982, to 149 to the dollar by the end of
that year.
   Border retailers on the U.S. side soon found their stores empty.
The Mexicans' money suddenly bought only one-sixth of what it used
to buy, so they no longer could shop in the United States. The
disappearance of the Mexican shopper quickly drove many stores out
of business all along the border.
   Mexican expenditures in Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and
California by 1983 dropped to half of what they were in 1979.
   Business in 1983 was off 80 percent in downtown McAllen, said
Larry Fallek, owner of Mike's Man Shop and the Palais de Parfum in
downtown McAllen and another men's clothing store at La Plaza Mall.
   He estimated that 85 percent of his downtown sales and 60
percent of mall sales are to Mexicans.
   Although the peso by 1987 dropped to 2,500 to the dollar as
foreign debt plagued the nation, Mexico's economy since has begun
to calm down. The exchange rate fell only to about 2,650 by
December 1989.
   Mexicans are spending abroad again because the peso has
stabilized, and because of new confidence in President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's economic liberalization, said Isabel Bagnasco,
an economist with the Mexico City-based Banco Nacional de Mexico.
   ``We are now having an economy with stable prices,'' she said.
   If Mexican spending on the U.S. side of the border for the
second half of 1989 continues at the rate of the first half, U.S.
retailers will surpass the $2.24 billion sales to Mexicans that
Banco Nacional estimated for the boom year of 1979. During 1988,
Mexican purchases of $2.09 billion in Texas, New Mexico, Arizona
and California were $500 million higher than in 1987, the bank said.
   Steady growth in Mexico's 1,500 border assembly plants, or
``maquiladoras,'' also has boosted the buying power of a new
industrial work force of about 350,000.
   ``When Mexico comes across, it stirs up the whole economy,''
said retailer Fallek in McAllen. ``They feel better about
themselves, about their country and their government. Right now,
they don't seem so worried.''
   Retail sales growth of 22.6 percent in 1988 in the McAllen area
was the biggest increase of all the state's metropolitan areas,
according to the State Comptroller's office. In the adjacent
Brownsville-Harlingen area at the southern tip of the state, retail
sales grew by 15.8 percent in 1988. In El Paso, the retail growth
rate was 9.5 percent.
   For comparison, sales grew state wide by only 6.4 percent in
1988.
   Retailers say this year will turn out even better. Fallek said
the gradual return of the Mexican shoppers since last year will
make 1989 his best year since 1981.
   Brownsville retailer Michael Begum said he also has seen a
steady improvement in sales since the peso crash cut his sales in
half. His downtown New Yorker store caters to customers like the
woman from Matamoros, Mexico, who on a recent Friday stopped in
looking for something to wear to a party and bought a $2,500 fur
coat.
   At the other end of the border, San Ysidro, Calif., retailers
see the same recovery, said Doug Perry, president of the Chamber of
Commerce.
   ``There doesn't seem to be a lot of (retail) space available for
anything, particularly close to the border,'' Perry said.
   Another positive economic sign in Mexico is the cooling of its
runaway inflation that hit 159 percent in 1987. Inflation dropped
to 52 percent in 1988, and is projected to be 20 percent for 1989
and 15 percent in 1990.
   Inflation, however, still makes many products cheaper in the
United States than in Mexico. Inflation-fighting consumers can be
found among the Mexicans driving or flying home with new dresses
and toys, as well as those carrying bags of toilet paper and
groceries across the international bridges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Sunday, Dec. 17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
