<FIRST>u f AM-GreatNorthern     12-13 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Northern,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Northern Wages Battle Against Georgia-Pacific Solely in Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Great Northern Nekoosa
Corp. said Wednesday his paper company is not discussing any
``white knight'' friendly mergers or defensive restructuring to
thwart the takeover attempt by Georgia-Pacific Corp.
   Great Northern instead is pinning its hopes on courtroom
decisions to fend off the unsolicited $63 a share tender offer,
valued at a total of $3.8 billion.
   ``While we're in the courts we're not considering anything
else,'' William R. Laidig, chairman and chief executive of Great
Northern.
   ``Naturally we're talking to our financial advisers about what
the future would look like when we finish winning this court fight
with Georgia-Pacific, but there's actually no specific work going
on right now and we certainly are not looking for a white knight,''
Laidig said.
   Laidig said other paper company executives have brought up the
takeover attempt but he has made sure not to get into any talks
about alternate mergers. When Georgia-Pacific made its initial
offer of $58 per share on Oct. 31, there was speculation by some
analysts that other paper companies might enter the bidding, but
that has not happened.
   Great Northern stock finished down 50 cents at $61.75 a share on
Wednesday. Georgia Pacific was unchanged at $50.87{ a share.
   ``I've talked to some other CEOs who have said they're sorry to
see this situation the way it is, but nobody's gone any farther
than that, because I wouldn't have let them even if they wanted
to,'' Laidig said.
   Laidig would not name any of the executives he had talked to,
but said Great Northern also has heard from foreign companies that
are watching the situation.
   ``We sell a lot overseas and there have been people who
questioned whether there was a long-term interest in staying
independent or something like that,'' Laidig said.
   ``Now whether that characterized the fact that they might be
interested in some other action or not, I don't know. We certainly
have had a lot of our customers overseas who have indicated they
are interested in whether we do or do not stay independent. But
none of them have come forward and said, `We'd like to buy you, or
buy this or buy that or anything like that.'''
   The legal battles are being fought in federal court in Maine,
where Georgia-Pacific filed a lawsuit challenging Great Northern's
``poison pill'' takeover defense and a state anti-takeover law, and
in Connecticut, where Great Northern has filed an antitrust suit
against Georgia-Pacific.
   The Federal Trade Commission in Washington also is examining the
proposed merger for potential antitrust problems and is expected to
state any objections by Dec. 21.
   ``We think that our offer for Great Northern will succeed, and
we think our acquisition offer fully complies with antritrust
laws,'' spokeswoman Gail Smith said Wednesday from
Georgia-Pacific's headquarters in Atlanta.
   Laidig was in Portland on Wednesday for a news conference at
which he defended company lawyers for persuading U.S. District
Judge Gene Carter to unseal a Georgia-Pacific consultant's study
that showed different cash-flow scenarios based on a theoretical
merger followed by sales of Great Northern mills in Maine, Georgia
and Wisconsin.
   Georgia-Pacific said the study, unsealed this week, had been
rejected long ago and accused Great Northern of a ``cheap shot.''
   Laidig said his company felt that people in Maine were entitled
to the information and Georgia-Pacific should have disclosed it
previously.
   But in response to a question, Laidig said he would not make
promises about Great Northern's willingness to protect jobs and
sensitive woodlands. The company, based in Norwalk, Conn., and
incorporated in Maine, has been in business for almost a century in
Maine and doesn't believe it has to prove anything to Mainers, he
said.
</TEXT>
