<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-13 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Prices Plunge As Soviet Union Rejects Radical Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices fell sharply Wednesday on New York's
Commodity Exchange as the Soviet Union rejected reforms that many
investors had hoped would lead to a gold-backed Soviet currency.
   Futures prices of silver and platinum also plunged, frustrating
speculators in the increasingly volatile precious-metals markets.
   On other commodity markets, heating oil for near-term delivery
rose for the 11th straight day; livestock and meat futures
advanced; and grains and soybeans were mostly higher.
   Gold futures fell $9.80 to $10.80 with the contract for delivery
in December settling $9.80 lower at $408.10 a troy ounce; silver
finished 12.8 cents to 13.8 cents lower on the Comex with December
at $5.544 a troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum futures sank
$13.70 to $14.10 with the January contract settling at $504.70 a
troy ounce.
   From mid-October through late November, gold soared from near
$360 an ounce to almost $420, partly on ideas that the economic
changes sweeping Eastern Europe would include a move by the Soviet
Union to back its currency, the ruble, with gold.
   Such a move would greatly increase the ruble's value on the
world market, where it is now almost useless, facilitating trade
with other countries.
   A gold-backed ruble apparently was not discussed by the Soviet
Parliament Wednesday, but they rejected other radical economic
reforms, disappointing gold traders who had hoped for some strong
indication of change, analysts said.
   ``There's been a lot of speculation but so far not anything
done, and I think that's kind of frustrated people,'' said Stephen
Platt, metals analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
``People were looking for something out of the Politburo.''
   Analyst James Steel of Refco Inc. in New York said the gold
selloff also appeared linked to an unconfirmed but persistent rumor
that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev had offered to resign.
   The rumor ``has shaken confidence in people who bought gold'' on
speculation of Soviet reform, he said.
   January heating oil futures surged on the New York Mercantile
Exchange following the American Petroleum Institute's report late
Tuesday of an unexpectedly large reduction in U.S. stocks of
petroleum distillates last week. Extremely cold weather in Europe
and the United States have kept demand for heating oil strong.
   Other energy futures were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent lower to 12
cents higher with January at $20.77 a barrel; heating oil was .60
cent lower to .66 cent higher with January up .66 cent at 67.96
cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .10 cent to .20 cent lower
with January at 51.93 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with most of the strength centered in the pork-belly pit,
where prices rose sharply in a technically-inspired rebound from
recent steep losses.
   Live cattle futures settled .07 cent lower to .10 cent higher
with December at 76.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent
to .20 cent higher with January at 83.42 cents a pound; live hogs
were .15 cent lower to .78 cent higher with December at 51.70 cents
a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1 cent lower to 1.53 cent higher
with February up 1.53 cents at 51.90 cents a pound.
   Most grain and soybean futures rose on the Chicago Board of
Trade in light-volume buying linked largely to weather concerns.
   Bitter cold temperatures in the nation's midsection are stirring
fears of damage to the winter wheat crop in the Great Plains and
spurring demand among cattle producers for soybean meal, a
high-energy feed additive.
   Wheat futures settled 1 cent to 1} cents higher with December at
$4.14{ a bushel; corn futures were \ cent to 2\ cents higher with
December at $2.33\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to } cent lower
with December at $1.43} a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 7
cents higher with January at $5.80{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
