<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Macy     12-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Macy,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Macy's Quarterly Loss Widens Due to Markdowns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.H. Macy &amp; Co. on Wednesday disclosed its
financial losses grew significantly in the late summer and early
autumn due to costs promotions aimed at boosting sales.
   The retailer said it lost $33.12 million, or $23.92 a share, in
its first fiscal quarter of 1990, compared with a loss of $19
million, or $15 a share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Sales rose 5.2 percent to $1.71 billion in the three months
ended Oct. 28 from $1.62 billion a year earlier.
   Macy, which went private in a leveraged buyout in 1986,
disclosed the losses in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   In a separate letter to investors, Macy Chairman Edward S.
Finkelstein described the retailing climate as ``chaotic'' and said
the first quarter results were ``somewhat disappointing although
essentially as expected.''
   In the SEC filing, Macy attributed the first-quarter loss to the
effects of ``increased markdowns taken in response to a highly
competitive retail environment.''
   ``We expect a sluggish economy this Spring but we are determined
to run a profitable business, expensed conservatively with improved
margins even with modest sales growth,'' read the letter, which was
signed by Finkelstein and Macy President Mark S. Handler.
   Macy opened two department stores during the quarter, although
it said it doesn't plan to open any others until 1991, when one new
store is planned.
   ``That temporary hiatus of new store activity has a double
benefit: we can concentrate our energies on improvement of stores
already in operation and capital expenditures will be capped at
levels significantly below plan, enhancing our cash flow,'' the
letter read.
   Macy said losses from the San Francisco earthquake, which
damaged its Macy's California and I. Magnin subsidiaries, did not
impact the latest results.
</TEXT>
