<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-IntegratedResources 1stLd-Writethru f0122 12-13
0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Integrated Resources, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0122,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1 Billion Quarterly Loss for Troubled Investment Firm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `The once... to UPDATE with
closing stock price, analyst comment; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Integrated
is...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc. on Wednesday announced
a second-quarter loss of more than $1 billion due to failing
businesses and cheap asset sales in a bid to avoid bankruptcy.
   The struggling financial services firm said the loss exceeded a
previously anticipated $600 million decline mainly because of
substantially lower-than-expected proceeds from the sale of its
core businesses.
   Integrated reported a loss of $1.04 billion, or $141.15 a share,
on revenue of $70.59 million in the April-June quarter. That
compared with earnings of $12.78 million, or 68 cents a share, in
the same period a year earlier.
   The once high-flying real estate concern stumbled trying to
expand into financial services. Integrated attributed the delay in
reporting its second-quarter results to drastic changes since it
defaulted on nearly $1 billion in debt in June.
   Integrated stock closed unchanged at 37{ cents Wednesday in New
York Stock Exchange trading. Before announcing the default,
Integrated traded at around $15 a share.
   ``Obviously what happened to them in a major way is just
shocking,'' said Tom Fendrich, a managing director for Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp. ``Everybody knew that Integrated was a deteriorating
situation, but nobody expected it to be an exploding one.''
   Integrated is seeking to restructure its debt and raise capital
to meet payments on a total of $1.75 billion in debt to and avoid
seeking bankruptcy court protection from its creditors.
   The bulk of the second-quarter losses was pinned on write-downs
in the value of businesses and assets Integrated has sold,
discontinued or plans to sell because of its financial troubles.
   A major contributor to the loss was the much-reduced sale price
for its central financial services businesses.
   Integrated in November reached agreement to sell the businesses
to Broad Inc., a Los Angeles financial services concern, for a
maximum of $225 million. It had hoped to receive $450 million.
   That deal, which is pending, is subject to price adjustments at
the time of closing that are expected to lower its value.
   ``These losses reflect the serious impact of our liquidity
problems,'' Integrated said in a statement. ``We are attempting to
address these problems by working with our creditors to restructure
the debt.''
   For the first six months of 1989, Integrated reported a loss of
$1.04 billion, or $141.93 a share, on revenue of $180.8 million,
compared with profits of $19.86 million, or 59 cents a share, on
$213.8 million in revenue a year earlier.
   The write-downs affect the financial services subsidiaries being
sold to Broad: Integrated Life Insurance Co. of Des Moines, Iowa;
Capitol Life Insurance Co. of Denver; Integrated Resources Asset
Management Corp., an investment adviser; Integrated Resources
Equity Corp., its main broker-dealer subsidiary; and Resources
Trust Co.
   Integrated said $110 million of the loss resulted from
restructuring expenses.
   The firm also cited poor industry conditions for the sale of
limited partnerships and real estate investment trusts, an absence
of revenue because of the termination or restructuring of some
investment programs and higher interest payments because of
increased borrowing.
</TEXT>
