<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1939EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BondRating     12-13 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bond Rating,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Bond Rating Falls To Lowest In Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts got the lowest state credit rating
in the nation Wednesday when Standard &amp; Poor's dropped its
long-term bond rating from A to BBB.
   That put Massachusetts a step below Louisiana, which is rated
BBB Plus, said Cathy Daicoff, S&amp;P's managing director of municipal
finance.
   Only a year ago, the state's economic boom was such that it was
dubbed the Massachusetts Miracle and nearly carried Gov. Michael
Dukakis to the White House. Now the Legislature is struggling with
tax hikes to ease an estimated $800 million budget deficit for the
current fiscal year.
   ``Massachusetts is the lowest-rated state,'' Ms. Daicoff said.
   Moody's Investors Service, the other major rating service,
dropped Massachusetts last month from A to Baa 1, tying it with
Lousiana as the lowest-rated state.
   The two services use different ratings and different symbols, so
they are not directly comparable, Ms. Daicoff said.
   State Treasurer Robert Q. Crane said he wasn't surprised by
S&amp;P's action.
   ``You can't argue with the fact there is a serious shortfall,''
he said.
   ``The only way it can be addressed is by some very important and
difficult cuts in our way of life, plus an input of fresh new
revenue streams, whether they be sales tax, sin tax or income tax
increases,'' Crane said.
   Dukakis' chief financial adviser, Admininstration and Finance
Secretary L. Edward Lashman, said the bonds still carry an
investment-grade rating, allowing them to be purchased by major
pension funds and other institutional investors.
   Asked if there was a danger of Massachusetts' rating falling
into the junk-bond category, Lashman said, ``If we don't get a tax
package very soon, we are in serious danger of it.''
   Ms. Daicoff said credit rating wouldn't be upgraded immediately
even if the state were to erase the budget deficit of about $800
million for the current fiscal year.
   ``For a higher rating to be assigned, we would have to see a
sharp reversal of the financial trends of the last 18 months,'' she
said. ``We would also have to be assured that any future fiscal
problems are addressed in a prudent fashion.
   ``S&amp;P expects the state to remain under fiscal stress for some
period of time,'' she said.
   Crane said he hoped the rating would improve before February,
the next time the state plans to go to market with long-term debt,
but Lashman agreed an upgrading would take a long time.
   ``The last time this happened, it took us 13 years to get back
to a top rating,'' Lashman said.
   S&amp;P said the downgrading affects $4.6 billion in outstanding
direct general obligation state bonds.
   The ratings service also lowered from A to BBB the ratings on
$2.5 billion in agency debt secured by state guarantees. That debt
includes bonds issued by state authorities when the borrowing is
not backed up by a stream of dedicated revenue, such as tolls or
fees.
   S&amp;P also lowered the rating on $747 million in direct general
obligation short-term notes from ``SP-1'' to ``SP-2.''
   However, Ms. Daicoff said the state's planned sale of $1.2
billion in short-term commercial paper will carry the highest
A-1-Plus rating because it is backed by a letter of credit from
three Japanese banks.
   That sale includes $700 million in new borrowing and a $500
million rollover of existing short-term debt. The borrowing is
required for the state to make a $1.1 billion aid payment to cities
and towns at the end of the month.
   ``The rating is based on the banks' creditworthyness, not the
commonwealth's,'' Ms. Daicoff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
