<FIRST>u f AM-Allied-FederatedFinances     12-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allied-Federated Finances,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federated and Allied Department Stores Threaten Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated and Allied department stores, owned
by the deeply indebted Campeau Corp., may file for bankruptcy as
early as January if lenders don't agree to restructure their $7
billion debt, according to a published report.
   The Cincinnati-based retailers said in a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing released Wednesday that they would run out of
cash by mid-March and possibly as early as January unless creditors
ease repayment schedules.
   ``What happens depends largely upon the cooperation that is
required from our bondholders and other lenders. So we will pursue
that cooperation aggressively,'' Campeau spokeswoman Carol Sanger
told The Cincinnati Enquirer for an article to be published in
Thursday's editions.
   According to the newspaper, the SEC filing said any hesitation
by lenders could force the company to seek federal bankruptcy
protection under Chapter 11. The document said the stores expect to
begin discussions with lenders soon, but had no assurance they
would reach agreement.
   ``Hopefully we'll be able to manage our way through this period
and conduct the restructuring process on a voluntary basis without
going the bankruptcy route,'' Ms. Sanger said.
   Campeau stock tumbled 1 to close at 4, a drop of 20 percent in
over-the-counter trading Wednesday largely on market rumors of a
possible bankruptcy filing, analysts said.
   The firms cited problems in their SEC filing that could
jeopardize their survival:
   _Performance in the fourth quarter _ the period including the
Christmas shopping season when the companies make more than half
their profits _ has fallen below a forecast that ``left little or
no margin for error.''
   _Federated could already be in default on some of the financial
performance clauses in loan agreements, and Allied will likely
breach them soon.
   _Federated must pay off $27.6 million of bonds on Jan. 27, and
another $72.0 million on Feb.1.
   ``The burdensome debt load is something that is becoming
increasingly difficult to manage,'' Ms. Sanger said. ``It requires
a tremendous amount of cash infusions.''
   Federated Department Stores and Allied Stores took on immense
debt, much of it in high interest ``junk bonds,'' as part of their
takeover by Canadian real estate magnate Robert Campeau. Campeau
bought Federated in May 1988 and Allied in December 1986.
   Their difficulty in meeting the massive interest payments
prompted an earlier financial restructuring and the ouster of
Campeau as chairman when Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. of Canada
bailed out Campeau Corp. in September.
   Toronto-based Campeau put Bloomingdale's, the crown jewel of its
retailing empire, up for sale in September after the beleagured
company said it was being forced to restructure under the weight of
$8 billion in debt from its acquisition of Federated and Allied.
   Federated is negotiating with six bidders to sell the
Bloomingdale's chain in February, in order to repay a $1.05 billion
short-term loan by April 30.
   But there is no assurance that sale will yield enough to pay the
company's debts, the document said.
   Among Federated's holdings is Lazarus department stores, a
43-store chain based in Cincinnati.
   Jerry Gafford, vice president of corporate affairs at Lazarus,
downplayed Wednesday's news.
   ``We're not worried about the possibility of being sold,'' he
said. ``This is something that needs to be done by the Campeau
organization. We're viewing it as business as usual.''
   There also is no reason to believe manufacturers will cease
merchandise shipments to the retailer, Gafford added.
   Ms. Sanger said Federated and Allied wouldn't close if they seek
federal bankruptcy protection. Chapter 11 allows companies to
remain in business while developing a plan to repay their debts.
   Wednesday's filing follows disclosure Tuesday of worsening
losses at Federated and Allied for the third quarter, despite
increases in sales.
   Besides Lazarus and Bloomingdale's, Federated operates
Manhattan's Abraham &amp; Straus, Burdines in Miami, and Rich's and the
Goldsmith stores in Atlanta.
   Allied Stores' operations include Boston-based Jordan Marsh,
Maas Brothers-Jordan Marsh in Florida, Bon Marche in Seattle and
Stern's in New Jersey.
</TEXT>
