<FIRST>r f AM-Turner-MGM-UA     12-13 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turner-MGM-UA,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ted Turner Back in Talks With MGM-UA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable TV magnate Ted Turner is back
in the hunt for MGM-UA Communications Co., trying to negotiate a
non-cash deal for Turner Broadcasting to acquire MGM-UA, people
close to the talks said Wednesday.
   The entrepreneur needs films to feed Turner Network Television,
his year-old cable network. MGM-UA, controlled by Beverly Hills
billionaire Kirk Kerkorian, has just that: a 1,000-picture library
of United Artists movies that include the James Bond, Rocky and
Pink Panther series.
   Turner already owns rights to the even larger library of MGM
films, which he purchased from Kerkorian in 1986. If he acquired
the United Artists films and some new MGM movies from Kerkorian, he
would control rights to about 4,000 pictures.
   A parade of famous companies and individuals have considered
buying MGM-UA since Kerkorian put the studio up for sale a year and
a half ago. Bidders such as Turner and media mogul Rupert Murdoch
have been seeking programming for ventures both here and abroad.
   Murdoch, for example, has started the Fox TV network here and
extensive satellite TV ventures in Britain and in continental
Europe. He offered $1.4 billion for MGM, but was outbid in
September by Australia's Qintex group, which later was unable to
get financing for its $1.5 billion offer.
   Those offers were for cash, but Turner is instead trying to
negotiate a deal to swap stock in their companies with Kerkorian,
according to reports in the Los Angeles Times and Wall Street
Journal that were confirmed Wednesday by a studio executive.
   Extended by his many ventures, Turner ``is not sitting on a pile
of cash,'' said the executive, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The reports on the stock swap talks are the latest in a series
of stories on Kerkorian's negotiations with buyers including Turner
and two companies that own a stake in Turner Broadcasting:
Denver-based cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. and Time Warner
Inc. in New York.
   Among others recently interested in MGM-UA was a foreign venture
jointly controlled by MCA Inc. and Paramount Communications.
   But MCA President Sid Sheinberg said Wednesday those
negotiations had been only ``loose proposals,'' adding, ``We're
certainly not in the running for it now.''
   Neither Turner Broadcasting nor MGM-UA would comment officially
on the talks Wednesday, and Kerkorian's personal spokesman, Jim
Mahoney, said he had no knowledge of where negotiations stand.
   ``(Kerkorian) wants to make a deal,'' Mahoney said. ``The
company is in play. But if he can't make a deal, he can live with
that too. People forget that outside of (MCA chairman) Lew
Wasserman, Kirk has run a studio longer than anyone in Hollywood,
and he's been successful at it.
   Mahoney added, ``He's willing to start back into production'' of
films if no deal can be made.
   Filmmaking has virtually halted at the studio since Kerkorian
put the company up for sale in April 1988.
   Entertainment analyst Jeffrey Logsdon of the Crowell Weedon
brokerage in Los Angeles estimated it would take at least $250
million a year for two years to get the studio back into full
production, but Mahoney said that figure was far too high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
