<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-Bonuses     12-13 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Bonuses,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing To Pay $500 Million In Bonuses To Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. will pay $500 million in bonuses
this month to its employees worldwide, including non-union workers,
the company said Wednesday.
   Of that amount, $374 million will go to nearly 107,000 employees
in Washington state, including more than 35,000 non-union workers
in the Seattle area.
   Both union and non-union workers will receive bonuses of 10
percent, the company said.
   Boeing, the Northwest's largest private employer, said earlier
it would give office workers, administrators and supervisors
bonuses, but did not give a percentage until Wednesday.
   Office workers have received bonuses annually, but professionals
and administrators last got bonuses three years ago, said Paul
Binder, company spokesman.
   The 43,000 members of the International Association of
Machinists &amp; Aerospace Workers in the state got 10 percent bonuses
last Friday, averaging more than $3,000 each.
   Under their contract ratified Nov. 20 after a 48-day strike,
they will get bonuses of 5 percent next year and 4 percent in 1991.
   If about 28,000 members of the Seattle Professional Engineering
Employees Association approve a contract offer, they will receive
10 percent bonuses Dec. 22. The engineers and technical workers
have until Dec. 18 to vote on the tentative contract.
   The proposed offer calls for engineers to get a bonus this year
only, but technical workers would get a 5 percent bonus next year
and 4 percent the following year.
   Engineers would get an average bonus of nearly $4,000 while
technical workers would receive nearly $3,000.
   The 1989 bonuses will also be distributed in four other areas
with major Boeing operations: Wichita, Kan., $72 million;
Philadelphia, $18.5 million; Portland, Ore., $7 million; and
Huntsville, Ala., $7 million.
</TEXT>
