<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 2347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Democrats-Japan 2ndLd-Writethru f0309 12-13 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Japan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0309,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Want Probe Into Economic Advisers' Foreign Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf: ```Gephardt could,'' to note Gephardt in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt and
other members of the Democratic leadership complained Wednesday
that President Bush is relying for economic counsel from aides who
have also served as advisers for Japan.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater dismissed the complaint
as ``a political cheap shot.''
   President Bush himself, in a brief exchange with reporters as he
left the Oval Office early in the evening, said, ``Mr. Gephardt's
complaining. So what's new?''
   Gephardt and 11 other House Democrats sent a letter to White
House counsel and ethics watchdog Boyden Gray saying they were
``deeply troubled by reports that senior officials in the
administration may be serving in the dual capacity of advising the
U.S. government while simultaneously providing counsel, advice or
other services to foreign governments ... corporations or other
foreign entities.''
   They said the chief Japan expert for the President's Council of
Economic Advisers, University of Michigan Professor Gary R.
Saxonhouse, is an adviser to Japanese financial groups, including a
research institute financed by Japan's Ministry of International
Trade and Industry.
   They also noted that Michael Boskin, chairman of the president's
council and Bush's chief economic adviser, served on the board of a
similar institute supported by the Japanese Finance Ministry before
he took his current post.
   ``This raises serious questions about conflicts of interest,''
said the Dec. 12-dated letter. The Democrats asked Gray to identify
other administration officials who ``serve in a dual capacity''
with any foreign entity.
   Fitzwater said Boskin had quit the Japanese advisory panel in
December 1988, a month before the start of the Bush administration.
Boskin was then a Stanford University economics professor; he had
been a top adviser toBush during the 1988 campaign.
   Saxonhouse is an unpaid adviser on a Japanese ministry board
that has not met in two years, said Fitzwater. He said Saxonhouse
works only part time for the White House, and ``there's no conflict
of interest.''
   Saxonhouse is not subject to ethics rules that cover the White
House staff.
   ``Gephardt's a Japan-basher, that's all,'' said Fitzwater.
   Gephardt could not be immediately reached for comment. He is in
Europe, his staff said.
   Gephardt sought the Democratic presidential nomination in 1988
on a platform of tough trade laws to restrict imports from
countries with big trade imbalances with the United States, such as
Japan.
   The Democrats' complaint was sparked by an article in Sunday's
New York Times on Japan's lobbying efforts in Washington and its
ties to American academics.
   Also signing the letter were Democrats William Gray of
Pennsylvania, the House majority whip; David Bonior of Michigan,
the chief deputy whip; Steny Hoyer of Maryland, chairman of the
House Democratic Caucus; Vic Fazio of California, vice chairman of
the caucus; Dan Glickman of Kansas; Howard Wolpe of Michigan;
Dennis Eckart and Marcy Kaptur of Ohio; Robert Torricelli of New
Jersey; Bob Wise of West Virginia; and David Nagle of Iowa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
